<FIRST>u w AM-D'AmatoCase     11-27 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-D'Amato Case,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Committee Switches Counsel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Ethics Committee said Monday it has
changed its outside counsel in a case involving Sen. Alfonse
D'Amato, R-N.Y.
   The committee hired former federal prosecutor Henry Schuelke, a
Washington attorney, to replace Robert Bennett, who is still
handling two other cases for the committee.
   The committee announcement said Bennett, also of Washington,
advised the panel last week that his law firm's diverse practice
could lead to an appearance of conflict of interest in the D'Amato
case. Details of how such an appearance could arise were not given.
   Mark Green, D'Amato's election opponent in 1986, has filed a
complaint with the committee accusing him of breaking Senate rules
in the HUD scandal and other matters. D'Amato has denied any
improprieties.
   Schuelke will take over Bennett's role of helping the committee
determine whether to proceed with a formal investigation, a review
that is expected to take several months.
   Bennett is still the committee's outside counsel in conducting a
similar review in a case involving five senators who interceded
with banking regulators on behalf of a contributor whose savings
and loan was collapsing.
   Bennett also is the committee's counsel in an investigation of a
book deal by Sen. David Durenberger, R-Minn.
</TEXT>
