<FIRST>u i AM-Uruguay 2ndLd-Writethru   11-27 0845</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Uruguay, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0780,0868</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governing Party's Presidential Candidate Concedes Defeat</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with early official results showing
Lacalle leading. Lacalle comment. Pickup 4th graf `Equipos Consultores...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MVD1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTEVIDEO, Uruguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An opposition presidential candidate
led in early returns Monday after the governing party's hopeful
conceded defeat.
   Jorge Batlle, candidate of the governing Colorado Party, said
Sunday night before official returns were released that he had lost
the race to Luis Lacalle of the National Party.
   Both parties are center-right and both candidates have promised
to trim down an atrophied welfare state in this small South
American country of 2.9 million people.
   ``According to the information available, the future president
will be Sen. Lacalle, to whom I extend my most sincere
congratulations and best wishes for success in his term,'' said
Batlle, whose name is pronounced BAHT-lee.
   Lacalle said he would issue a public statement on Monday, but
acknowledged that he had received congratulatory calls from
President Julio M. Sanguinetti and Liber Seregni, presidential
candidate for the leftist Broad Front.
   The Interior Ministry, issuing the first official returns
shortly after midnight that results from 152 of the 8,493 voting
stations gave 10,170 votes or 39 percent to the National Party,
8,040 votes or 30 percent to the Colorado Party and 3,547 votes or
13 percent to the Broad Front, a coalition of leftist parties.
   Equipos Consultores, a respected independent polling agency,
projected the National Party received 38 percent of the total vote,
compared to 31 percent for the Colorados. Equipos did not state how
many votes its projection was based on.
   The leftist coalition Broad Front tallied 22 percent of the vote
nationwide, according to Equipos, and the front's cndidate for
mayor of the capital Montevideo, Marxist doctor Tabare Vazquez, won
that coveted post.
   Batlle acknowledged that the ``trend indicates a majority for
the Broad Front'' in Montevideo. ``That trend is irreversible,'' he
said. ``The next mayor of Montevideo will be Tabare Vazquez.''
   At stake were the presidency, the vice presidency, the posts of
30 senators and 99 deputies, and governments in 19 provinces.
   A win for the National Party would be the first time it took
power since 1967 and only the third time this century.
   Uruguayans voting to replace Sanguinetti and both houses of
congress said their main concern was invigorating an economy that
has been in decline for three decades.
   ``Things aren't going to change if politics don't take a turn
and politicians look for something different,'' said Luis Suarez, a
63-year-old retiree.
   ``When we look at the outside world, there have been tremendous
advances,'' said Marcos Larghero, 47, a graphic designer. ``The
opposite has occurred here. We deteriorate a little bit each year.''
   Election officials anticipated a turnout of 90 percent or better
of the 2.32 million Uruguayans eligible to vote. Radio stations
reported that 21 percent had voted by 11 a.m.
   In the last elections in 1984, the main issue was who could best
lead Uruguay back to democracy after a 12-year military regime that
trampled human rights, stifled political opposition and ran the
economy to the ground.
   Batlle's great-uncle, Jose Batlle y Ordonez, forged modern
Uruguay during his presidencies in 1903-07 and 1911-15. Using huge
surpluses from beef and grain exports, Batlle y Ordonez established
the 8-hour work day, a minimum wage, retirement pensions and paid
vacations.
   Batlle's father, Luis Batlle Berres, used reserves built up
during World War II to promote local industry by blocking imports
during his 1947-51 presidency. He also expanded social programs.
   Today, public education through college is free. The state
provides mortgages and insurance as well as pensions, runs the
banking system and employs 270,000 Uruguayans, or about one-quarter
of the work force.
   However, salaries are so low that teachers, bus drivers and
others frequently go on strike, retirees can hardly live on their
pensions, and the quality of public services has declined. Teachers
earn about 84,000 pesos ($110) a month.
   The gross national product, now $8 billion, and real wages
recovered modestly under Sanguinetti. But inflation, now at 82.5
percent, did not. Unemployment, at 14 percent in 1985, is down to 9
percent.
   Lacalle and Batlle pledged to reduce inflation, balance the
national budget, sell gold reserves and pay off some of Uruguay's
$6.3 billion foreign debt, and sell inefficient public companies.
They also pledged to open the economy, encourage competition
through deregulation, and restrict the right of organized labor to
strike.
   Lacalle took the lead in public opinion surveys, analysts said,
partly because he convinced voters he would seek solutions
gradually on the basis of negotiation, not right away or by force.
   Uruguay's aging, politically conservative population includes
650,000 retirees. A majority of voters are 40 years old or more.
   Lacalle, a 48-year-old attorney and senator and a member of a
prominent political family, pledged to form a coalition government
and said he would offer Cabinet posts to leaders of other parties.
   The new president takes office March 1, 1990, and congress and
the departmental governments begin Feb. 15.
</TEXT>
