<FIRST>r a PM-CaffeLena     11-27 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Caffe Lena,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>Folk Music Stars Perform at Memorial for Coffeehouse Founder</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GERMAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some top performers of the folk
music boom returned to the Caffe Lena to play a few tunes in memory
of the owner of the coffeehouse that helped launch their careers.
   The memorial Sunday included performances by Loudon Wainwright
III, Rosalie Sorrells, David Bromberg and Dave Van Ronk.
   The music was filmed for a documentary about the folk music
shrine and its founder, Lena Spencer, who died Oct. 23 at age 66
from injuries sustained in a fall.
   The one-hour documentary for the BBC and PBS will memorialize a
``driving force in folk music,'' said director Stephen Trombley,
who grew up in nearby Ballston Spa and now lives in London.
   The upstate New York coffeehouse helped launch Bob Dylan's
career and featured Arlo Guthrie, Don McLean and Pete Seeger.
   Among the performers Sunday was Jack Landron, the first musician
to play at Caffe Lena when it opened in 1960. Landron dedicated a
song called ``A Little Traveling Music'' to Spencer because, he
said, ``some of us think of death as a journey.''
   Such a lasting folk club ``had to happen somewhere and couldn't
have happened just anywhere,'' Trombley said. ``A lot of places
wouldn't have accepted Lena. ... Saratoga Springs is a wacky town
and one of the few places it could have happened.''
   Christine Lavin, who worked as a waitress at Caffe Lena in the
mid-1970s, said Spencer's encouragement made her stick with her
music career. Spencer occasionally thrust Lavin on stage to build
her confidence, she said.
   ``Lena thought I had talent and wanted to give me a chance,''
said Lavin, whose performance at the memorial included a
baton-twirling drill.
   ``When I twirled here Lena was a nervous wreck because she
didn't have a lot of extra microphones,'' Lavin said. ``But I
convinced her I had enough control'' not to smash the mikes.
   Blues artist Rory Block said she was thankful Spencer never let
business interfere with who she booked at the club. Spencer let
Block play in the early 1980s, when she wasn't a big enough draw to
fill the tiny coffeehouse, she said.
   ``I never had a financial arrangement with Lena,'' said Block,
who now has five albums behind her. ``At the end of the night,
whatever she paid me, she paid me. And she paid performers every
penny she could afford and probably a little more.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891127-0024 </DOCNO>
