<FIRST>r w PM-Education-ChapterOne 2ndLd-Writethru a0449 11-27 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Education-Chapter One, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0449,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0454 to fix editor's note.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Chapter One Program Helps Some Kids; Others Left Out</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Deletes outdated 2nd sentence of 9th graf.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HYATTSVILLE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delonte Washington plopped on his
headphones, deftly fingered the computer keyboard and gleefully
watched as the screen exploded into brightly colored pictures and
the machine ``talked'' about the day's reading lesson.
   For third-grader Washington and many other students, the time
spent in the computer laboratory is a favorite part of the school
day. Yet regulations for the federal Chapter One program bar some
of his schoolmates from using the same lab because their families
aren't poor enough or there's not enough federal money to serve all
the eligible children.
   Barring such use of computer equipment is ``a waste of material
and community resources and it doesn't help education in general,''
said Warren Simmons, director of instructional support programs for
Prince George's County, Md.
   ``The money could be stretched farther if you had the
opportunity to say, `well, if these computers are not being used
for a certain part of the day, then other at-risk kids can use
them,''' he said.
   The frustration felt by Simmons and other educators made the
Chapter One program a prime topic of discussion at this fall's
national education summit.
   ``Several states report that large numbers of computers
purchased by federal funds are idle at nigh, while adult education
classes that need them either do without or use scarce tax dollars
to buy other equipment,'' said a statement signed by President Bush
and representatives of the governors who attended the two-day event.
   The federal government spends about $4 billion a year on Chapter
One, a program that provides remedial classes, teachers and
equipment to help bring educationally disadvantaged children up to
par.
   ``Clearly by every account Chapter One is one of the most
effective federal programs,'' said Michael Edwards, manager of
congressional relations for the National Education Association.
   But according to the NEA, the number of students served in
Chapter One fell from 7 million in 1980-81 to 5.7 million in
1988-89, while the number of children needing the extra help
increased to 8.5 million.
   In Prince George's County, Chapter One provides an $8 million
budget for about 8,100 eligible low-income students. The county has
104,000 students.
   Washington and about 246 other students at Langley
Park-McCormick Elementary School are Chapter One students. They
scored poorly on academic tests and were identified as needing
educational services to raise their achievement level.
   ``I'm glad to get the special attention,'' he says.
   ``The computer lab is one of the favorites,'' said Jeri Taylor,
who oversees the school's program. ``The students always want to
know, `Is today the day we go to the lab?'''
   Like most Chapter One schools, Langley Park-McCormick strictly
follows the rules to identify students and to allow only designated
children to use its equipment and remedial education material.
   That means that computers, other educational materials and even
teachers and assistants can be used only by designated students,
and sometimes are idle.
   Langley Park-McCormick has been able to leap over some of the
regulation hurdles.
   ``In a school as large as Langley Park-McCormick'' with a total
student body of 681, ``we have such a large population of Chapter
One kids, that we are not as affected as other schools,'' said Ms.
Taylor.
   Langley Park is one of only two elementary schools in the county
to be equipped with a state-of-the-art IBM computer laboratory _ 20
terminals _ for Chapter One children.
   Last year, Langley Park-McCormick won special permission to use
the computer lab, which was made for the county and is connected
into one main computer, for an evening class of English as a second
language. Six hundred adults enrolled.
</TEXT>
