<FIRST>u i PM-Prague-Rally     11-27 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prague-Rally,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>Long-Silenced Opposition Finds Voice At Joyous Rally</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ONDREJ HEJMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hours after Communist authorities
released him from jail, Jiri Ruml found himself on a frigid,
wind-swept podium, speaking to 300,000 Czechoslovaks who share his
desire for democratic reform.
   ``I had dinner in Ruzyne last night,'' the underground publisher
told the rally, referring to the Prague jail where he was
imprisoned until his Saturday night.
   ``It wasn't the hotel,'' he added, noting a nearby hotel of the
same name.
   A chant rose from thousands at the joyous rally: ``What did you
have?''
   Ruml smiled. ``Mine was good. Since I'm on a diet, it was cherry
cake and coffee,'' he said as laughter swelled from the throng.
   ``Let them (Communist leaders) eat that cake,'' the crowd
chanted.
   ``Cherry cake at the castle, put Stepan on a diet,'' the
demonstrators roared in an acerbic reference to the overweight
Miroslav Stepan, a Communist hard-liner who resigned as Prague's
party boss Saturday and was dumped from the ruling Politburo today.
   Ruml joined other singers and speakers from the Czechoslovak
underground _ many banned from performances for two decades _ who
found their public voices again Sunday at the festive rally.
   They were recognized by the masses, who remembered their works
and recited their lyrics despite all official efforts at enforced
forgetting.
   Alexander Dubcek, the leader of the failed Prague Spring refoms
of 1968, received jubilant applause throughout his speech although
many listeners admitted being baffled by his thick Slovak accent
and his use of language heavily laden with Communist jargon.
   The crowd roared in approval as he called on the Soviet Union,
East Germany and Bulgaria to join Poland and Hungary in apologizing
for participating in the Warsaw Pact invasion that crushed his
reforms movement.
   ``Our people want the truth without delay, and that should be
one of the first steps of the (new) Central Committee,'' he added
to thunderous applause.
   Playwright Vaclav Havel, whose works are banned from his country
and who has spent more than three years in prison since 1979 for
his opposition to Communist rule, also was cheered.
   A moment of silence settled over the elated throng when the Rev.
Vaclav Maly asked for a moment of silence for Pavel Wonka, a
dissident who died in jail in 1988.
   As Premier Ladislav Adamec appeared before the crowd, they
chanted ``Adamec! Adamec!''
   Adamec, introduced as a ``guest,'' was invited to address the
the huge rally after an unprecedented dialogue with opposition
leaders earlier in the day.
   His presence at the rally was a dramatic departure for the
normally reclusive leadership, accustomed over decades to simply
issuing orders by decree and to addressing crowds carefully
choreographed to deliver shows of support.
   ``As I said on television last night, I will gladly explain my
opinions and listen to anyone who wants to find a common
language,'' Adamec said.
   ``Thank you, Thank you,'' the crowd roared in response.
   But the crowd's goodwill quickly turned sour when Adamec urged
the people to shorten a general strike set for today from two hours
to two minutes.
   The plea, viewed as an attempt to render the strike meaningless,
drew loud boos and whistles from the crowd.
</TEXT>
