<FILEID>AP-NR-11-27-89 0407EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DrugTax Bjt   11-27 0729</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drug Tax, Bjt,0747</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kansas Drug Tax More Prosecutor's Tool Than Revenue Raiser</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HANNA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drug dealers owe the state $33.3 million in
unpaid taxes and penalties on their pot, cocaine and other illegal
uppers and downers, and the Revenue Department has collected only
$23,392.96.
   But officials say the tax on illegal drug sales does more than
bring in revenue. It gives prosecutors an easy-to-prove charge that
can mean a longer prison sentence or a better bargaining position
when defendants want to plea bargain.
   Revenue chief Ed Rolfs, whose office made the estimate of how
much is owed, said his agency became more active in trying to
collect taxes on illegal drugs earlier this year, after the 1987
law survived a legal challenge. He said it may collect $500,000
next year.
   ``The prosecutors are using it,'' said David Johnson, director
of the Kansas Bureau of Investigation. ``Prosecutors, I think, take
it very seriously, and I know law enforcement takes it very
seriously.''
   At least 18 other states have taxes of some kind on illegal
drugs, according to the Council of State Governments in Lexington,
Ky.
   And as of October, West Virginia, Connecticut, Massachussetts
and Michigan were considering similar measures, according to the
council.
   Under the Kansas law, dealers are taxed $100 on each ounce of
marijuana, $200 on each gram of cocaine or controlled substance
sold by weight and $2,000 for 50 doses of drugs sold by dose,
usually prescription drugs obtained illegally.
   The law provides that a dealer who pays the tax will get a tax
stamp to put on his bags, bottles and vials. The stamps are plain
2-inch-square stickers, green for marijuana, blue for controlled
substances sold by weight and red for controlled substances sold by
dose.
   So far, only eight people have bought a total of 377 stamps
worth a total of $4,155.50, and most of the buyers are probably
stamp collectors, officials said.
   The state assesses people for taxes when it is notified of drug
busts. It has made 291 such assessments since the law went into
effect, and collected $19,237.46 in back taxes and penalties.
   The 1987 law prohibits the disclosure of the names of people who
buy the stamps _ a provision designed to protect a person's right
against self-incrimination. Dealers are liable for the tax and an
equal amount in penalties, and can be sentenced up to five years in
prison and fined another $10,000.
   ``The idea is to try to make it more costly to be in that
business,'' said Rolfs, who co-sponsored the Kansas legislation.
   Rolfs said the amount collected is small because local and
federal law enforcement agencies already have the right to seize
property used in dealing drugs. Nola Foulston, a prosecutor in
Wichita, said some people caught dealing drugs don't have much to
seize.
   ``It's like squeezing blood out of a turnip sometimes,'' she
said.
   Supporters of the law like to say that gangster Al Capone went
to prison for tax evasion, not racketeering or murder. But some
prosecutors only infrequently use the drug tax law in their cases.
   Ms. Foulston said her office had filed tax charges in about 20
of the 600 drug cases it has handled this year. Her office has
three lawyers working on drug cases, she said, and they don't have
time to document and file tax charges each time someone is arrested.
   District Attorney Nick Tomasic, in Kansas City, said he doesn't
use the law because most of the people he prosecutes in drug cases
are small-time criminals.
   ``It's not like they've got a big house we can seize, or a big
car we can seize,'' he said. ``They end up with a court-appointed
attorney.''
   Last year, defendants in Topeka and neighboring Osage County
challenged the law, saying that paying taxes for drugs would be
tantamount to violating their right against self-incrimination,
guaranteed by the Fifth Amendment. Two state district court judges
agreed.
   The state Supreme Court upheld the law as constitutional in
March. The justices unanimously ruled that the law contained
sufficient protections and labeled the defendants' fears ``merely
trifling or imaginary hazards.''
   According to the Council of State Governments, the other states
with such taxes are Alabama, Arizona, Colorado, Florida, Idaho,
Illinois, Maine, Maryland, Minnesota, Montana, Nevada, New Mexico,
North Carolina, North Dakota, Rhode Island, Texas, Utah and Wyoming.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891127-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-27-89 0424EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p PM-FloridaPolitics     11-27 0728</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Florida Politics,0751</SECOND>
<HEAD>GOP Tide Still Rolling in Florida</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOUNT DORA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Jeffrey S. Book, long-time
Democratic Party activist and Michael Dukakis delegate at the 1988
national convention, has joined the Republican tide rolling across
the state.
   ``I have to focus on what's real,'' Book said. ``I've gotten
older and more conservative. I was a Democrat because I perceived
that party to be the most effective party for what I wanted to
accomplish.
   ``I am now a Republican for the same reason,'' said Book, a
Harvard-educated politician who last month at age 30 was re-elected
to his second two-year term without opposition.
   His central Florida city has only about 7,000 residents,. But
Book's switch last month was big news among politicians statewide
because of his activity on a number of local, state and national
Democratic groups.
   Such switches provide a big boost to the GOP's goal of making
Florida its first majority state in the South since Reconstruction,
said state party Chairman Van Poole.
   ``Any time we get an elected official to switch, he usually has
a following that stops and thinks,'' Poole said.
   Democrats are hoping to reverse that trend when they meet at a
party convention this weekend in Hollywood.
   The 1980s have been filled with victories for Republicans in
Florida. In 1980, there were 3,087,427 registered Democrats and
1,429,645 Republicans. As of two weeks ago, there were 3,063,673
Democrats and 2,298,005 Republicans.
   ``We're getting four out of every five new people who
register,'' said GOP state spokesman Stan Smith.
   The 1988 elections were a new high-water mark. George Bush
enjoyed his widest margin in Florida, Republican Connie Mack picked
up a U.S. Senate seat, two Republicans were elected to the state
Cabinet for the first time, and the party gained three U.S. House
seats.
   Since then, U.S. Rep. Bill Grant switched parties, giving the
GOP a majority for the first time in Florida's congressional
delegation. At least 40 state officeholders have changed parties.
   After Democratic Rep. Claude Pepper's death at age 88,
Republican Ileana Ros-Lehtinen won a special election in August for
the seat Pepper held for the Democrats since 1962.
   ``We continue to climb, and they're in an airplane in a tailspin
they can't pull out of,'' Poole said.
   Next year's Florida elections will have far-reaching effects.
Gov. Bob Martinez, struggling in the polls, will try to become the
first two-term Republican governor in recent Florida history, while
the party tries to cinch another post-Reconstruction first for the
South: control of the Florida state Senate. The Republicans can do
it if they win four new seats.
   The Legislature will draw new boundaries after the 1990
elections. Florida, one of the nation's fastest-growing states,
will gain at least three congressional seats and possibly four
after the 1990 census.
   Poole's opposite number, Cuban-born attorney Simon Ferro of
Coral Gables, said the Democrats can reverse the trend quickly by
defeating Martinez next year.
   ``We foresee there will be a halt and then a swing back in 1990
and 1991,'' Ferro said. ``The governorship constitutes a very
substantial advantage to a party when it comes to maintaining the
focus of the people on party politics.''
   The Democrats opposing Martinez include U.S. Rep. Bill Nelson,
state Sen. George Stuart and Alcee L. Hastings, the recently
impeached federal judge.
   Democratic leaders are trying to head off a divisive primary by
rallying early behind Nelson, a one-time Space Shuttle passenger
they see as having the diverse appeal needed in Florida.
   Nelson has concentrated early on conservative Southern Democrats
who have been voting Republican in statewide elections. The
Democrats say they can win them back; Republicans say the
Democratic registration majority exists on paper only.
   Divisiveness has hurt the Democrats, however. Ferro himself won
the party chairmanship in a tense backroom battle with former U.S.
Rep. Kenneth MacKay, who narrowly lost the 1988 Senate race to Mack.
   Book said Ferro's defeat of MacKay was the final straw in his
decision to switch parties. MacKay, a fiscal conservative with a
pristine record on ethics, was clearly the best choice to get the
party turned around, Book said.
   MacKay, now the state campaign chairman, said Democrats still
represent the true beliefs of most Floridians.
   ``A lot of it is not ideology. They've been turning away because
they think we've lost our vitality,'' MacKay said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891127-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-27-89 0422EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     11-27 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Hit New Record High in Tokyo, Dollar Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index rose to its
fourth consecutive record high closing today, while the dollar
declined against the Japanese yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 397.06 points, or 1.09
percent, closing at 36,881.53. The previous record was 36,484.47,
set Friday, when the index climbed 197.55 points.
   Dealers attributed the continued rise to stabilized external
factors such as foreign exchange rates and prospects for lower U.S.
interest rates.
   The U.S. Federal Reserve Board recently lowered the nation's
federal funds rate, a short-term lending rate between commercial
banks.
   ``Normally, trading on the last day of the month is inactive,
but today it was different,'' said Yutaka Yoshino, a trader with
Nikko Securities Co.
   He said today's trading was very active as investors expected
further rises in the index for their December transactions, which
start Tuesday.
   Investors bought a wide variety of issues including steel,
shipbuilding and trading house shares, Yoshino said.
   ``Recent democratization in Eastern Europe also encouraged
buying because many investors think such changes in the Eastern
bloc will provide them more business opportunities,'' he said.
   An estimated 1 billion shares changed hands on the first section
Monday, up from Friday's 900 million.
   In currency dealings, the dollar closed at 143.35 yen, down 0.45
yen from last Friday's 143.80-yen finish. It opened at 143.18 yen
and ranged between 143.05 yen and 143.38 yen.
   Dollar-yen dealing was inactive in Tokyo, as trading was
dominated by buying of the West German mark, said Minori Takeuchi,
a Chemical Bank trader.
   The dollar opened lower in Tokyo following a similar downswing
overseas as market players sold dollars to buy the West German
currency.
   West Germany is expected to become a major beneficiary of the
recent moves toward democracy and economic reform in Eastern Europe.
   Shortly before the market closed, the Japan Broadcasting Corp.
reported that the United States may announce plans for a troop
reduction in Europe, but Ms. Takeuchi said it would have little
impact on the market.
   In the past, market players have bought dollars on rumors of
U.S. arms reductions.
   ``If you only look at the defense budget, the arms reduction (in
Europe) may improve the U.S. deficit,'' Ms. Takeuchi said. ``But
what are military personnel going to do after they return to
America? That may increase the unemployment rate in the United
States, and that does not necessarily improve the situation.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
