<FILEID>AP-NR-11-27-89 0446EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-GrainMan     11-27 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Grain Man,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain Dealer to Close Elevator After 52 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANKAKEE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Clyde Rabideau saw horse-drawn wagons
deliver grain to his downtown elevator, never required his
customers to sign contracts, and occasionally loaned them money.
   After 52 years in the grain business, Rabideau has decided to
retire and close his elevator.
   ``I'm 78. It's time to go,'' said Rabideau, who knows it won't
be easy to leave. ``It's rough.''
   He glanced anxiously at his watch, reached for his old portable
radio, and at precisely 1:50 p.m., turned it on.
   The announcer read the day's highs, lows and closing prices for
corn, soybeans and wheat. Rabideau recorded the numbers in his
ledger, as he has done for decades.
   The ritual soon will end _ perhaps as early as Dec. 1.
   When the last grain stored at the elevator has been sold,
Rabideau will put the radio back on the corner of his desk, return
the ledgers to the huge steel vault, and walk away.
   ``This elevator was built in 1918, so it was built for the horse
and buggy,'' he said.
   Rabideau Grain is a rural island in downtown Kankakee, a
northwestern Illinois city of 100,000.
   When the elevator opened, it was perfect for the single grain
wagons pulled by tractors or an occasional team of horses.
   ``It just wasn't made for these 500-bushel trucks,'' said
Rabideau. ``They can't get into the driveway very well, and the
traffic right downtown is terrible.''
   Rabideau was born on a farm near Clifton in 1911, but decided
early that life on the land was not for him.
   ``There was no money in it, and way too much work,'' he said.
   He worked four years at a hospital, and attended Gallagher
Business School for a year. It was Mary Gallagher who sent him to
see Claude Carter at the grain elevator for a job.
   Rabideau was paid $15 a week.
   ``I tell that to people now and they think it just can't be
so,'' he said. ``But ... working on the farm meant working for $10
or $15 a month.''
   Buying and selling grain was only part of the business.
   ``We did grinding of corn and oats for dairy cattle, plus mixing
hog and poultry feed,'' Rabideau recalled.
   In 1972, he bought the business from Carter.
   His customers were his friends; a handshake was his bond.
   ``We made many contracts these past 52 years,'' said Rabideau.
``We never had one of them signed by any customer.''
   Only twice in half a century did that cause a problem.
   ``Once in a while, some of our customers would need a few
hundred dollars,'' said Rabideau. ``If we were in a position to
help out, we would.''
   Through the years, retired farmers have stopped in the elevator
office to chat with Rabideau and other friends and neighbors.
   ``In the end, we were buying grain from their children and
grandchildren,'' he said.
   Most of the grain delivered to Rabideau was sold to processors
in the area.
   Rabideau will take some mementos with him _ the brass
thermometer on the wall and his old brass grain probe.
   And, he will take something even more valuable.
   ``I've had, and still have, many fond memories of working with
our farmers,'' he said. ``They're a grand bunch of honest and
hard-working people.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
