<SECOND>PM-Eastern Arrests,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seven Strikers Arrested in Rock-Throwing Incident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Machinists were banned from picketing at the
airport after strikers pelted cars with rocks and beat up an
Eastern employee, authorities said.
   Seven strikers were arrested Sunday on charges of unlawful
assembly when they refused to leave the area at the Hartsfield
Atlanta International Airport. Machinists involved in the strike
against Eastern have set up a tent city on the airport grounds.
   The Eastern worker, Stanley Almon, told police he was leaving a
maintenance hangar after the shift change when strikers began
throwing rocks at his car and smashed windows.
   Almon was attacked by about 15 men when he jumped from his car
and yelled at about 300 strikers near the hangar, said police
Officer C.W. Wood.
   Wood, assigned to guard the area, said he waded into the melee
and rescued Almon, who was treated at a hospital for a dislocated
finger.
   After the incident, police ordered all but 20 strikers out of
the tent city, said Mark Coates, airport operations spokesman. He
said the 20 were allowed to remain to guard equipment at the
encampment.
   One striker, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
Machinists union members were frustrated by the events of the past
week, which included a decision by Eastern's pilots and flight
attendants to end their walkout that began to show solidarity with
the Machinists.
