<FIRST>r a PM-Salvador-WomanHeld     11-27 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador-Woman Held,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>Young Connecticut Women Faces Gun Hiding Accusations in El Salvador</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Salvador</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THOMASTON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mother and friends of an American
church activist arrested in El Salvador denied the accusations of
Salvadoran police that she had hidden explosives and ammunition for
leftist guerrillas.
   ``Jennifer is working for the church,'' said Audrey Casolo, the
mother of 28-year-old Jennifer J. Casolo. ``She is working to help
the poor people.''
   Salvadoran police on Sunday arrested Ms. Casolo and seized a
cache of ammunition they said was buried under her house in San
Salvador. Police briefly exhibited Ms. Casolo for reporters Sunday,
but she was not provided an opportunity to comment.
   Ms. Casolo, of Thomaston, is a representative of the Christian
Educational Seminar, an ecumenical group based in San Antonio,
Texas, that provides tours of El Salvador to visiting Americans.
   Sen. Christopher J. Dodd, D-Conn., said he was assured by the
Salvadoran ambassador in Washington, D.C., that Ms. Casolo would
not be harmed.
   Maj. Mauricio Chavez Caceres, an Salvadoran armed forces
spokesman, said 40,000 rounds of ammunition for U.S.-made M-16
rifles, 40,000 rounds of ammunition for Soviet-designed AK-47
rifles, 203 blocks of TNT and 403 detonator caps were found in Ms.
Casolo's house and at other locations.
   Chavez said the cache ``proves church involvement'' with the
Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, the guerrillas of El
Salvador. Salvadoran authorities said they were tipped off to the
arms cache by a rebel deserter.
   Friends noted that Ms. Casolo's arrest came amid a wave of
harassment and arrests of church workers of various denominations
in El Salvador. Six Jesuit priest-professors were slain Nov. 16 and
witnesses said the military was involved.
   Since her 1983 graduation from Brandeis University, Ms. Casolo
has worked with the church and the poor. After receiving her degree
in American and Latin American studies, she worked at a soup
kitchen in Chicago and taught English to refugees in Maryland.
   In 1984, she taught adults to read and write in a village in the
Dominican Republic.
   Four years ago, she went to El Salvador to organize tours for
delegations from the United States and Canada, said Susan Abbott, a
friend from Thomaston High School.
   ``She would take them around,'' she said. ``They would see
government officials. They would go to refugee camps, the
cooperatives they had down there. From the left to the right, she
tried to give the delegations a real feel for what was going on in
El Salvador.''
   Another friend of Ms. Casolo from New Haven, who once worked
with her in El Salvador, said she suspects the ammunition was
planted by agents of the Salvadoran government.
   ``They're trying to frame her to justify the actions taken by
the military against international church workers in the last two
weeks,'' said the friend, Ann Lutterman. ``They're trying to imply
that churches are responsible for the violence, which is
ludicrous.''
   John Blatz, a spokesman for the Christian Educational Seminar,
called the accusations against Ms. Casolo ``part of their
persecution of the churches. That's clear.''
   At times family and friends have wanted Ms. Casolo to return to
United States, but Ms. Casolo felt she had a calling among the
people of El Salvador, Abbot said.
   ``She feels like she's really being helpful. That's where she
was happy being,'' Abbott said. ``Naturally, we're all worried
about her.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
