<FIRST>r a PM-CitiesMeeting     11-27 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cities Meeting,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Pushers, Users, Crime Rate Targeted by Big City Mayors</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AX2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICIA WALSH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   City governments are willing to be soldiers in
the battle against drugs but need more than just fighting words
from the Bush administration, mayors attending an annual conference
said.
   Mayor Terry Goddard of Phoenix, president of the National League
of Cities, said Sunday the federal government must do more to fight
illegal drugs, viewed by Americans as the gravest problem facing
the country.
   ``And yet, we've heard all the rhetoric, we heard (drug czar
William) Bennett make all the right analyses, and then the mountain
labored and out came a mouse. There were no new resources, no new
commitment to fight drugs,'' Goddard said at the conference
attended by 5,000 officials.
   ``The federal government needs to step in,'' said Seattle Mayor
Charles Royer. ``Give me a break about `the federal government's
money' _ just because they print it doesn't mean they earn it.''
   With such a large chunk of federal tax being funneled into
defense, it is hard to get funding for local programs, Royer said.
   Mayor Andrew Young, a former U.S. ambassador to the United
Nations, said major cuts in military spending won't come soon,
despite the improved relations between the United States and the
Soviet Union and the growing independence of Eastern Europe.
   ``A 5 percent cut in military spending may be realistic, but I
don't see a drastic dismantling of the military empire,'' Young
said. ``We must wait and see if the changes are maintained. We were
doing pretty well in China, and all of a sudden they clamped down.''
   Young said the lack of federal resources to resolve domestic
problems is rooted in the lack of decisive national leadership.
``The problem with Washington is that nobody will make a decision
about anything,'' he said.
   Cleveland Mayor George Voinovich said that inadequate public
education is the root of the drug problem. ``Somehow, we have to
get these kids as early as we can and teach them not to use
drugs,'' he said.
   ``When I was elected in 1977, crack was not even in our
vocabulary. Now, it is the symbol of a lost generation ... of
people who are not safe on the streets,'' Royer said.
   Vice President Dan Quayle canceled a scheduled address today due
to a death in his family. Jack Kemp, secretary for Housing and
Urban Development, is scheduled to speak Tuesday.
</TEXT>
