<SECOND>PM-Flight 103-Malta,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Flight 103 Relatives Seek Action against Iran, Syria at Malta Summit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Relatives of those killed in the bombing of
Pan Am Flight 103 have asked President Bush and Mikhail Gorbachev
to discuss sanctions against Syria and Iran during their summit
meeting this week.
   In a letter delivered to the U.S. and Soviet embassies in London
on Friday, three organizations representing the relatives aske the
leaders to ``spare the time to address the problem of international
state-backed terrorism'' during their weekend meeting at Malta.
   The relatives have not received a reply from the Soviets or the
White House. Relatives have said they may hold a news conference in
Malta during the meeting.
   The groups urged that economic sanctions be used to combat
state-backed terrorism. They believe Flight 103 was blown up over
Lockerbie, Scotland by a Syrian-backed terrorist group and financed
by Iran in retaliation for the downing of an Iranian airliner by a
U.S. warship.
   The letter was written by the two groups of U.S. victims'
relatives, Victims of Pan Am Flight 103 and Families of Pan-Am
103-Lockerbie, and the relatives' group in the United Kingdom, U.K.
Families _ Flight 103.
   Among the 270 killed in the Dec. 21 bombing were 11 people on
the ground in Lockerbie.
