<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     11-27 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against most major foreign
currencies except the British pound in early European trading
today. Gold prices were higher.
   Currency dealers predicted the dollar could have firmer moments
on technical rebounds, but said it's on a weak trend through the
end of the year.
   ``The dollar no longer has very much support,'' said one analyst
in Milan, Italy.
   Jens-Uwe Fischer, senior trader at Manufacturers Hanover in
Frankfurt, said the primary factor behind the dollar's recent
weakness was the drop in U.S. Federal Funds rates to 8.25 percent
from 8.50 percent.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.45 yen to a closing 143.35 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 143.39 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Friday:
   _1.7907 West German marks, down from 1.8040
   _1.6030 Swiss francs, down from 1.6145
   _6.1163 French francs, down from 6.1600
   _2.0215 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0340
   _1,322.50 Italian lire, down from 1,333.75
   _1.1665 Canadian dollars, unchanged
   In London, the dollar rose against the British pound. It cost
$1.5567 to buy one pound, compared with $1.5635 late Friday.
   Chancellor of the Exchequer John Major reiterated on Sunday he
was prepared to raise the cost of borrowing if necessary to bring
down inflation.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $417.90 a troy ounce, up
from $416.25 bid late Friday. At midmorning, the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $417.15.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $417.00, up from $416.10 bid late
Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.12 to close at a bid $418.02.
   Silver rose in London to a bid price of $5.85 a troy ounce, down
from Friday's $5.86.
</TEXT>
