<FIRST>r i PM-MexicanElections     11-27 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexican Elections,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Impound Hundreds of Ballots in Suspected Vote Fraud</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MATAMOROS, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The opposition claimed fraud in the
northern state of Tamaulipas after election officials impounded
more than 1,000 apparently pre-marked ballots.
   The ballots were in polling boxes stuffed with votes cast for
the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party, known by its Spanish
initials PRI, before the polls opened Sunday.
   At Matamoros precinct No. 35A, where only 18 people had signed
in to vote by mid-morning, election officials counted 562 ballots
cast in the race for state representative, and 429 in the separate
box for the mayoral election.
   Almost all of the extra ballots were marked for candidates of
the PRI.
   ``The people of Matamoros will not accept this, and neither will
the people of Tamaulipas,'' said Jorge Cardenas, candiate for mayor
of Matamoros for the opposition Authentic Party of the Mexican
Revolution.
   Matamoros, a city of about 180,000 people, lies just across the
Texas border from Brownsville.
   Reymundo Padilla, president of precinct No. 35A, said he did not
know how the ballots ended up in the boxes before polls opened.
   ``Somebody put them in the boxes,'' Padilla said.
   ``Fraude, fraude, fraude,'' a crowd chanted at a health clinic
where the ballots were being tallied. Voting was suspended
temporarily.
   PRI mayoral candidate Javier Muzquiz said vote fraud would be
impossible in Matamoros because precinct officials would discover
it.
   PARM officials turned over 300 additional ballots marked for the
PRI after discovering a man carrying them with him.
   Valentin Jimenez Mora, a PARM candidate for state
representative, said the votes ``were to be used for tacos'' _
ballots with several additional ballots secretly folded inside,
making it possible for one person to cast more than one vote.
</TEXT>
