<FIRST>r a PM-Loyola-Abortion     11-27 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Loyola-Abortion,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Catholic University Suspends Pro-Choice Student Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Loyola University barred a student group from
meeting on campus unless it reverses its support of women's right
to choose abortion and to use contraception.
   The Women's Center at the Roman Catholic school cannot be
recognized as an official student group if it insists on advocating
abortion rights and contraception, said university spokesman Joseph
Marren.
   ``It's a freedom of speech issue _ the anti-choice position is
clearly represented on campus,'' said David Gandolfo, a Women's
Center member.
   He said the Women's Center was founded on campus in 1978 and had
its constitution approved by the administration in 1982.
   The Catholic Church teaches that abortion is murder and forbids
the use of artificial contraceptive devices.
   On one occasion, Loyola officials stopped the group from
distributing Illinois Public Health Department packets on AIDS,
each of which included a condom.
   The dispute follows controversies at other Catholic universities
this fall over publication of an advertisement in student
newspapers urging attendance at Nov. 10 abortion-rights rallies.
   At Marquette University in Milwaukee, the business manager for
student publications was fired for running the ad, and two students
were suspended from their posts on the newspaper staff.
   Student editors at Georgetown University in Washington, D.C.,
refused to publish an edition of the school newspaper when they
were barred from running the ad.
   The ad ran in the student newspaper at the Catholic University,
also in Washington, prompting protests from anti-abortion advocates
and a critical letter to the editor from a university official.
</TEXT>
