<FIRST>r a PM-LotsofLeftovers     11-27 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lots of Leftovers,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Food Bank To Distribute Thanksgiving Food</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST PITTSBURGH, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hardly anyone showed up at a
Thanksgiving party for the poor but a food bank will distribute the
hundreds of pounds of leftovers.
   Caterer John Kostik said he had hoped to serve at least 700
needy people at his banquet hall in this Pittsburgh suburb
Thursday. Twenty-four showed up, fewer than the 35 volunteers who
offered to help serve the food.
   After his plight was publicized, Kostik and his wife, Jane, both
40, gave out food to about 80 people Friday but still had about 200
pounds of turkey, 210 pounds of potatoes, 60 cases of bulk corn and
more than 200 pumpkin pies left.
   Kostik said his use of the word ``needy'' on the flyers may have
discouraged some people in the neighborhood _ home to many
unemployed former steelworkers and senior citizens _ from showing
up.
   ``We don't have a lot of street people in East Pittsburgh,'' he
said. ``This is a quiet, depressed area with a population that is
too proud to ask for help.''
   Kostik said he mailed dozens of public service announcements
about the feast, which cost him $1,000, to newspapers and
television and radio stations, but apparently none were used.
   Volunteers posted flyers throughout the neighborhood, but that
didn't help either.
   Kostick said he was disappointed at the turnout.
   ``I was left with a real empty feeling, but the media attention
helped us _ after the fact,'' he said.
   The Greater Pittsburgh Community Food Bank will distribute the
leftovers to poor families, said Joyce Rothermel, the group's
executive director.
</TEXT>
