<FIRST>r a PM-Hezbollah 1stLd-Writethru a0459 11-27 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hezbollah, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0459,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hezbollah Network in West Africa, Report Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `The pro-Iran ...' to recast to change `credit'
to `responsibility'.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Shiite Moslem extremist group Hezbollah
has established a network of operatives in West Africa that may be
preparing attacks against Western targets, a newspaper reported
today.
   Hezbollah agents are active in the Ivory Coast, Senegal, Gabon,
Zaire and possibly other countries, the Los Angeles Times reported,
citing unidentified U.S. and French officials.
   As Western intelligence agencies have focused on Iran and
Lebanon, Hezbollah may have moved to create an alternative arms
network in West Africa as early as 1986, the newspaper said.
   French authorities believe a Hezbollah cell played ``a prominent
role'' in planting a bomb aboard a French airliner that exploded
over Niger in September, killing 171 people.
   ``Tehran's reach now extends into Hezbollah communities in West
Africa, and it seeks to duplicate there what it did in Lebanon,'' a
U.S. official said.
   The pro-Iran Hezbollah, or Party of God, has claimed
responsibility for taking Western hostages and terrorist bombings
in Lebanon.
   On Saturday, Spanish police said a Hezbollah cell had tried to
smuggle 18 pounds of plastic explosives into Spain, according to
the newspaper. It said 10 people were arrested in a plot to attack
targets in Europe.
   In recent months, French officials have discovered security
breaches at their embassies in Guinea, Gabon, Senegal and Tunisia
involving the sale of passports and intelligence cables to
Hezbollah agents, the newspaper said.
   In the most serious incident, a French consular official in
Conakry, Guinea, provided 100 identity cards and 60 passports to a
Shiite cell, the Times said. The scheme surfaced when a Lebanese
national carrying one of the passports blew himself up with a
homemade bomb in London last summer, French diplomats told the
newspaper.
   In Dakar, Senegal, officials reportedly caught a French embassy
employee selling French identity cards to another group of
Lebanese. And in Brazzaville, Gabon, where the doomed UTA French
airline flight originated, a security breach involved stolen
diplomatic cables, the newspaper said.
   Most of the French consular officials involved were contract
workers who had served in Beirut or had Lebanese connections,
French officials said. Several were arrested.
   ``We don't believe the cells are being created to destabilize
the countries they are in,'' said a French official. ``But all
these countries offer bases for operations against the West.
   ``They are in the courtyard of Europe. And security is
notoriously lax in West Africa,'' the official said.
   Intelligence officials suspect the agents operate among tens of
thousands of Shiite Muslim emigres who work in the region. A State
Department source told the Times there was no evidence that Iran
has sponsored the implantation of the cells.
</TEXT>
