<FIRST>u i PM-Uruguay-Elections 1stLd-Writethru a0485 11-27 0683</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Uruguay-Elections, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0485,0699</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governing Party Ousted In National Elections; Economy Main Issue</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE vote totals, date Lacalle takes
office; Picks up 8th graf, `The rest ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTEVIDEO, Uruguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Uruguayans chose Luis Lacalle as
president in hopes his opposition National Party would reverse
three decades of economic decline in this once-rich South American
nation.
   In Montevideo, a Marxist doctor easily defeated all rivals to
become mayor of the country's capital and largest city.
   Eight hours after polls closed Sunday, the Interior Ministry had
issued tallies from more than half of the 8,493 voting districts
that gave Sen. Lacalle a comfortable lead.
   Lacalle, who will take office March 1, has pledged to work with
people of all political stripes in reforming Uruguay's
state-dominated economy and easing its foreign debt burden. He
pledged to build a governing coalition.
   On the basis of party and independent tallies, Jorge Batlle of
the governing Colorado Party _ the son and grand-nephew of
presidents _ acknowledged his bid had failed.
   ``The future president will be Sen. Lacalle, to whom I offer my
most sincere congratulations and best wishes for success in his
term,'' said Batlle, a 62-year-old senator who ran unsuccessfully
for president in 1966 and 1971.
   According to the Interior Ministry, the National Party received
430,846 votes, or 39.8 percent, compared with 325,879 or 30.7
percent, for the Colorados. The leftist Broad Front coalition
finished third with 168,830 votes.
   The rest of the vote was split among six smaller parties. About
2.32 million voters _ or 80 percent of those registered _ took part
in the mandatory balloting, election officials said.
   Lacalle, 48, in brief comments to reporters at his party's
headquarters, said his would be a government of ``national unity.''
After accepting the congratulations of Broad Front's presidential
candidate, retired Gen. Liber Seregni, Lacalle said he would issue
a public statement later today.
   Lacalle's party, which last held executive power in 1967, was
expected to receive the biggest bloc but not a majority in the
30-seat Senate and 99-member House of Deputies.
   In Montevideo, thousands of residents danced to bongo drums, set
off firecrackers, waved banners and cruised in cars after Broad
Front candidate Tabare Vazquez defeated all rivals to become mayor.
   ``Celebrate, neighbors, because the needy will be the most
privileged,'' an exultant Vazquez told several thousand cheering
supporters outside his party's headquarters.
   ``The mayoralty is the first step,'' said supporter Osvaldo
Martins, 37, a clothing wholesaler. ``The next step is national
power. ... If we govern well here, the rest of the country will
support us.''
   In campaigning to replace President Julio M. Sanguinetti, who
was elected in November 1984 and took office in March 1985 to
replace a military dictatorship, Lacalle focused on Uruguay's
economy.
   Under Sanguinetti, unemployment dropped from 14 percent to about
9 percent, and the deficit was halved to about 4.5 percent of gross
national product.
   But inflation refused to go below 57 percent, payments on the
$6.3 billion foreign debt cut sharply into public programs and
standards of living continued to decline.
   ``I think we're the same as we were four years ago, and some
people are worse off than before,'' said Jorge de Melo, a
26-year-old metalworker.
   ``When we look at the outside world, there have been tremendous
advances,'' said Marcos Larghero, 47, a graphic designer. ``The
opposite has occurred here. We deteriorate a little bit each year.''
   Lacalle made no promises that Uruguay would soon take its place
among the world's wealthier nations, as it was for the first half
of this century.
   But he said inflation would decrease to 20 percent, exports
would increase by 20 percent to $2 billion a year and unemployment
would continue to decline throughout his five-year term.
   To resolve the foreign debt, Lacalle proposed to sell some of
Uruguay's 3 million ounces of gold reserves, and buy investments
that would generate interest to help pay the debt.
   Lacalle has pledged to sell inefficient public companies, cut
federal bureaucracy and encourage foreign investment.
</TEXT>
