<FIRST>r i PM-Netherlands-US     11-27 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Netherlands-US,0416</SECOND>
<BYLINE>No U.S. Withdrawals From Europe Before Arms Deal, Cheney Promises
^By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney said
no U.S. troops will be withdrawn from Europe without a superpower
agreement on conventional arms, the Dutch government said today.
   The comment followed news reports that quoted Cheney as saying
more troop reductions have been made possible by the continued
``erosion'' of the Soviet military threat in Europe. He reportedly
said this during his flight to the Netherlands from Washington.
   Cheney, who was scheduled to travel to Brussels for an annual
meeting of North Atlantic Treaty Organization defense ministers,
was not immediately available for comment.
   The Dutch defense minister, Relus ter Beek, quoted Cheney as
saying he expected the Vienna-based talks on Conventional Forces in
Europe to be followed by another round of disarmament negotiations
between NATO and the Warsaw Pact.
   ``Withdrawal of ... American troops from the European continent
will take place (only) after a (conventional arms) agreement,'' the
Dutch official told reporters after meeting with Cheney for several
hours Sunday and today.
   Ter Beek said he was promised by Cheney that the Pentagon's
plans for cutting $150 billion to $180 billion over the next five
years would not affect the NATO alliance before a conventional arms
agreement is concluded.
   The conventional arms talks are aimed at achieving parity
between the number of troops deployed in Europe by NATO and the
Warsaw Pact.
   Cheney said he expected further troop reductions once a
conventional arms agreement is completed, probably some time next
year, according to Ter Beek.
   A conventional arms agreement would include withdrawal of at
least some of the 300,000 U.S. troops stationed in Europe as well
as reductions in the number of soldiers and conventional weaponry
being deployed by the other NATO allies. Most of the U.S. troops
are in West Germany.
   ``We were very pleased to hear that the U.S. secretary also
assumed ... an initial agreement in Vienna will be followed'' by
another round of talks aimed at further conventional troop
reductions, Ter Beek said.
   The Dutch official said he and Cheney also discussed the swift
movement for democratic change in Eastern Europe, including
Czechoslovakia, where demonstrations have resulted in the ouster of
several hard-line Communist leaders.
   Ter Beek said the two agreed on the need for ``full support for
perestroika,'' Mikhail Gorbachev's policy of restructuring the
Soviet political and economic system.
</TEXT>
