<FIRST>r i PM-Hostages     11-27 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hostages,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Journalist Marks Birthday in Captivity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British journalist John McCarthy today turned 33
years old in captivity, his fourth birthday since he was taken
hostage in Lebanon.
   Friends appealed to the government for greater efforts to free
McCarthy, and they released eight white doves outside the Foreign
Office.
   ``The doves are symbolic of peace. We are releasing them as a
gesture of freedom in the hope of galvanizing the Foreign Office to
do more,'' said McCarthy's girlfriend, Jill Morrell.
   McCarthy's friends and relatives also placed a large
advertisement in a Beirut newspaper appealing for his release.
   McCarthy, who works for Worldwide Television News, disappeared
after being seized on the road to Beirut airport on his way home
April 17, 1986.
   He is one of four Britons missing in Lebanon. A total of 18
Westerners, including eight Americans, are held there, most by
pro-Iranian groups.
   ``John has obviously suffered 3{ years of torture,'' Miss
Morrell said. ``I know he will have found some way of coping with
it because John has a strong character, but I can't imagine how he
keeps sane. I don't think I could have done that.''
   The hostage held longest is Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press. He was seized March 16,
1985.
