<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Lee     11-27 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Lee,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Californian Loses Challenge to OK of Kennedy to Supreme Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today rejected the appeal of
a Hollywood, Calif., man who sued the Senate Judiciary Committee
over its unanimous vote last year favoring Justice Anthony M.
Kennedy's appointment to the high court.
   The court, without comment, let stand rulings that threw out
Monte Lee's lawsuit.
   Kennedy did not participate in considering Lee's appeal or in
the court's action today.
   Lee's suit contended that the committee's 14 senators violated
his rights by voting for Kennedy without investigating allegations
of wrongdoing against the nominee.
   Lee's allegations arose from Kennedy's participation in 1986 as
a member of a 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals panel in a ruling
unfavorable to Lee. According to court documents, Lee had been
challenging the doctrine of judicial immunity in the case.
   The Senate Judiciary Committee's unanimous vote was taken Jan.
27, 1988. The full Senate confirmed then-President Reagan's
nomination of Kennedy by a 97-0 vote Feb. 3, 1988.
   A federal trial judge dismissed Lee's lawsuit, and the dismissal
was upheld by a 9th Circuit court panel last June 5.
   The appeals court said the senators are absolutely immune, under
the Constitution's speech and debate clause, from being sued over
their alleged failure to investigate Kennedy properly.
   The case is Lee vs. Biden, 89-591.
</TEXT>
