<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Strip Search,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kentucky Officials Sued for Strip-Searching Lose Appeal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kentucky law enforcement officials sued for
strip-searching a woman charged with operating her car without
proper registration or insurance lost a Supreme Court appeal today.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that
strip-searching people accused of minor traffic violations
generally violates their rights.
   Karen Masters pleaded not guilty Aug. 21, 1986, to driving her
car with expired registration plates and failure to maintain auto
insurance.
   She was ordered to return to court on Oct. 23 and was given a
card to remind her of that date. By mistake, the judge recorded
Mrs. Masters' next scheduled appearance as Oct. 16.
   Jefferson County police officers arrested Mrs. Masters at her
home Oct. 21 for failure to appear in court on Oct. 16.
   After police dropped off her two young children with Mrs.
Masters' mother, they handcuffed Mrs. Masters and took her to jail.
   A female attendant frisked her and ordered her to open her
blouse in front of a window and in view of other people. About four
hours later she was taken to another room where she was ordered by
another female attendant to take off all her clothes for a more
thorough search.
   After putting on a jail dress, Mrs. Masters was placed in a cell
with other prisoners. She was not released until later that evening.
   Throughout her ordeal, Mrs. Masters repeatedly protested that
her arrest was a mistake. She showed police her ``reminder card''
as evidence she had not failed to report for her court date.
   Mrs. Masters later sued four police officers and the head of the
county corrections department for allegedly violating her rights.
   The law enforcement officials said they should be immune from
such a suit, largely because of a 1985 court consent decree that
settled an unrelated case involving overcrowding at the county jail.
   The decree authorized strip searches of inmates at the jail when
they are transferred from one area to another.
   The 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals last April rejected the
county officials' arguments aimed at killing Mrs. Masters' suit.
   ``We have found no authority approving a practice of conducting
a strip search of a person arrested for a simple traffic violation
in the absence of at least reasonable suspicion that the person
might be carrying a weapon, illegal drugs or other contraband,''
the appeals court said.
   The consent decree did not give the police power to ignore
clearly established principles protecting rights of people accused
of minor traffic offenses, the appeals court said.
   The case is Frey vs. Masters, 89-576.
</TEXT>
