<FIRST>r a PM-FishermenLost     11-27 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fishermen Lost,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Continues Search for Five Missing Fishermen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Coast Guard intensified its search this
morning for five missing fishermen after a cutter and a jet spotted
white flares in the area where the lobster boat disappeared.
   The men, aboard the 72-foot Heidi Marie out of Stonington,
Conn., were reported missing Wednesday after they failed to call
the boat's owner, James P. Garbo.
   The Coast Guard found fishing markers from the lobster boat
Friday and identified an emergency floating radio beacon as
belonging to the vessel.
   Petty Officer Elizabeth Brannan said the cutter spotted a white
flare about midnight Sunday, prompting rescuers to launch a
nighttime jet search about 200 miles south of Nantucket.
   ``The jet sighted a flare, but ... while they were searching
they weren't able to confirm the source before having to turn back
to refuel,'' Brannan said.
   The hunt was stepped up early today and, in addition to the two
cutters on the scene, it included five jets from as far away as
North Carolina that would cover 8,400 square miles of ocean, she
said.
   Petty Officer Ellen Harrington said it was not known if the
flares were related to the missing vessel, adding that ``white
flares are not generally considered distress flares, but we have to
consider that they are.''
   Officer Jack Mason described Sunday's effort as a ``full-blown''
search, using Navy aircraft from Massachusetts, Maine, New York and
North Carolina, as well as the two 270-foot cutters from Boston.
   There were no immediate plans end the search for the fishermen,
Mason said. ``We go as long as we feel there's reasonable hope,''
he said.
   Coast Guard officials have said there was still some reason to
believe there could be survivors. The vessel was equipped with a
high-quality inflatable covered life raft that held up to eight
people.
   During the five days of searching, rescuers have used
sophisticated equipment and special flare searches while
criss-crossing 10,000 square miles of sea under mostly fair weather
conditions and good visibility.
   Garbo declined comment Sunday through his attorney, Tom Clinton.
He has not yet spoken publicly about the incident, although his
wife said he is in constant touch with the Coast Guard.
   The crew members were identified as Michael Hare, Capt. Mark
Middleton, 33; Ray Gould, Arthur Banks and Ray Morris, all in their
twenties, the Coast Guard said.
</TEXT>
