<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Westies     11-27 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Westies,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>New York Gang Members Lose Challenge to Convictions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today rejected appeals by
four men and a woman convicted for their roles in a hoodlum gang,
the Westies, in the Hell's Kitchen section of New York City.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that the five
were prosecuted fairly.
   Convicted of racketeering and related charges were James Coonan
and Edna Coonan, James McElroy, Richard Ritter and William Bokun.
   Prosecutors described Coonan as the ringleader of an underworld
group that terrorized the Manhattan neighborhood for 20 years until
the mid-1980s.
   Coonan was sentenced to 75 years in prison and fined $1 million;
his wife received a 15-year sentence and $200,000 fine; McElroy was
sentenced to 60 years, Ritter to 40 years and Bokun to 50 years.
   The Westies were involved in murders, kidnapping, extortion,
loansharking, gambling and drug distribution, the government said.
Three victims were dismembered and their bodies dumped into the
East River.
   Prosecutors said Coonan supervised the gang even while serving a
prison sentence for murder. They said his wife ran the Westies'
loansharking operation and relayed messages from the jailed Coonan
to his subordinates.
   McElroy was described as a chief enforcer, Bokun as a killer and
cocaine dealer and Ritter as a cocaine dealer and loanshark.
   In the appeal acted on today, the Coonans said they were
convicted largely on the basis of hearsay and gossip. They said
while Coonan was in prison other gang members falsely boasted they
had committed crimes with him to intimidate victims.
   Ritter said police illegally searched his apartment. Bokun said
he was denied adequate legal representation after his attorney was
forced to withdraw eight weeks into the trial because of illness.
   McElroy and Edna Coonan said they were denied a fair trial
because the judge barred a psychiatrist from testifying about the
mental illness of a prosecution witness.
   The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the convictions in
May.
   The cases are Coonan vs. U.S., 89-379; Ritter vs. U.S., 89-5497;
Bokun vs. U.S., 89-5512; McElroy vs. U.S., 89-5601.
</TEXT>
