<FIRST>r i PM-EastGermany 2ndLd-Writethru a0514 11-27 0685</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-East Germany, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0514,0702</SECOND>
<HEAD>Party Criticizes Youth Group For Splitting From Party</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with allied party urging `humane
socialism', recasts lede; Picks up 8th graf, `In another ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Germany's Communist Party today
criticized its 2.3 million-member youth organization for breaking
away and said the leadership in Czechoslovakia was paying ``a
bitter price'' for resisting reform.
   The official party newspaper Neues Deutschland said the decision
by the Freie Deutsche Jugend, or Free German Youth, to abandon the
party could threaten the youth group's future.
   The group, the traditional stepping stone to success for the
Communist leadership, including party chief Egon Krenz, announced
Friday it no longer wanted to be the ``helper and fighting
reserve'' of the party.
   In a commentary, Neues Deutschland spoke of a ``loss of
confidence'' in the youth group, which it said is ``struggling for
a new profile and perhaps for its existence.''
   Another Communist-run daily, the Berliner Zeitung, offered East
Germany's harshest criticism to date of Czechoslovakia's rulers,
saying they were paying ``the bitter price for the grave errors of
the past.''
   The commentary traced the troubles of the party leadership in
Prague to refusing political reforms and to ``the illusory, risky
business of trying to choke the call for democracy with police
clubs 10 days ago.''
   It was referring to the police crackdown on demonstrators in
Prague on Nov. 17. The severity of the crackdown sparked an
unprecedented series of protest that has forced the ouster of
hard-line Communists, including party chief Milos Jakes.
   The National Democrats, one of the smaller parties long allied
with the Communists, appealed today for a ``more effective and more
humane socialism'' in East Germany.
   The comments by party leader Fred Dumke echoed Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's remarks Sunday in Pravda. Gorbachev's
statement was seen as an endorsement of the 1968 ``Prague Spring''
slogan of ``socialism with a human face,'' adopted anew by
pro-democracy protesters in Czechoslovakia.
   In another sign of the East German party's own problems,
Communist sources said Sunday that huge amounts of money earned
from Communist Party-owned businesses in East Germany are
unaccounted for.
   Party reformers have urged an inquiry to determine if the
revenues were diverted, the sources said.
   The charges of revenue diversion concern money earned at
businesses, including trading firms and hard-currency shops, set up
to earn West German marks and other foreign currency, the party
sources said Sunday on condition of anonymity.
   Earnings of the roughly 100 companies total from $3.8 billion to
$6.5 billion per year, much of which is unaccounted for, the
sources said.
   ``These companies have misappropriated money that belongs to the
people,'' one source said.
   The party sources said several high-ranking reform-minded
Communists, whose names were not disclosed, have called for an
investigation to determine where the money went.
   The enterprises included electronics and transport companies and
an art trading company, among many others, the party sources said.
   They said the enterprises include the East Berlin company
Intrac, specializing in trade in chemicals and metals, and a
company identified only as one ``for internal and foreign trade in
radioactive and stable isotopes.''
   Such an investigation would be only the latest show of
discontent with the party.
   The party has lost about 200,000 people _ or 10 percent of its
membership _ in the past two months, Neues Deutschland quoted
Central Committee member Heinz Mirtschin as saying in its weekend
edition.
   Krenz, facing a battle for his political career at a party
congress next month, has been trying to shift attention to abuses
that can be blamed on his predecessor, Erich Honecker.
   Krenz, however, was a member of Honecker's inner circle and
former chief of the country's security apparatus.
   Honecker was ousted Oct. 18 and replaced by Krenz, who has
presided over the opening of the Berlin Wall and an official
commitment to reform.
   Among Krenz's moves toward power-sharing have been to propose
``round-table'' talks with the opposition, similar to the
discussions that led to dramatic political changes in Hungary and
Poland.
</TEXT>
