<SECOND>PM-BRF--Inmate Charged,0138</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Inmate Charged In Camp Hill Riot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMP HILL, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities have charged the first inmate
in connection with a three-day-long riot last month at a
medium-security state prison that injured nearly 125 people and
caused extensive damage.
   William Diggs, 25, was arraigned on a variety of charges,
including kidnapping and making terroristic threats, Cumberland
County District Attorney J. Michael Eakin said today. Charges
against other inmates will be filed within several weeks, Eakin
said.
   Officials didn't release any details of any alleged activities
by Diggs during the riot Oct. 25-27 at the 52-acre prison about
five miles west of Harrisburg.
   Eakin said he filed the charges against Diggs, serving time for
robbery, on Friday to prevent the inmate's scheduled release
Saturday. Diggs remains incarcerated in lieu of $500,000 bail.

