<FILEID>AP-NR-11-27-89 1058EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-India-Elections 3rdLd-Writethru a0550 11-27 0903</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Elections, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0550,0929</SECOND>
<HEAD>Voters Abandon Gandhi's Party, Force Him To Form Coalition Gov't</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with Parliament dissolved, new
vote figures; Picks up 12th graf, `Many undeclared ...'; INSERTS 1 graf
after 16th, ``We will ...' with background on forming coalition.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DEL2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi's party
today failed to win a majority in elections for only the second
time in 42 years as voters deserted it for a new centrist alliance
and a fundamentalist Hindu party.
   Incomplete results from the election for a new Parliament showed
the Congress Party with more seats than any single opposition group
but far short of a mandate to form the next government alone.
   That leaves Gandhi in the difficult position of trying to form a
coalition government _ the first in the history of the world's most
populous democracy.
   The fundamentalist Bharatiya Janata Party, capitalizing on a
rise in Hindu nationalism, appeared destined to be the pivotal
player. Its leader said today he would ``see to it that they
(Congress) fall from power.''
   President Ramaswamy Venkataraman dissolved Parliament tonight,
the first formal step toward seating a new Parliament. Gandhi is
now a caretaker prime minister until his party or the opposition
manage to form a new government.
   The election was a major blow to Gandhi, who had been tainted by
allegations of government corruption and ineptitude. His family
dynasty has governed India for all but five years since it won
independence from Britain in 1947.
   Gandhi's leadership also had been called into question by the
widespread vote fraud and violence in the election that claimed 137
lives, making it the bloodiest balloting in modern India's history.
   The election for seats in Parliament's policy-making lower house
started Wednesday and was scheduled to end Sunday, but re-voting
was ordered in some districts because of alleged fraud. Balloting
ended today, and by sundown winners were declared in 373 of the 525
races.
   State television, compiling results from the Election
Commission, said the Congress Party had 160 seats. Its party allies
had 17.
   A majority in the new Parliament _ and with it the mandate to
form a new government _ requires 263 seats.
   The centrist National Front, a five-party alliance led by former
defense and finance minister Vishwanath Pratap Singh, had 81 seats.
Singh, an ex-Congress Party member, was once Gandhi's ally but is
now the prime minister's most outspoken political foe.
   The Bharatiya Janata, which won just two seats in the last
elections in 1984, had 69. The rest of the seats went to smaller
parties and independents.
   Many undeclared seats are in states where the National Front was
expected to do well.
   The Congress Party's poor showing could hurt it in the search
for coalition partners or trigger a revolt against the prime
minister by colleagues in his own party.
   ``If Congress wants to win anything, the prime minister must
go,'' said independent analyst Bhabani Sen Gupta. ``With Rajiv
Gandhi, very few things are possible. Without Rajiv Gandhi, many
things are possible.''
   The Congress Party dismissed the possibility of a coalition with
the Bharatiya Janata Party.
   ``We will contemptuously reject any overtures from the BJP.
There's no question (of aligning with them),'' Congress spokesman
Anand Sharma said. ``Congress is not in a tearing hurry'' to seek a
coalition with anyone.
   India has never had a coalition government, and the prospect
plunged many into confusion. To create a coalition, the president
would ask the party with the most seats to try to muster enough
partners for a parliamentary majority. If that fails, the president
could ask another party to try to forge a majority in alliance with
other parties.
   Gandhi, 45, the grandson of India's first prime minister,
Jawaharlal Nehru, was plunged into the leadership when his mother,
Prime Minister Indira Gandhi, was assassinated in 1984.
   His party then took an unprecedented 415 of the seats in the
lower house.
   The initial euphoria over a young, seemingly dynamic leader was
soon tarnished by allegations of government corruption and
ineptitude.
   The trouble came home to roost in Gandhi's own election district
of Amethi, where the outcome of his race for re-election is still
in limbo.
   Gandhi was expected to win easily when the remote area of dusty
villages voted on Wednesday. But the National Front complained of
widespread fraud by Congress Party activists, and another vote was
held today in about 18 percent of the district.
   Polling officer Uday Raj Pandey estimated more than 50 percent
of the voters showed up in Amethi.
   There were few issues in the campaign, apart from being for or
against Gandhi and the Congress.
   Another factor in the election was a revival of Hindu
fundamentalism.
   The surge followed Hindu-Moslem riots earlier this month that
left more than 300 people dead. The riots were sparked by a
campaign to build a temple on the site of a 16th century Moslem
mosque.
   Moslems voters also may have abandoned the Congress Party, their
traditional election choice, because the government did not prevent
the riots. Most of those who died were Moslems.
   Parliament's lower house has 543 seats, but only 524 were at
stake in the elections. No election was held for a seat with an
unopposed candidate.
   The elections for the rest of the seats were postponed
indefinitely because of incomplete voter lists or candidates'
deaths.
</TEXT>
