<SECOND>PM-BRF--Philly Homicides,0155</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shootings Break City's Homicide Record</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A shooting possibly related to crack use and
an apparent murder-suicide broke Philadelphia's record for
homicides in a single year, authorities said.
   The murder became the city's 445th this year, breaking the
record of 444 set in 1974, when widespread gang violence inflated
the city's death tally.
   Thomas Svenningsen, 60, a retired police officer, and his wife,
Betty, 59, were found dead of gunshot wounds by a son just before
midnight Sunday, police said.
   Earlier Sunday, police responding to a call found David
Williams, 28, lying in the living room of a West Philadelphia
house. Williams, who had been shot once in the back and once in the
groin, was pronounced dead at a hospital.
   Two people who were inside the house were questioned by police,
who said there was evidence of crack use. No arrests were made,
police said.
</TEXT>
