<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Baltics     11-27 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Baltics,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baltic Economic Autonomy Approved</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislators today gave final approval to a plan
putting the small Baltic republics on the road to economic autonomy
from Moscow next year and possibly issuing their own currencies.
   Deputies from the tiny republic of Estonia stood and cheered
after the Soviet Parliament approved the measure on a vote of
296-67. Another 37 deputies abstained.
   A final vote on the bill had been delayed from Friday after a
sharp debate on whether the move amounted to an effort to tear
apart the Soviet system.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev presided over the sessions Friday
and today and supported the bill as a step toward economic reform.
   The Tass news agency said the law goes into effect Jan. 1 and
gives Lithuania, Latvia and Estonia ``the right to engage in
independent economic activity and envisages equal participation in
union activity.''
   Baltic deputies stressed that the law gives them more control
over factories now controlled by government ministries based in
Moscow. They say it does not exclude the possibility of issuing
their own currencies.
   One deputy from the Soviet Far East, Nikolai Danilyuk, said
Friday he opposed the bill because ``I would not like to become a
participant in the disintegration of our great state.''
   But Estonian Prime Minister Indrik Toome said that only a
radical restructuring giving the republics more autonomy could save
the Soviet Union from disintegration that he said was caused by too
much control in Moscow.
   The law was given preliminary approval in July and sent to
legislative committees for further work.
</TEXT>
