<HEAD>Today's East Bloc Developments</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS Hungary to UPDATE with Socialists conceding defeat; ADDS
1 graf at end of Soviet Union with vote on Baltic autonomy.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today's East bloc developments:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CZECHOSLOVAKIA</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   All enterprises are affected by a symbolic general strike called
by the opposition, the latest move in 11-day-old effort to end
one-party Communist rule. Hours earlier, in an apparent effort to
head off the strike, embattled Communist leaders ousted three more
hard-liners from the ruling Politburo. The Communists also endorse
a ``dialogue'' with the opposition and agreed to a parliamentary
inquiry of the brutal police crackdown on a peaceful student rally
Nov. 17.
   The concessions come one day after unprecedented talks between
opposition leaders and Communist premier Ladislav Adamec, who told
about 300,000 demonstrators that authorities were ready to listen
to the people on reform.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EAST GERMANY</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The ruling Communist Party criticizes its 2.3 million-member
youth organization for splitting from the party. The official
Communist newspaper Neues Deutschland says the decision Friday by
the Freie Deutsche Jugend to abandon the party could threaten the
youth group's future.
   Another Communist-run daily, the Berliner Zeitung, offered East
Germany's harshest criticism to date of the Czechoslovak party,
saying it was paying ``the bitter price for the grave errors of the
past.'' The commentary traced the troubles of the party leadership
in Prague to refusing political reforms and to ``the illusory,
risky business of trying to choke the call for democracy with
police clubs 10 days ago.''
   East German police also dealt violently with protesters in early
October as an initiat response to pro-democracy demosntrations.
Now, authorities say they're investigating police brutality.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>HUNGARY</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Results are incomplete on the first free vote in more than 40
years of Communist rule, but the ruling Socialist Party says
Hungarians have decided to postpone presidential elections until
after a new democratic Parliament can be elected. With 91 percent
of Sunday's vote counted, an opposition-backed referendum trails
49.8 percent to 50.2 percent, but officials expect the referendum
to pass after all votes are counted.
   The opposition wants a delayed presidential vote, saying it
needs time to mount a successful campaign.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>SOVIET UNION</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party daily Pravda prints a 2{-page compilation of
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's thoughts on the future of
socialism and his reforms, in which he endorses socialism with a
``human face'' _ the slogan used by the Czechoslovak progressives
toppled by a Soviet-led invasion in 1968.
   In the Sunday article, Gorbachev says achievements attained
under capitalism, like ``equality of all before the law'' and
general prosperity, should not be dismissed because of ideology.
   Legislators give final approval to a plan putting the small
Baltic republics on the road to economic autonomy from Moscow next
year and possibly issuing their own currencies.
</TEXT>
