<FILEID>AP-NR-11-27-89 1216EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Asia-Refugees     11-27 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Asia-Refugees,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>Repatriation of Vietnamese to Begin in February or March</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The forced repatriation of Vietnamese boat people
from Hong Kong camps will begin by February or March, the Foreign
Office said Monday.
   Foreign Minister Francis Maude would not confirm or deny a
report in the Financial Times of London that the repatriation will
begin by Christmas and that Britain has agreed to pay Vietnam $620
for each person on the first airlift.
   The Financial Times, quoting Vietnamese officials in Hanoi, said
the first repatriations probably would be on a 120-seat Boeing 737
chartered by the Hong Kong government. It said Hong Kong also was
considering chartering larger aircraft or troop carriers, and
passenger liners capable of carrying up to 1,000 passengers.
   The repatriation ``has to start before the sailing season starts
again in February or March,'' Maude said on BBC radio. ``Last year
no fewer than 32,000 people arrived in Hong Kong from Vietnam. We
cannot possibly tolerate that happening again.''
   Britain says most of the 56,000 people sheltered in Hong Kong
have not fled political or religious persecution, but simply are
seeking a better standard of living than that available at home.
   Each is being screened in accordance with standards set down by
the Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for refugees.
Only 13,000 have been declared genuine refugees.
   Referring to U.S. objections to Britain's plans for forcible
repatriation, Maude said the United States ``has agreed that there
is nowhere for these people to go other than back to Vietnam.''
   Asked whether Britain would be relieved if another country
offered to take 5,000 or 10,000 of the boat people, he replied:
``There would still be 30,000 to 35,000 left. There are no takers
for these people. ... There has been unanimous agreement in the
international community that there is no place for these people to
go other than back to Vietnam.''
   The Foreign Office has said Britain would likely pay
compensation to the boat people it sends back so they can buy tools
and seeds. It has said the sum would be similar to the $600 paid to
boat people who go home voluntarily.
   So far, fewer than 400 people have returned voluntarily to
Vietnam.
</TEXT>
