<FIRST>r a PM-PottyTrainingDeath     11-27 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Potty Training Death,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Social Workers Offered $100 Fine in Abuse Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BARTOW, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three of four state social workers charged
with failure to report suspected abuse before the potty-training
death of a toddler would pay only a $100 fine under a deal offered
today by prosecutors, attorneys said.
   The offer by prosecutors would avoid jail sentences for the
three, who were each charged with misdemeanors Aug. 31 in the case
of 2-year-old Bradley McGee.
   The boy died of a brain hemorrhage after his mother and
stepfather punished him for soiling his diapers by dunking him
head-first into a commode, police said.
   An investigation revealed that the child was released to his
parents' custody despite warnings by a foster parent of the
possibility of abuse.
   The plea agreement was offered to Kenneth Houk, a state program
administrator, supervisor Judy Ross and caseworker Shirley DuBoise;
each was charged with failing to report child abuse, a misdemeanor.
   Caseworker Margaret Barber was charged with aggravated child
abuse, a felony charge, in addition to the misdemeanor charge. She
was not offered any deal, attorney said.
   A conviction on the felony could mean a jail sentence of up to
five years; conviction on the misdemeanor could be punished by up
to 60 days in jail.
   Assistant State Attorney John Aguero acknowledged that a plea
agreement was in the works, but would not comment on the details.
   A pre-trial hearing on the case was set for Dec. 28.
   The mother and stepfather of McGee have been charged with
first-degree murder in the July 28 death of the child.
   Earlier this month, the Florida Legislature passed a bill
allocating $39 million to pay for more caseworkers to prevent child
abuse.
</TEXT>
