<FILEID>AP-NR-11-27-89 1231EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Honduras-Elections 1stLd-Writethru   11-27 0732</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Honduras-Elections, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0481,0753</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Claims Victory In Honduran Vote</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with later results, election officials
saying their count may have to begin again because of computer problems.
Pickup 5th pvs, `Minor parties...;' Insert graf after 18th, `Also at...'
with results from other races. Pickup 19th pvs, `More than...;</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition presidential candidate
Rafael Leonardo Callejas, a U.S.-trained economist, claimed victory
today in Honduras' third free election this decade. Official
returns were incomplete.
   ``I invite my opponents to join me in reconstructing Honduras,''
Callejas, of the National Party, told a cheering crowd at election
headquarters early this morning.
   In unofficial returns representing about 67 percent of
precincts, Callejas had 595,807 votes, or about 50.2 percent, to
526,110, or about 44.5 percent, for Carlos Flores of the governing
Liberal Party.
   Official returns, much slower in coming out, showed a narrower
lead. After announcing Callejas had 44,538 votes to Flores' 43,383
late Sunday, the electoral tribunal announced that its computer had
crashed and it closed for the night.
   ``We may have to start over,'' said Mario Arnaldo Barrientos, a
member of the tribunal's information committee, in an interview at
the computer center today. He said the problem may have been
related to the large volume of incoming results, but tests were
being run.
   Minor parties took the rest of the vote; only a plurality was
needed to win.
   ``If the present trend continues, Callejas will win,'' said
Liberal Party treasurer Jorge Roberto Maradiaga in a telephone
interview. ``The people will regret this.''
   If Callejas takes office on Jan. 27 for a four-year term, he
will become the first opposition candidate to take power in a
peaceful vote in 57 years.
   The winner faces grim problems in this underdeveloped nation of
about 5 million _ a stagnant economy, an unpayable debt and wars in
two bordering countries, El Salvador and Nicaragua. On Sunday, El
Salvador suspended relations with Nicaragua and accused it of
arming leftist Salvadoran guerrillas.
   ``In this violent Central America, where the youth of our
neighbors is spilling its blood, the people of Honduras have given
a `yes' to peace and a `no' to blood,'' Callejas said in an earlier
victory statement at party headquarters Sunday night.
   Callejas, like Flores, has made it clear that he wants
U.S.-supported Contras fighting Nicaragua's Sandinista government
to leave Honduras, but he also fears Honduras will alone have to
deal with getting rid of the Contra fighters if U.S. aid stops.
   He offered no new ideas for achieving that end during the
campaign. On Sunday he called for Central American presidents to
``reconstruct'' the peace process in the wake of El Salvador's
decision to break with Nicaragua.
   He also said he would be willing to accompany Azcona to any
summit that might take place before Jan. 27.
   Callejas has promised to privatize government-owned companies,
cut government spending and open the nation to foreign investment.
   The International Monetary Fund has suspended loans on Dec. 1
because Honduras has refused to negotiate over payments on old debt.
   Honduras owes $3.2 billion, most of it to international
institutions, and the United States is holding up $70 million in
fiscal aid until Honduras makes an arrangement with those
institutions.
   Callejas, 46, comes from a landowning family and was trained as
an agricultural economist at Mississippi State University.
   He attributed the election's results to ``hard work and the
desire for change'' and pitched his campaign against the government
of President Jose Azcona Hoyo, saying eight years of Liberal
government had only made things worse.
   Also at stake were three vice presidential posts, a 130-seat
unicameral congress and 289 mayoralties. Voting was by party slate,
with no ticket splitting allowed.
   The Nationalists appeared to be gaining a congressional
majority, and National Party candidate Nora Melgar claimed victory
in the capital of Tegucigalpa.
   More than 2.2 million people were registered, but voting was
concentrated at relatively few locations and some people had to
travel long distances.
   Turnout was nevertheless heavy and observers reported few
irregularties.
   ``The problems don't appear to systematically favor one side or
another,'' said an observer for the Organization of American States.
   The last time there was a party-to-party transition came in
1933, when Tiburcio Carias Andino of the National Party took over
from Liberal Vicente Mejia Colindres. Carias didn't allow another
vote until 1948.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
