<FILEID>AP-NR-11-27-89 1246EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-HomeSales     11-27 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Home Sales,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Existing Home Sales Remain at Highest Pace in Nine Months</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Existing-home sales last month remained steady
at their highest level since January, a real estate trade group
said Monday, and analysts expect single-digit mortgage rates to
sustain sales well into the new year.
   The National Association of Realtors said sales of existing
single-family homes totaled a seasonally adjusted annual rate of
3.52 million, the same as September's revised rate and the highest
since January's 3.55 million rate. The September rate was 1.2
percent above August's 3.48 million sales.
   The Realtors' survey, falling mortgage interest rates and an
earlier government report of a 12 percent increase in new housing
starts in October make ``things look somewhat brighter for the
housing market in the future,'' said economist Rob Rosenblatt of
the Mortgage Bankers Association.
   Rosenblatt and the Realtors' chief economist, John A. Tuccillo,
predicted that mortgage rates will remain low into next year, with
Rosenblatt suggesting they could fall as low as 9 percent by early
next spring.
   ``Overall, home financing conditions probably will stay quite
favorable in the months ahead,'' Tuccillo said.
   Rosenblatt also said he expects October's new home sales to post
a sharp rebound from September's 14 percent drop, which analysts
said resulted from a spike in mortgage rates to above 10 percent.
   Fixed-rate mortgages fell steadily from 10.10 percent to 9.82
percent during October, according to the Federal Home Loan Mortgage
Corp., and had dropped to 9.74 percent by last Wednesday.
   ``Lower rates are sustaining sales at a healthy clip,'' said
Realtors' President Norman D. Flynn. ``Buyers priced out by higher
rates earlier this year are in the market now.''
   For a year, the Federal Reserve pushed interest rates higher to
battle inflationary pressures. But, since last spring, the central
bank has been gradually easing its grip on credit, allowing
mortgage rates and a variety of other consumer and business loan
rates to fall.
   The Realtors said the national median price for an existing
single-family home was $92,100, down $2,200 from September. The
median price means that half the homes sold for more, half for less.
   The West posted the only increase in sales in October, up 3.4
percent to an annual rate of 610,000 units, the Realtors said. The
median price for a home in the West was $142,200, $5,400 below the
September cost.
   Sales were unchanged from September's 1.34 million unit rate in
the South, where the median home price was $83,400, down $1,000
from September.
   Sales declined 1 percent in the Midwest to 980,000 and dropped
1.7 percent to 580,000 units in the Northeast. The median price for
a home in the Midwest was $70,900, $1,300 below the September
price, and $143,300 in the Northeast, $2,400 below the September
cost.
</TEXT>
