<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Honecker     11-27 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Honecker,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Honecker a `Broken Man,' Bodyguard Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Erich Honecker is ``a broken man'' since his
ouster as East German leader last month, his bodyguard said Monday.
   ``For him the world has fallen apart,'' said Gen. Guenter Wolf,
speaking to reporters at the secluded Wandlitz residential area
oustide East Berlin.
   Honecker, 77, was ousted Oct. 18 amid a massive exodus of East
Germans heading West and large anti-government demonstrations. He
was replaced by Egon Krenz.
   Wolf, speaking to reporters outside Honecker's house in the
wooded compound, said the former leader was ailing.
   Krenz also has said that Honecker is too ill to be questioned by
a party commission conducting a disciplinary investigation of
Honecker. He underwent two gall bladder operations during the
summer, and his wife has said he still has not recovered fully.
   Reporters caught a glimpse of Honecker on the upper floor of the
house, apparently talking to a visitor and looking through some
papers.
   Wolf said Honecker and his wife, Margot, who lost her post as
education minister shortly her husband's ouster, want to move from
Wandlitz before the end of the year.
   ``But it's not easy to find a suitable apartment for old men and
their families in East Berlin,'' Wolf said. ``Otherwise, this place
would be empty already.''
   The Communist Party elite for years has lived in the walled,
heavily guarded compound. But Krenz moved to a modest house in East
Berlin one week ago and said other leading party officials would
follow.
   Authorities allowed East German journalists to tour Wandlitz for
the first time last week, and on Monday allowed a tour of the
compound by Western reporters.
   Other ousted Politburo members still live in Wandlitz, including
former economy chief Guenter Mittag and former propaganda chief
Kurt Hager.
   Krenz's new leadership has blamed Honecker and Mittag for
plunging the country into the crisis and Mittag has been kicked out
of the party. The investigation of Honecker could result in his
ouster from the party.
   A special parliamentary commission also is investigating charges
of abuse of power by the former leadership.
</TEXT>
