<HEAD>White House Lauds Czechs' Steps Toward Democracy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House today applauded the democratic
steps taken by Czechoslovakia and urged the communist country to
follow the path Poland and Hungary are taking toward political and
economic renewal.
   The statement came as millions of Czechs took part in a two-hour
strike to press their demands for political freedoms.
   The country's communist rulers, faced with demonstrations by
hundreds of thousands of Czechs, have purged several members of
their Politburo and promised to lift most censorship. Communist
premier Ladislav Adamec held unprecedented talks Sunday with
opposition leaders.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said in a statement:
   ``Over the weekend the public demand for basic freedoms has
spread to another country in Eastern Europe, Czechoslovakia. The
Czechoslovak people have spoken loudly and clearly. They have
firmly expressed their desire for political freedom, including free
elections, free speech and the release of political prisoners.
   ``President Bush commends the Czechoslovak people for both their
courage and for their restraint. Their example is an inspiration to
free peoples everywhere,'' the spokesman said.
   Fitzwater added:
   ``The new regime has spoken of a dialogue with the Czechoslovak
people. The United States hopes that dialogue will commence at an
early date and that Czechoslovakia will follow the path explored by
Poland and Hungary to political and economic renewal.
   ``It is time for this once-proud democracy and strong economy to
be reborn. That opportunity now exists and we hope the leaders of
Czechoslovakia will seize it and move rapidly and peacefully toward
free elections.''
