Romanians.'' Referring to changes occuring in other East European
countries, Michael said ``it is time that the same happens in
Romania.''
   But, responding to a question, he said he doubted that a popular
uprising was likely soon in Romania because of the government's
repressive nature.
   Michael said he and his family have received death threats
periodically since he went into exile in 1948, and that such
threats have intensified. ``They certainly come from the secret
police,'' he said.
   Michael, who holds a British passport and lives near Geneva, has
said he considers his abdication as not valid because he acted
under coercion from the Soviet-installed government.
