<FIRST>r a AM-HauntingWords     11-27 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haunting Words,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Official's Spending Endorses Topless Bar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convention recruiter who had hoped public
fervor was quelled when he promised city officials he would no
longer take clients to a posh topless nightclub has learned that
signs of the controversy still exist.
   Jordy Tollett, director of the Houston Civic Center, has found
his explanation has become a giant endorsement for the nightclub.
   Printed in large yellow letters at the bottom of a
40-foot-by-20-foot billboard for Rick's restaurant and bar are
Tollett's words: ``Our clients want to go there!''
   In September, The Houston Post reported Tollett had spent more
than $2,000 entertaining male clients at the club with funds from
the Greater Houston Visitors and Convention Bureau _ 75 percent of
which come from taxes. The Civic Center department, with a $26
million budget, oversees the George R. Brown Convention Center,
among other facilities.
   In his defense, the mayoral appointee said he was wooing
convention business.
   ``Unfortunately, Rick's just happens to be something that's very
well-known,'' Tollett said at the time. ``They (clients) just
wanted to go there. I couldn't say, `You can't go there.' ''
   Tollett was admonished privately by Mayor Kathy Whitmire and
subsequently promised never to take clients there again.
   Since then, Rick's owners have spent $6,000 a month for three
billboards.
   The billboard also features endorsements from Robin Leach of
``Lifestyles of the Rich &amp; Famous'' and ``Penthouse Magazine.''
   But the appearance of Tollett's words has embarrassed him and
angered Mark Henry, the new president of the convention bureau.
   ``I have limited sympathy for their discomfort because I'm very
proud of my business and the city of Houston's better off for it,''
said Robert Watters, an owner of Rick's.
   But there were sore feelings over the matter at Rick's, which
boasts an expensive and sophisticated atmosphere.
   ``It's the same old hypocrisy thing,'' said Watters, who said
the convention bureau solicits its membership each year and
privately acknowledges that conventioneers flock to the cabaret.
But, he said, publicly, bureau officials complain about the club.
   He said at first, the endorsement was attributed to the bureau
itself. But after Henry called several times to complain, Watters
said the sign was changed to reflect Tollett as author of the
statement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891127-0098 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-27-89 1315EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Jordan     11-27 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jordan,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>King Pledges Greater Freedom for Jordanians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMAL HALABY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Hussein told the new parliament Monday
he will legalize political parties and relax martial law, opening
the way to more freedom in Jordan after the first national
elections in 22 years.
   ``There is no doubt the current national assembly represents a
new phase in our life,'' Hussein said in a speech inaugurating the
legislature.
   He spoke of commitment to freedom of thought and expression in
Jordan, where political parties have been banned for 33 years, and
martial law has been in force for 22, since the Arab-Israeli war of
1967.
   Hussein, dressed in a black ceremonial military uniform, said he
would have a royal commission draft a national charter defining
``the basic central concepts of nationalism and patriotism.''
   ``The emergence and activity of political organizations will be
based on these concepts and definitions,'' he told a joint session
of the 80-member Chamber of Deputies, elected by the people, and
the 40 members of the Senate, appointed by the king.
   Parties were banned in 1957 after a coup attempt by leftists,
but the government permitted them to run candidates in the
elections last month.
   The king said the government would try to strengthen civilian
courts ``to reduce gradually the need for martial and special
courts.''
   Loss of the West Bank to Israel in 1967 made blocked national
elections until Hussein renounced sovereignty over the territory
last year, in favor of the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Martial law gives the government sweeping powers, forbids
unlicensed gatherings and restricts legal rights. It has been
applied to a range of matters from murder cases through bank
scandals to allegations of price-gouging by vegetable vendors.
   In their campaigns, most legislative candidates demanded
legalization of parties, an end to martial law and greater press
freedom.
   Islamic fundamentalists, who won the largest bloc of seats, were
divided in the first major action of the new Chamber of Deputies,
splitting their vote for speaker.
   Suleiman Arar, former interior minister and an ally of the king,
defeated a candidate of the conservative Moslem Brotherhood 44-36
with the aid of more- liberal Islamists.
   The government must work with the Islamists to get its
legislation passed, Hussein can block any law he dislikes, either
in the Senate or by veto. He also has the power to dissolve the
legislature and rule without it.
   Conservative Islamists _ the Brotherhood and their allies _
campaigned for more social welfare programs, a crackdown on
corruption, stricter observance of Islamic law and the destruction
of Israel. They seek bans on liquor and the levying of interest,
and greater segregation of sexes.
   Prominent Islamist deputy Yousef Azem said Monday, however, the
fundamentalists hope to ``cooperate with the government for the
interest of the country and its citizens.''
   Hussein repeated his support for the PLO and its steps toward
peace, and declared to the assembly: ``Israel is the side that
continues to thwart progress.''
   About half the 3 million people in Jordan are Palestinians, many
of them refugees displaced by the creation of Israel.
   ``The only solution to the Palestinian problem lies in
recognizing Palestiniian rights on Palestinian national soil,'' the
king told the legislators.
   He reported progress toward overcoming problems caused by its
foreign debt of $8.3 billion, which led in April to four days of
rioting in southern Jordan. Hussein reorganized the government and
moved toward democratic reform after the riots.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
