<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Poland     11-27 0707</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Poland,0729</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moscow Recognizes Poland's Right to Own Political System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LENINGRAD, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union formally recognized
Monday the right of Poland to evolve a political system free of
outside interference.
   In a joint declaration at the end of a five-day visit to the
Soviet Union by Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki, head of Poland's
non-Communist government, the two nations expressed their concerns
about a reunified Germany.
   The Soviet Union and Poland welcomed the developing democratic
landscape in East Germany but voiced the conviction that the
relationship between the two Germanys must respect the border
between East and West.
   Maintenance of the border has ``an unusually important
significance for the maintenance of stability and security in
Europe,'' the statement said.
   Both the Soviet Union and Poland suffered deeply from Nazi
aggression during World War II and Polish officials have expressed
concern about the potential emergence of a powerful unified Germany
in the heart of Europe.
   Mazowiecki's election Aug. 24 ended more than 40 years of
Communist rule in Poland and has contributed to opening the way for
other East European nations to introduce democratic reforms.
   The moves have the support of President Mikhail S. Gorbachev,
who says they are necessary for Eastern Europe to catch up to the
West.
   Mazowiecki, a former Solidarity editor and close adviser to Lech
Walesa, exchanged views on the East bloc with Soviet leaders,
concluding that the process of democratization is allowing the
nations the freedom to choose their own form of government.
   Poland and the Soviet Union are to develop ``as before, their
alliance relations on the basis of mutual trust, recognizing the
free choice of the development of the social-political path, full
reciprocity and non-interference in internal affairs,'' it said.
   ``They are determined to develop good-neighborliness and
alliance relations between the two countries on the basis of new
political thinking,'' the document said.
   It formalized the Soviet guarantee that it would not interfere
in the internal affairs of its East European neighbors, even if
they chose to reject communism.
   The primary Polish aim of the visit was to gain public Soviet
acceptance of the new government, many of whose members come from
the Solidarity free trade union movement.
   Apart from developments in Eastern Europe, the visit focused on
economic issues, the question of historical ``blank spots'' _ parts
of history the communist authorities have rewritten or suppressed _
and the situation of the estimated 2 million Soviet citizens of
Polish origin.
   The statement said the Soviet Union was ready to maintain its
supply of oil and raw materials in exchange for delivery of Polish
manufactured goods.
   Both sides agreed to coordinate future development of trade as
Poland converts its centrally planned economy to a market-oriented
system. Trade with the Soviet Union accounts for one-third of
Poland's foreign trade.
   The hopes of many Poles for a clear Kremlin statement on the
massacre of 4,300 Polish officers in the Katyn forest in the Soviet
Union during Wold War II were not met.
   Most Poles and Western historians believe the officers were
murdered by the Soviet secret police in 1940. The Soviet Union says
the Nazis were guilty.
   On Sunday, Mazowiecki made an emotional visit to the forest,
about 250 miles west of Moscow, and took part in a Roman Catholic
Mass in honor of the dead.
   The statement said both countries believe that clarification of
historical issues _ and above all, the Katyn question _ would
strengthen their ties. The two countries also agreed to create
conditions to improve the situation of Poles living in the Soviet
Union.
   The Poles will be guaranteed the right to develop schools to
teach the Polish language, create their own cultural societies and
be able to attend church services.
   Mazowiecki traveled to Leningrad on Monday to meet with
intellectuals in a city with which Poland had close ties before the
1917 Bolshevik Revolution.
   Some of Poland's most prominent poets, lawyers and political
activists of the 19th century studied in St. Petersburg, as the
city was known then, and Mazowiecki's advisers say he is interested
in reviving the ties.
   Mazowiecki was applauded warmly by about 50 intellectuals when
he encouraged them to develop independent political and cultural
initiatives.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891127-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-27-89 1340EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Uruguay     11-27 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Uruguay,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>President-elect Seeks Coalition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTEVIDEO, Uruguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Luis Lacalle, whose
National Party gained ground in Congress but fell short of a
majority, said Monday he would try to form a coalition government.
   His center-right National Party won 37.4 percent of the votes in
Sunday's general elections, compared with 28.8 percent for the
Colorado Party, which has been in power; 19.7 for the Broad Front;
and smaller totals for five other parties, according to official
count of 90.4 percent of returns.
   The Colorados also are center-right. The Broad Front alliance is
leftist and includes the Socialist Party, Communist Party and
former Tupamaro guerrillas who tried to overthrow a Colorado
government in the late 1960s.
   Lacalle's party was was projected to win 12 of the 30 Senate
seats and 38 places in the House of Deputies, which has 99 members.
   He said meetings will be held this week to build ``a governing
coalition, which we ... consider indispensible for the correct
functioning of the government.''
   Taking a customary morning stroll beside a beach near his home,
the president-elect said: ``I'm aware the task that awaits me is
very difficult ... but I always knew that.''
   President Julio M. Sanguinetti of the Colorados and Jorge
Batlle, the party's unsuccessful presidential candidate, indicated
support for a coalition.
   Sanguinetti, who was barred by law from seeking another term and
remains in office until March 1, said he did not ``see any
particular inconvenience'' in opening the coalition to the Broad
Front.
   Liber Seregni, the Front's presidential candidate, told Lacalle
his party ``is disposed to talk ... in the search for solutions our
country needs.''
   Uruguay, a small South American republic between Argentina and
Brazil, suffers from chronic inflation and economic stagnation.
   A modest recovery occurred during Sanguinetti's five-year term,
but wages and pensions remain low, the cost of living has risen 82
percent this year and the gross national product of $8 billion
improved by only about 1 percent.
   Public services in Uruguay were a model for the continent in the
1950s. Now schools and hospitals are deteriorating, and electricity
and gas are so expensive many people must use them sparingly.
   Lacalle, a 48-year-old senator, pledged in his campaign to
curtail inflation by negotiating a reduction of Uruguay's $6.3
billion foreign debt, thus freeing more public funds for other
uses. He proposes to sell some of the 3 million ounces of gold
reserves and invest the money to earn interest.
   Areas in which talks with the Broad Front may founder are the
foreign debt and Lacalle's plans for deregulation and getting the
government out of an economy it has directed for decades.
   Labor and leftist political parties oppose paying the debt, and
fear selling state enterprises over to private owners may result in
pay cuts and the loss of jobs.
   ``We say we don't have to pay one cent'' of the foreign debt,
said Julio Marenales, a founder of the Tupamaros. ``That money
should be invested in the country.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891127-0103 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-27-89 1342EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-Summit-Bush     11-27 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Summit-Bush,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Will Consider Reducing U.S. Troops in Eastern Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A reduction in U.S. troops in Western Europe
is an option President Bush will bring to his meeting with Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, a White House spokesman said today.
   But press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said the administration
does not want to ``get the cart in front of the horse'' in
discussing any such reductions prematurely, and before consulting
with NATO allies.
   ``Any actions that we would suggest or recommend would only be
with the appoval of our allies,'' Fitzwater said.
   Fitzwater said Bush also will raise with Gorbachev at the Dec.
2-3 shipboard summit the issue of continued shipments of
Soviet-bloc arms to leftist rebels in El Salvador.
   He noted that among weapons found over the weekend in the debris
of a crashed Nicaraguan aircraft destined for a Salvadoran rebel
base ``were Soviet-made SA-7 missiles.''
   Bush ``will tell President Gorbachev that the introduction of
surface-to-air weapons in a guerrilla war in El Salvador is a
dangerous escalation of a conflict, contrary to high-level Soviet
assurances,'' Fitzwater said.
   ``Despite Soviet promises to use their influence for peace in
Central America, it is clear the Sandinistas and their Marxist
allies continue to destabilize the legitimate democracies of the
region,'' Fitzwater said.
   Conventional force reduction in Europe will remain the subject
for ongoing international negotiations, Fitzwater said.
   Noting the nation's tight budget posture, he said, ``if there
are arms control agreements or changes in military posture...that
allow us to make defense spending cuts, we certainly are willing to
do that.''
   Responding to reports that the upheaval in Eastern Europe could
lead to major cuts in U.S. defense spending, Fitzwater said:
   ``Certainly the two presidents in Malta will talk about arms
control and military force structure. Those discussions will bear
on future decisions about changes in our own military posture.''
   Asked whether Bush planned to bring troop cuts to the table at
Malta, Fitzwater said: ``The president will have in his mind all of
the options that are available to him. The president wants to be in
a postion to discuss the situation with the Soviet leader, to be
responsive and to be in a positon to then go to our allies and say,
here's what our discussion produced.''
   ``As the president considers the budget, as he considers all of
the options that might be available to us as a result of the
reduction of Soviet force strength, there are all kinds of numbers
floating around,'' Fitzwater added.
   The events in Eastern Europe are expected to dominate next
weekend's superpower summit, although Bush and Gorbachev also will
be discussing arms control, trade and regional conflicts from
Nicaragua to Afghanistan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
