<FIRST>r a AM-TurtleEggs     11-27 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turtle Eggs,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Turtle Or Egg? Appeal Should Answer Question</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When does a sea turtle egg become a
turtle? That twist on the old chicken-egg debate is at the heart of
an appeal by a man convicted of poaching more than 1,000 sea turtle
eggs.
   Some species of sea turtles are endangered, so state law treats
offenses against turtle life harshly.
   James A. Bivens was found guilty in March, sentenced to 60 days
in jail and fined $500, plus $100 for each egg taken from the beach
at John D. MacArthur Beach State Park on Singer Island, for a total
fine of $109,300.
   Bivens' appeal claims the fine is illegal because state law
allows a judge to levy a $100 fine ``per unit of marine life.''
   ``An egg, according to the facts of nature that an egg becomes a
life when it is hatched ... is not a turtle,'' Bivens' lawyer wrote
in court briefs. ``Hence the universal question: Which came first,
the chicken or the egg?''
   Oral arguments on the appeal are set for Jan. 18.
   Prosecutors and wildlife officials say the argument is a new one
to them, but ridiculous nevertheless.
   ``If you kill an egg, it's not going to become a turtle,
obviously,'' said Barbara Schroeder, sea turtle recovery
coordinator for the state Department of Natural Resources.
   But Bivens thinks the laws concerning turtles are too vague.
   ``Just as a chicken is not an egg (and when one eats eggs for
breakfast, one is not eating chicken), a marine turtle is not a
turtle until it comes out of its egg,'' Assistant Public Defender
Louis Carres wrote on Bivens' behalf.
   ``Most of (the eggs) don't even turn into turtles,'' said the
public defender, although he did not know what percentage of sea
turtle eggs usually hatch.
   Carres did not defend his client's motive, saying he was
``probably up to no good'' when caught with the eggs and should
have been fined $500 for having them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
