<FIRST>u a PM-BoxOffice     11-27 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Box Office,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Back to Future' Propels Box Office to Record Weekend</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The time travel saga ``Back to the Future Part
II'' hit warp speed in a record Thanksgiving holiday weekend,
gobbling up nearly $40 million at the box office to eclipse
previous champ ``Rocky IV.''
   According to estimates released today, total movie house
revenues for the fall period hit an all-time record of $832
million, up 24 percent from last year.
   ``Back to the Future Part II'' had the biggest non-summer
weekend ever. ``Rocky IV'' punched up $32 million over the same
holiday period in 1985.
   Leading the five-day holiday box office, according to Exhibitor
Relations Co., were Eddie Murphy's ``Harlem Nights'' (estimated
$15.3 million), ``Look Who's Talking'' ($10.8 million), ``The
Little Mermaid'' ($9.9 million) and ``Steel Magnolias'' ($9.4
million).
   ``All Dogs Go to Heaven'' was estimated to have revenues of $6
million, ``Prancer'' had $4.6 million, ``Dad'' claimed $3.9
million, ``The Bear'' earned $3.1 million and ``Crimes and
Misdemeanors'' had ticket sales of $2 million.
   Last Wednesday, ``Back to the Future Part II,'' starring Michael
J. Fox, opened to $7 million in what Universal Pictures called the
biggest ever Wednesday box-office gross.
   The previous box office champ on an opening Wednesday was
``Rocky IV'' with a $5.7 million turnstile take.
   ``Back to the Future'' also opened over a five-day holiday
period _ the extended Fourth of July weekend in 1985 _ and its
five-day opening gross was $14.9 million. The film ended up doing
$350 million worldwide.
</TEXT>
