<DOCNO> AP891127-0118 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-27-89 1442EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-East-NATO     11-27 0675</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East-NATO,0696</SECOND>
<HEAD>Europeans Urge U.S. to Maintain Commitment to Europe</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite the easing of East-West
tensions, European defense ministers Monday urged the United States
to remain strongly committed to the defense of their continent.
   The ministers, representing European members of the 16-nation
North Atlantic Treaty Organization, welcomed the rapid changes in
Eastern Europe but cautioned the allies should keep up their guard.
   ``We ... need to be careful,'' said Spanish Defense Minister
Narcis Serra, who is president of the Eurogroup, made up of a dozen
European nations in NATO.
   The statement comes amid reports the United States is planning
sharp cuts in the Pentagon's budget. The reports have raised
concern about the United States' future ties to Europe.
   U.S. Defense Secretary Dick Cheney arrived in Brussels from the
Netherlands for Tuesday's start of a two-day meeting of alliance
defense ministers at NATO headquarters.
   Serra said the European defense chiefs put off until Tuesday
discussions of possible U.S. defense cuts, wanting to hear
first-hand from Cheney.
   In the Netherlands, Cheney promised that no U.S. troops would be
pulled out of Europe without an East-West agreement on reducing
conventional, or non-nuclear, arms, the Dutch government said.
   Dutch Defense Minister Relus ter Beek quoted Cheney as saying he
expected the conventional arms talks in Vienna to be followed by
another round of disarmament negotiations between NATO and the
Soviet-led Warsaw Pact.
   ``Withdrawal of ... American troops from the European continent
will take place (only) after a (conventional arms) agreement,'' ter
Beek said after meeting with Cheney.
   According to the Dutch official, Cheney said the Pentagon's
budget-cutting work would not affect the Western alliance before a
conventional arms pact was reached. The Defense Department is
drawing up plans to cut planned increases in U.S. military spending
by $180 billion in the 1992-94 budget years.
   The United States has 340,000 troops based in Western Europe,
most of them in West Germany.
   Cheney was quoted in U.S. newspapers as saying that more cuts in
American forces in Europe than now under consideration may be
possible because of the ``erosion'' of the Soviet military threat.
   The stunning political reforms in Eastern Europe have prompted
talk of a reduced _ or different _ role for the military alliances
in the future.
   But the European defense ministers cautioned that ``periods of
rapid change and transformation may ... carry risks of their own.''
   Even after promised arms reductions by the Soviet Union and its
allies, the Warsaw Pact still will ``retain military forces which
substantially outnumber those of the alliance in Europe,'' the
ministers said.
   The presence of U.S. nuclear and conventional forces in Europe
``remains vital to the security of Europe, just as Europe's
security is vital to that of North America,'' the ministers said.
``We therefore reaffirm the high priority that we attach to the
continuing U.S. commitment to the defense of Europe.''
   They called for a successful conclusion of the conventional arms
talks. ``We need a prompt agreement at Vienna,'' Serra said.
   NATO officials expect an accord to be completed next year.
   Such an agreement would lead to hefty cuts in tanks, armored
troop carriers and artillery pieces in an area spanning the
Atlantic to the Ural Mountains in the Soviet Union. President Bush
in May urged big reductions in U.S. and Soviet troops stationed in
Europe by 1993.
   The European officials also said there have been improvements in
some contributions to NATO. The subject has been a sore point in
the alliance. Critics in the United States complain that some
European members don't do enough for the Western defense while
Washington does too much.
   But the Europeans said Italy, Luxembourg, Norway, Spain and
Britain have increased planned defense spending, and that Spain for
the first time agreed to contribute to NATO's military budget.
   NATO defense ministers meet twice a year in their role as the
Defense Planning Committee. France, which is outside NATO's
military structure, does not attend. Iceland, which has no armed
forces, has observer status.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
