<FIRST>u i PM-Colombia-Plane 8thLd-Writethru   11-27 0671</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia-Plane, 8th Ld-Writethru,a0568,0691</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Leads with 21 grafs to UPDATE with caller to radio station claiming
drug traffickers bombed jet. Pickup penultimate graf, `The last...</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jet With 107 Aboard Crashes Outside Bogota; All Reported Dead</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Colombian jet with 107 people aboard
crashed in flames today outside Bogota, and officials said all on
board were killed. A caller to a radio station claimed drug
traffickers bombed the jet.
   Witnesses reported seeing the Avianca Airlines Boeing 727-100
explode before it plummeted to the ground at about 7:15 a.m.
   Hours later, a person called the Caracol radio network and said
The Extraditables, a shadowy group linked to the Medellin drug
cartel, bombed the plane because police informants were on board.
   The caller did not identify himself, and there was no way to
authenticate the claim.
   The airline refused comments on reports the plane exploded. Col.
Edgar Leal, chief of national police in the state, said
investigators had not found anything to indicate a bomb blew it up.
   Avianca spokeswoman Patricia Duarte said the plane crashed into
a hilly area just south of Bogota, the capital. She said all 101
passengers and six crew members were killed.
   RCN radio quoted officials at the control tower at El Dorado
Airport in Bogota as saying the jet crashed three minutes after
taking off for the city of Cali, 190 miles to the southwest.
   It quoted the flight controller as saying the pilot reported
everything normal seconds before communication with the plane was
lost.
   ``The plane exploded in the air and then fell to the ground and
caused a huge explosion,'' said Jairo Alba, who witnessed the
crash. Alba, interviewed by the RCN radio network, said the jet was
destroyed.
   Radio stations quoted other witnesses as saying they saw smoke
pouring from one of the three engines and then seeing the plane
blow up.
   ``The plane was flying along when suddenly it exploded, broke in
two and fell in flames and smoke,'' witness Alfonso Moreno told
Radio Caracol.
   ``I heard explosions and I thought there was some problem with
transformers in the electrical station, but I looked up and saw a
plane explode in the air, and bodies and pieces of luggage were
falling,'' another witness Mario Vasquez, said.
   The chief of the Civil Aviation Authority, Col. Jorge Gonzalez,
said the crew of a Colombian air force jet flying in the area saw
two explosions on the jet. He spoke to the radio networks RCN and
Caracol.
   No one on the ground appeared to have been hurt, Gonzalez said.
   Caracol said Flight 203 just cleared the southern edge of this
city of 6 million when it crashed. Witnesses said wreckage was
scattered for miles.
   The nationalities of those on board were not immediately known.
   Boeing Co. spokesman Tom Cole in Seattle said the company would
send investigators to Bogota to help determine the cause of the
crash.
   The government of President Virgilio Barco declared war on drug
traffickers in August, and since then there have been several
bombings and other attacks, but none on a large scale.
   The person who claimed responsibility on behalf of the
Extraditables said six informants on the plane were targeted
because they gave police information that led to the discovery of
the hiding place of the head of the Medellin cocaine cartel.
   The Extraditables take their name from the U.S. Justice
Department's list of 12 Colombian drug suspects most wanted in the
United States. The head of the Medellin cartel, Pablo Escobar, tops
the list.
   Last week, authorities raided a jungle hideout, and Escobar
reportedly came close to capture.
   The last major passenger jet crash in Colombia occurred March
17, 1988, when an Avianca Boeing 727-100 crashed into a mountain
near the northern city of Zulia, killing 138 people.
   On July 27, 1985, an air force transport plane crashed in the
Amazon jungle, killing all 74 people aboard. The military plane was
carrying passengers because of a airline strike.
</TEXT>
