<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--WaterCrisis     11-27 0141</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Water Crisis,0144</SECOND>
<HEAD>Workers Search For Water Leak In Rural Water System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MERIDIAN, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers tested pipelines of a 22-mile
rural water system Monday to find a leak that has deprived as many
as 400 families of water for nearly two weeks.
   Army National Guardsmen and volunteer firefighters trucked in
water Sunday for use by customers of the
Nellieburg-Tanglewood-Suqualena Water Association in west
Lauderdale County after county officials declared an emergency,
said Sandy Metrolis, director of the Lauderdale Emergency
Management agency.
   ``They obviously have a problem on the system somewhere. It
seems to be a gigantic leak,'' Metrolis said Monday.
   More than 5,000 gallons of water for drinking and household use
were trucked into the area.
   The leak apparently sprang Nov. 14, officials said; water
pressure declined steadily until some homes lost all water about a
week ago.
</TEXT>
