<DOCNO> AP891127-0124 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-27-89 1512EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Scotus-Glance     11-27 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Glance,530</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are highlights of actions
taken Monday by the Supreme Court.
   
   HANDICAPPED
   
   The court refused to let public schools cut off educational help
to severely handicapped children even though they may not be able
to benefit from such services.
   The court, without comment, rejected an appeal by a New
Hampshire school district ordered to help a profoundly retarded
13-year-old boy.
   The case has attracted widespread attention from educators and
state and local government officials nationwide who supported the
appeal by the Rochester, N.H., school district.
   At issue is the duty of states and local school officials under
the federal Education for All Handicapped Children Act, which
provides federal aid and in turn requires programs to help such
children.
   The case is Rochester, N.H., vs. Timothy W., 89-515.
   
   HOMELESSNESS
   
   The court dealt a blow to New York City's campaign to halt the
spread of homelessness by refusing to revive a local law
successfully challenged by developers.
   The justices, without comment, left intact a ruling that a law
banning conversion or demolition of single-room-occupancy housing
unconstitutionally confiscates private property.
   The cases are New York City vs. Seawall Associates, 89-388;
Coalition for the Homeless vs. Seawall, 89-403; Wilkerson vs.
Seawall, 89-552.
   
   STRIP SEARCH
   
   The court turned down an appeal by Kentucky law enforcement
officials sued for strip-searching a woman charged with operating
her car without proper registration or insurance.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that
strip-searching people accused of minor traffic violations
generally violates their rights.
   The case is Frey vs. Masters, 89-576.
   
   PIT BULLS
   
   The court left intact an Overland Park, Kan., ordinance
restricting the ownership and possession of ``pit bull dogs.''
   The justices, without comment, refused to hear arguments that
the city ordinance is unconstitutionally too vague.
   The case is Hearn vs. Overland Park, 89-412.
   
   WESTIES
   
   The court rejected appeals by four men and a woman convicted for
their roles in a hoodlum gang, the Westies, in the Hell's Kitchen
section of New York City.
   The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that the five
were prosecuted fairly.
   The cases are Coonan vs. U.S., 89-379; Ritter vs. U.S., 89-5497;
Bokun vs. U.S., 89-5512; McElroy vs. U.S., 89-5601.
   
   TELEPHONE BILLS
   
   The court rejected an appeal by a telephone company ordered to
notify customers, along with their monthly bills, of their right to
join a lawsuit against the company.
   The court, without comment, let stand a Colorado ruling that the
company's free-speech rights are not violated by requiring it to
include such notices with its bills.
   The case is Mountain States Telephone vs. District Court of
Denver, 89-531.
   
   KENNEDY
   
   The court rejected the appeal of a Hollywood, Calif., man who
sued the Senate Judiciary Committee over its unanimous vote last
year favoring Justice Anthony M. Kennedy's appointment to the high
court.
   The court, without comment, let stand rulings that threw out
Monte Lee's lawsuit.
   Kennedy did not participate in considering Lee's appeal or in
the court's action today.
   Lee's suit contended that the committee's 14 senators violated
his rights by voting for Kennedy without investigating allegations
of wrongdoing against the nominee.
   The case is Lee vs. Biden, 89-591.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
