<FIRST>r a PM-Donor-Lewis 1stLd-Writethru a0508 11-27 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Donor-Lewis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0508,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carl Lewis Pleads for Liver Donor for Woman</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Liver Transplant, Bjt</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with woman receiving liver. No pickup.</UNK>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman was in critical condition today
after nine hours of surgery to receive a new liver, following a
plea from track star Carl Lewis to help locate an organ.
   Hospital officials said Wendy Marx was in critical but stable
condition following the emergency liver transplant surgery. Doctors
put her on a national organ donor list last week, and by
Thanksgiving grouped her among patients most urgently in need of
transplants.
   Marx, 22, went into surgery at 10:30 p.m. Sunday for the
transplant that ended about 7:30 this morning, said Pacific
Presbyterian Medical Center spokeswoman Julie Murray. Doctors began
monitoring her for signs of transplant rejection or infection.
   ``At this point, they (the doctors) were pleased with it,'' she
said. The liver came from an anonymous donor and it was not
immediately known if it was the result of Lewis' appeal.
   Lewis pleaded for the liver donor in a desperate attempt to save
Marx, the sister of a journalist who is helping to write Lewis'
autobiography.
   Earlier, Marx was clinging to life in a coma earlier and doctors
gave her 24 hours to live without the operation.
   Marx, the sister of Pulitzer Prize-winning journalist Jeff Marx,
had swelling on her brain and was likely to have irreversible brain
damage without an immediate liver transplant, doctors said.
   ``I am here to ask for help in saving a young woman's life,''
Lewis said.
   Lewis pleaded for a donor Saturday and stayed at the hospital
with the Marx family again Sunday, saying the case indicates the
``desperate need'' for organ donors throughout the nation.
   ``This has hit me like no athletic event ever has,'' said Lewis,
28.
   Marx suffered irreparable liver damage after contracting
hepatitis B several weeks ago and has been hospitalized for the
past week.
   Lewis, an Olympic gold medalist in 1984 and 1988, has been
active in support of a national donor network. Lewis and the Marx
family became elated about 10 p.m. Saturday when it seemed a donor
had been found. The liver, however, turned out to have been damaged
in a car accident.
</TEXT>
