<FIRST>u p PM-Wilder-VaVote 2ndLd-Writethru a0590 11-27 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wilder-Va Vote, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0590,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Coleman Seeks Recount in Virginia Governor's Race</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with official count, edit for transition;
picks up 5th graf, ``Coleman had until ...''</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEAN McNAIR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican J. Marshall Coleman said today
he will seek a recount and contest the results of the governor's
race, which he narrowly lost to Democrat L. Douglas Wilder by less
than half a percentage point.
   In official returns certified today by the State Board if
Elections, Wilder received 897,139 votes to 890,285 for Coleman out
of nearly 1.8 million ballots cast for a margin of 6,854 votes, or
.38 percent.
   Coleman's announcement came about three hours before the State
Board of Elections announced the official results of closest
gubernatorial election in Virginia history.
   The unofficial returns from the Nov. 7 election had shown Wilder
defeating Coleman by 6,852 votes.
   Coleman said previously he probably would seek a recount if the
certified margin of Wilder's victory was less than one half-percent
of the 1.78 million votes cast, or about 9,000 votes.
   Coleman had until Dec. 7 to request a recount but today was the
deadline for contesting the election to the state Legislature
because of alleged irregularities.
   ``In an election as close as this one, irregularities which
would not ordinarily have a probable impact on the outcome assume a
greater importance,'' Coleman said in a letter to leaders of the
Democrat-controlled General Assembly.
   Susan Fitz-Hugh, secretary of the board of elections, said there
is no precedent for a statewide recount. She has declined to
estimate the length of time or cost of the recount, which would be
overseen by a panel of three judges headed by the chief judge of
the Richmond Circuit Court.
   Wilder has distanced himself from debate over whether Coleman
should accept the certified vote.
   ``We've said all along the ball is in the loser's court,''
Wilder spokeswoman Laura Dillard said.
   Wilder has proceeded with plans for his inauguration Jan. 13 as
Virginia's third straight Democratic governor, and has named a
transition team.
   The grandson of slaves and former state senator from Richmond
was elected lieutenant governor in 1985.
</TEXT>
