<FIRST>r a PM-HazelwoodTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0540 11-27 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hazelwood Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0540,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hazelwood Hearing To Get Under Way</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with hearing beginning; picks
up 10th graf, ``A federal ...'' ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prosecutor told a judge today he will
put officials on the stand to support the state's contention that a
former Exxon tanker skipper should not escape prosecution for
causing the nation's worst oil spill.
   At a pretrial hearing in the case of Joseph Hazelwood, state
Assistant Attorney General Leonard Linton Jr. said he planned to
call several Coast Guard officers and a state environmental
official as witnesses.
   Linton told Superior Court Judge Karl Johnstone that he also
planned to put on the stand residents of Ellamar, a Prince William
Sound village from which the Exxon Valdez was seen after it became
impaled on Bligh Reef.
   Hazelwood was captain of the 987-foot tanker when it ripped its
hull open on the reef early March 24 after leaving the Alaska oil
pipeline terminal at Valdez. The vessel spilled nearly 11 million
gallons of heavy North Slope crude oil into Prince William Sound.
   Shortly after the spill, Exxon fired Hazelwood, a veteran
mariner from Huntington, N.Y.
   Hazelwood, 43, is accused of reckless endangerment, operating a
vessel while intoxicated and negligent discharge of oil, all
misdemeanors, and three felony counts of criminal mischief.
   His trial is set for Jan. 22.
   Hazelwood's lawyers have said they would try to get his case
thrown out on claims of immunity, a flawed sobriety test and other
grounds.
   Defense motions included claims that Hazelwood received immunity
from prosecution when he reported his ship's grounding and the oil
spill the morning it happened. A law intended to encourage
self-reporting of environmental calamities such as oil spills
provides protection against self-incrimination, laywers contend.
   They say virtually every piece of evidence in the case against
Hazelwood grew from his report to the Coast Guard that the Exxon
Valdez was aground and leaking oil.
   Linton said, however, that discovery of the spill was
inevitable. He contends the position that Hazelwood's informing the
Coast Guard ultimately led to the evidence against him is
groundless.
   A federal judge in Fairbanks refused last month to block
Hazelwood's trial in state court.
   The oil blackened hundreds of miles of shoreline, killed tens of
thousands of birds and marine mammals and disrupted lucrative
fishing seasons. Exxon said it spent more than $1 billion on oil
spill claims and cleanup work, and state officials say the cleanup,
suspended for the winter, is unfinished.
   The case was moved from Valdez to Anchorage because of concerns
that publicity about the spill would make it too hard to find an
impartial jury. The port in south-central Alaska relies heavily on
the oil industry for jobs and also has commercial fishing interests.
   If convicted of the three felonies, Hazelwood faces a possible
maximum penalty of 10 years in prison and $100,000 in fines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
