<FIRST>r a AM-Carter-Ethiopia     11-27 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Carter-Ethiopia,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government and Rebels Have Agreed on Co-Chairman, Carter Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Ethiopian government and Eritrean rebels have
resolved a knotty issue in their preliminary peace talks by
inviting former Tanzanian President Julius K. Nyerere to be
co-chairman of future talks, said former President Jimmy Carter.
   Carter, who has been mediating the latest round of talks in
Nairobi, Kenya, said the negotiations almost broke down twice, but
``both sides got what they wanted by Saturday.''
   Carter commented to The Atlanta Constitution in an interview
published Monday.
   The decision to invite Nyerere to join him as co-chairman of the
main talks was the last of 12 agenda items for the preliminary
talks, he said.
   Delegates from the government and the rebel Eritrean People's
Liberation Front resumed talks last week in Nairobi after agreeing
on nine issues in Atlanta in September. Carter said the delegates
have now resolved the three remaining issues: a co-chairman, a
secretariat and observers.
   The nations that will be asked to observe future talks on ending
28 years of war will be named this week, when the preliminary talks
are expected to end, Carter said.
   He said Nyerere has been traveling in Asia and had not yet
responded to the requests from both delegations to participate, but
added that he expects Nyerere to accept the invitation.
   ``He has indicated in the past that he would if the invitation
came from both sides, and not just from me,'' Carter said.
   Carter flew through Sudan and Ethiopia on Sunday while the
negotiating teams took a break.
   Carter met with Sudanese President Omar Hassan Ahmed Bashir in
Khartoum for 90 minutes. Carter helped arrange preliminary peace
talks Dec. 1 between Bashir's government and southern rebels, but
he will not be directly involved.
   Carter and Ethiopian President Mengistu Haile Mariam discussed
the Nairobi talks in Addis Ababa. Carter also met with three
members of the Sudan People's Liberation Army, which is based in
Ethiopia's capital.
   Carter initiated the Ethiopian peace talks in Atlanta, and he
said Sunday that he was pleased with their progress. However, he
cautioned that trust is still lacking between the Ethiopians and
the Eritreans.
   ``There were a couple of times when the talks almost broke up
when one side or the other announced that they were leaving,'' he
said. ``There is still a lot of misunderstanding, a lot of
mistrust.''
   Carter said he cannot guarantee the success of the main
negotiations, but added: ``If I didn't think there was hope, I
wouldn't be spending my time out here.''
</TEXT>
