<HEAD>Oklahoma Couple to Get Bush's `Point of Light' Award</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Oklahoma City physician and his wife, both
inflicted with multiple sclerosis, were saluted by President Bush
on Monday as ``an inspiration to us all'' for their volunteer work
in running a free medical clinic.
   Bush said he was bestowing his second daily ``Point of Light''
award to Dr. William Hale and his wife, Sandy.
   Bush presented the first award to the Memphis Commercial Appeal
last Wednesday for articles spotlighting outstanding volunteers in
the community and said he would issue the recognition daily.
   John Galletta, a White House aide, said that, starting with the
Hales, a new recipient would be announced every day but Sunday.
   ``It is not an awards program as such,'' Galletta said. ``This
is just recognition. These programs are representative of
outstanding work being done throughout the country.''
   In a statement, the White House called Hale the ``driving
force'' behind the all-volunteer clinic that has operated from a
Baptist mission center in Oklahoma City for 15 years.
   The clinic, which is run entirely by volunteers and accepts no
government funds, has treated nearly 43,000 indigent people, the
statement said.
   ``After learning that some of their patients could not afford to
buy prescriptions, the Hales arranged for donations of medicine
from local pharmacies as well,'' it said.
   ``The president extends his deepest appreciation to the Hales
for their outstanding work. Their courage and determination is an
inspiration to us all.''
   The Hales will get a letter from the president praising them for
their work, Galletta said.
