<FIRST>r i AM-EC-East     11-27 0669</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-EC-East,0689</SECOND>
<HEAD>European Community Signs Trade Accord with Soviets</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT J. WIELAARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Community Commission said
Monday it has signed a trade and economic cooperation accord with
the Soviet Union that goes beyond similar deals signed in the past
14 months with Hungary, Poland and Czechoslovakia.
   The pact provides for a gradual lifting of import quotas on
Soviet industrial goods by 1995 and cites a dozen areas in which
the two sides plan to establish economic cooperation, an EC source
said.
   These include science and technology, banking, transport,
agriculture, environmental protection, energy, raw materials and
mining. The accord excludes trade in goods considered to be
sensitive militarily, according to the source, who asked not to be
identified.
   He said the agreement calls for reciprocity in trade benefits.
``That is the objective of this accord ... to get an effective
access to the Russian market for EC products,'' the source said.
   Officials could not give an assessment of the economic impact of
the agreement.
   EC trade with Eastern Europe is small. It totaled $56 billion in
1987, the last year for which complete figures are available.
EC-Soviet trade that year was only $24.6 billion.
   The agreement with Moscow was reached after five days of talks
between EC Commission and Soviet negotiators. It must be approved
by the 12 EC states and the European Parliament.
   That is a formality, however, given the EC's interest in
increasing economic links with Eastern Europe and getting access to
its market of 390 million consumers.
   The Soviet accord, negotiated in about four months, is the
fourth the EC has signed with an East European nation in just over
a year.
   It signed a trade and economic cooperation agreement with
Hungary in September 1988; a more limited deal with Czechoslovakia
covering only trade in manufactured goods was signed in December
1988; and an agreement with Poland was signed Sept. 19.
   These accords follow a June 25, 1988, agreement under which the
EC and the Moscow-led Comecon trade bloc, after years of ignoring
one another, signed a mutual recognition agreement in Luxembourg.
   The EC on Monday also widened market access for farm and textile
goods from Poland and Hungary. Through the measure, which will be
in effect only during 1990, the EC suspended import quotas for the
two countries that are fixed through the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade, the world trade body.
   In a statement, the 12 EC foreign ministers said the one-year
lifting of quotas was an ``exceptional solution to an exceptional
problem'' and represents no change in the EC's overall position on
quotas in world trade.
   The move follows an EC decision Nov. 6 to increase market access
for industrial goods from Poland and Hungary.
   The EC foreign ministers were notified of the agreement with the
Soviet Union but did not discuss the issue in depth.
   The Soviet accord goes further than any other deal the EC has
signed with an East European nation, notably by subjecting nuclear
energy safety and mining to economic cooperation, sources said.
   Also on Monday, European Community External Relations
Commissioner Frans Andriessen called developments in Czechoslovakia
of the last week ``a cause for profound rejoicing throughout
Europe.''
   ``Political reform and economic liberalization in Czechoslovakia
form part of a wider process which, for the first time in more than
40 years, offers to future generations the prospect of a Europe no
longer riven by division,'' he said.
   EC officials said it was too early to speak of a widening of the
accord with Czechoslovakia.
   The Commission is still negotiating trade and economic
cooperation agreements with Bulgaria and East Germany. Talks with
East Germany are in an ``exploratory'' stage but will likely be
speeded up by next week's visit to East Berlin by Andriessen.
   East Germany has asked the EC for an accord on trade and
economic cooperation. The EC has broken off talks for closer
economic ties with Romania in view of its human rights record.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891127-0137 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-27-89 1653EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SanFrancisco-Tourism     11-27 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-San Francisco-Tourism,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>San Francisco Mayor Launches Tourism Campaign in Chicago</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLIFF EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People who left their hearts in San Francisco can
come back for them anytime, the city's mayor said Monday. The city
by the bay, hit by a killer earthquake Oct. 17, is eager to welcome
visitors again.
   ``I came to say `Thank you' to the people of Chicago and the
people of the Midwest,'' Mayor Art Agnos said at a news conference
with Chicago Mayor Richard M. Daley during his first stop on a
three-city tour.
   He said Chicago was the first city to send food after the
7.1-magnitude quake, which killed 67 people and caused $7 billion
in damages in the San Francisco Bay area.
   Daley, a friend of Agnos, sent Chicago-style deep-dish pizza,
cheesecake and beer, the visiting mayor said.
   Agnos said he also came ``to tell people here in the Midwest
that we're ready to offer the same kind of hospitality that San
Francisco is famous for.''
   Tourism, which is San Francisco's No. 1 business and generates
$3.4 billion a year, is still reeling from the effects of the
quake, he said.
   Tourism dropped off sharply after the quake, and is about 80
percent of normal, Agnos said.
   Media coverage of the quake focused on spectacular damage, and
has many potential visitors thinking the entire area was leveled,
he said.
   He noted that the San Francisco-Oakland Bay Bridge, which was
closed when a 50-foot section of its upper deck fell on the lower
deck, has reopened and that traffic is flowing normally.
   Agnos also said many people who live in the heavily damaged
Marina district returned home for Thanksgiving when electricity and
gas were restored six weeks ahead of schedule.
   However, San Francisco's homeless population has nearly doubled
because many of the hotels with single-occupancy rooms occupied by
low-income residents were destroyed, the mayor said.
   And the city's two elevated freeways will be closed for repairs
until at least June, he said.
   But everything else is back to normal, said Agnos, who plans to
spread the word in New York and Washington on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
