<DOCNO> AP891127-0138 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-27-89 1627EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Czech-Scene 1stLd-Writethru a0655 11-27 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czech-Scene, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0655,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prague's Biggest Industrial Factory Joins Peaceful Revolt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, ``Others greeted ...'' with 1 graf to CORRECT
reference when group started to earlier this month, sted 10 days ago.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Petr Varga's hands were almost
blue from the cold as he held up one of the hundreds of signs,
banners and flags rising from the human sea filling the street in
front of Prague's largest industrial plant.
   ``We have been waiting for this for years,'' said Varga, a
27-year-old mechanic. ``This is just wonderful.''
   He had been in a column of workers, many in stained overalls,
that poured into the street after sirens from two fire trucks
bedecked with the blue, red and white national flag sounded the
beginning of a two-hour general strike.
   The column joined tens of thousands filling the street to listen
to speakers addressing them from atop a flatbed truck.
   Signs called for free elections, an end to one-party rule and
free trade unions.
   Others greeted the Civic Forum, the opposition group that sprang
to life earlier this month after police brutally suppressed a
peaceful student demonstration.
   ``I never voted,'' said Varga, who said he makes about $350 a
month _ slightly less than the average pay of a blue-collar worker.
``I knew that these elections were always faked.''
   On top of the truck-turned-platform, workers mingled with
students and actors waiting to speak. Even three policemen wanted
to contribute.
   One after another, they called for a change in the system,
drawing rousing cheers and chanted slogans: ``Long live the
students!'' ``These are the demands of a free people!'' and
``Thanks to the Forum!''
   One worker demanded that all Czechoslovak Communists who helped
the Warsaw Pact invaders crush the ``Prague Soring'' reforms be
brought to trial.
   It was at the CKD plant, where Varga works, that the last
general strike was proclaimed two days after the invasion of Aug.
21, 1968.
   Jeers and shouts of ``Shame!'' went up when another speaker
cited the name of a CKD worker who was elected to the party's
ruling Politburo in a reshuffle of the leadership less than 12
hours earlier. ``He is not one of us!'' the crowd chanted.
   ``This is just the beginning,'' someone in the crowd said as the
rally ended with Czechoslovakia's national anthem.
   ``We will continue. Now we will go to Wenceslas Square for a new
demonstration. This is the 11th day,'' he said.
   ``It's fantastic,'' said a worker who identified himself only as
Martin. ``Imagine this comes after half a century of no freedom,
first under the Nazis and then under the Communists.''
   Martin said he went to the United States after the 1968 invasion
but returned a year later ``because I was homesick.''
   Flags were lowered from many windows of the drab apartment
blocks facing the 400-yard-long front of the plant, the largest of
the CKD group. Two men stood atop a building, swinging a flag
precariously close to the edge of the roof.
   ``Where is the people's militia?'' someone asked, referring to
the Communist Party's paramilitary force that had been guarding the
gates of all factories in recent days.
   At one point, they were officially reported to have been asked
to help police to ``maintain public order'' during the giant
demonstrations. ``Haven't seen them,'' was the answer from another
bystander. ``But they have sent word that they will never act
against the workers.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
