<DOCNO> AP891127-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-27-89 1702EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Honduras     11-27 0616</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honduras,0636</SECOND>
<HEAD>President-Elect Congratulated, Calls For Dialogue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rafael Leonardo Callejas, the
opposition National Party's winning presidential candidate, called
Monday for talks with members of the Liberal Party on solving
Honduras' economic crisis.
   ``The only way to solve the problems of inflation and
unemployment is to create an economy that's strong and
productive,'' said Callejas, who beat Carlos Flores of the
incumbent Liberals in elections Sunday.
   Callejas, a 46-year-old U.S.-trained agricultural economist,
also accepted congratulations from minor party candidates and the
U.S. Embassy on his victory. Flores did not make a concession
statement.
   Callejas' inauguration Jan. 27 will mark the first peaceful
transition of power to an opposition party in Honduras in 57 years.
   ``What Hondurans have accomplished should prove to be an
inspirational example to other peoples of the region who also seek
democracy,'' the U.S. Embassy said in an obvious reference to
neighboring Nicaragua.
   The problem of Central American peace will be one of the first
and most difficult to confront Callejas. The country borders El
Salvador and Nicaragua, and Honduras has long served as a base for
U.S.-supported Contras trying to overthrow the Sandinista
government.
   El Salvador broke relations with Nicaragua on Sunday over arms
smuggling to Salvador's leftist guerrillas, and Callejas said he
would be willing to participate in a Central American summit if
incumbent President Jose Azcona Hoyo is agreeable.
   Callejas has said peace is vital to his effort to attract new
foreign investment to Honduras _ there has been no significant new
investment in years _ but he suggested no new ideas during the
campaign.
   He has said he supports the presence of U.S. troops on training
missions for as long as Central America remains unstable.
   Other problems Callejas will face include high unemployment _
estimates put the figure at 1 million in a nation of 5.2 million.
   War, refugees, inflation, a $3.2 billion foreign debt on which
no payment has been made this year and an economy closed by
protectionism have all combined to leave Honduras one of the
poorest nations in the hemisphere, with a per capita annual income
estimated at $500.
   Callejas said in a radio interview Monday that he would not
devalue the lempira, which has been pegged at 2-1 against the U.S.
dollar since 1918, although the current black market rate is 4-1.
   However, Callejas said he would attempt to install a two-tier
system with a 2-1 rate for things like petroleum and medicine, with
a free or different rate for other trade.
   Callejas, a moderate conservative who admires President Carlos
Salinas de Gortari's efforts to modernize Mexico, has also promised
to decentralize the government, sell some state-owned companies,
cut the budget and create incentives for export and investment.
   Official vote totals were stalled by computer problems, but
unofficial vote totals gathered by radio and television showed
Callejas with a clear lead over Flores.
   With about 67 percent of the vote in, Callejas had 595,807
votes, or about 50.2 percent, to Liberal Carlos Flores' 526,110, or
about 44.3 percent.
   Callejas said he believed his party would take 69 or 70 of the
unicameral legislature's 130 seats, as well as the mayoralty ot
Tegucigalpa, the capital and largest city.
   The mayoralty of the second-largest city and commercial center,
San Pedro Sula, was in doubt, but a strong Nationalist showing
there showed how deeply Callejas had cut into the Liberals'
traditional strongholds.
   ``The Liberal Party didn't lose. The people of Honduras lost,''
said party treasuere Jorge Roberto Maradiaga.
   Flores, who reportedly was in San Pedro Sula, released no
statement Monday. His newspaper, La Tribuna, headlined ``Callejas
Claims Victory.''
   Below was another headline: ``Conservatives Also Win In
Uruguay.''
</TEXT>
