<FIRST>r a AM-RoadKill     11-27 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Road Kill,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eagles Spurn Road-Killed Deer at Arsenal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A project to feed bald eagles with deer killed on
the highways is failing because the eagles are too finicky, federal
officials say.
   The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service has been collecting mule deer
carcasses along highways, especially those close to the foothills
west of Denver, and bringing them to the Rocky Mountain Arsenal as
eagle food.
   But the bald eagles apparently are uninterested in the deer,
officials said, leaving the agency swamped with dead deer.
   ``We've got a third of a refrigerated semitrailer filled up, and
we're still averaging four deer a day from across the area,'' said
wildlife service biologist Mike Lockhart.
   Lockhart said the pilot project may have to be suspended. If so,
the business of disposing of road kills would fall back to county
crews, which typically dump the animals at landfills.
   The state wildlife division reports about 1,000 deer killed
annually on roads throughout the Front Range.
   Fish and Wildlife Service biologist Pete Gober in Lakewood said
Monday the project began in early November, when eagles arrive to
winter at the arsenal. It probably will continue as long as the
eagles stay, March, he said.
</TEXT>
