<FIRST>r a AM-PottyTrainingDeath     11-27 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Potty Training Death,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>Social Workers Offered $100 Fine In Potty Training Abuse Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BARTOW, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors proposed $100 fines Monday as
the total penalty for three state social workers accused of failing
to report suspected abuse before a toddler's death during toilet
training, attorneys said.
   ``This gives the appearance the state wants to give this case
away,'' said Nat White, attorney for defendant Shirley DuBoise. ``I
almost fell out of my chair when they made the offer.''
   Two-year-old Bradley McGee died July 28 after being repeatedly
dunked head-first into a toilet and pounded with pillows because he
soiled his diaper, prosecutors say.
   His mother and stepfather, Thomas and Sheryl Coe of Lakeland,
have been charged with first-degree murder, and the social workers
were accused of failing to act on earlier complaints the couple had
abused their son.
   Prosecutors offered the plea bargain Monday only to state
Department of Health and Rehabilitative Services program
administrator Kenneth Houk, supervisor Judy Ross and caseworker Ms.
DuBoise, who were charged with the second-degree misdemeanor Aug.
31 amid controversy over the boy's death.
   The misdemeanor charge carried a maximum penalty of 60 days in
jail.
   Another HRS caseworker, Margaret Barber, was charged with
aggravated child abuse in addition to the misdemeanor charge. No
plea offer was made to her, the attorneys said.
   As a result of the case, the Legislature earlier this month
allocated $39 million to pay for more caseworkers to prevent child
abuse.
   ``We make plea offers in cases every day. The fact that this is
a high-profile case makes no difference to me,'' said Assistant
State Attorney John Aguero, who refused to comment on the details
of the plea bargain.
   Any offer would have to be approved at a pre-trial hearing Dec.
28, Aguero said.
   Both White and Jack Wilkins, the attorney for Houk, said they
would advise their clients to take the deal only if it involves a
no-contest plea in which they do not have to admit guilt. Ms. Ross'
attorney, Glen Brock, was not immediately available for comment; he
was out of his office visiting clients.
   ``Even if it's a small fine, nobody wants this on their
record,'' Wilkins said.
   ``I think $100 is fair,'' White said. ``My feeling was that even
if they were found guilty, the judge would not be able to impose a
stiff sentence anyway.''
   Houk, Ms. Ross and Ms. Barber were temporarily suspended but
have returned to work. Ms. DuBoise quit her job Aug. 3.
</TEXT>
