<FIRST>r a AM-EconomicTextbook     11-27 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Economic Textbook,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Will Use UNL Prof's Economics Text</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A textbook used for introductory college
economics courses throughout the United States is being translated
into Russian for use in a nation looking for new economic ideas _
the Soviet Union.
   Campbell McConnell, professor of economics at the University of
Nebraska-Lincoln, wrote the popular textbook ``Economics'' in 1960.
In its 11th edition, the book has been translated into Portuguese,
Spanish, German and French.
   McConnell recently completed a foreword for the Russian
translation, which McGraw-Hill Book Co. expects will take two to
three years to complete. In his introductory comments, McConnell
addresses the reduction in the past two decades of the high
economic growth rates that characterized the Soviet economy after
World War II and acknowledges the vigorous responses of Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev. McConnell also reviews the role of
a competitive price system in achieving and maintaining an
efficient allocation of scarce resources.
   ``It is perhaps in providing an overview of the functioning of a
competitive price system that this Russian translation of my text
will be of most interest to Soviet students and academicians who
are involved in the new thinking,'' he writes.
   McConnell says he tried to make clear that the U.S. market
system is not without faults and that ``going to a market economy
may solve some of the Soviet problems, but it is not a panacea.''
   University spokesman David Ochsner said there is a client for
the book, but the arrangements were made by McGraw-Hill and he did
not know who the client was. Calls to the publisher were not
immediately returned.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
