<DOCNO> AP891127-0146 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-27-89 1702EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-Class Bjt   11-27 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Class, Bjt,0640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Talk of the Town: Is the Class System Dead?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The class system, that mysterious code the British
like to believe is uniquely their own, has suffered a double blow
in recent days.
   First comes a survey saying that Britons, for all their
fascination with accents, dress and good form, are no more
class-conscious than any other nation.
   No sooner has that shocking revelation been digested than a
schools association brandishes statistics to show that the old
school tie no longer binds.
   Only the other day Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher was telling
Parliament: ``The old class-based order is being replaced by one
based on merit, ability and effort. This is the new Britain _ the
Britain for the 1990s.''
   Appropriately enough, the grocer's daughter who leads the
Conservative Party made her remarks during the first House of
Commons session to be televised. Television, like income tax and
traffic jams, is one of the great levelers of class in Britain.
   ``British Social Attitudes,'' a survey published this month by
Social and Community Planning Research, an independent research
institute, finds that Britain is fairly average by most social
indicators.
   After studying data from Britain, Italy, Austria, Holland, West
Germany, Hungary, the United States and Australia, the study
concludes: ``Britain does not emerge as an especially
class-conscious or class-bound society. Such differences as there
are have been talked up, as much by British observers as by anyone
else.''
   Meanwhile, a survey for the Independent Schools Information
Service points to massive changes in the makeup of the so-called
public schools, the private institutions from Eton downward that
have long been regarded as bastions of the upper classes.
   The survey reports that only six percent of public school kids
attend the same schools as their parents, and that 41 percent have
parents who weren't educated in public schools.
   ``The myth of the old school tie has been finally nailed,'' said
David Woodhead, national director of the service. ``The picture
that emerges is of a highly critical body of parents, unfettered by
traditional loyalties or by prejudice.''
   And yet debate rages on as to whether Britain is a class-bound
nation. The Daily Telegraph calls it ``The Great British
Obsession,'' while another newspaper, Today, devotes two pages to
demonstrate that the old class divisions that were based on money
and family lineage are being replaced by snobbery, a game anyone
can play.
   In January, the newspaper The Independent commissioned opinions
from writer Emma Tennant and Eton headmaster Eric Anderson.
   Ms. Tennant said that ``despite appearances to the contrary,
social class still holds this country in its grip,'' while Anderson
argued the opposite.
   He wrote that class barriers were crumbling, and pointed to
studies showing that by the year 2000, 70 percent of all job will
require brains, not brawn, compared with only 30 percent in 1945.
   ``If the class system is a divisive force, it is not a very
effective one,'' he wrote. And even if some parents still chose
Eton just for the social cachet, ``we take the boy anyway in the
confidence that we can teach him better values.''
   The Duke of Westminster doesn't believe that Mrs. Thatcher, even
after 10 years in power, can break down all the conventions built
up over the centuries.
   ``The class barriers have been broken down to a huge extent,
although certain conventions are adhered to,'' he said in an
interview.
   Accent is still a great pigeonholer, but nobody watching BBC-TV
news can help being struck by the gallimaufry of regional accents
that predominate among its reporters, from chainsaw Ulster through
Edinburgh burr to Midlands twang. The plummy BBC voices of 30 years
ago would be laughed out of the studio.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891127-0147 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-27-89 1724EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Murphy     11-27 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Murphy,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lack of Funds Stalling Retarded Inmate's Release</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEG McENTEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lack of state funding is delaying
court-ordered freedom for a retarded man who has been confined for
31 years at a state hospital, attorneys said Monday.
   Bernt Murphy, a 51-year-old who has the mental capability of an
8-year-old, has a full-time job and is ready to move from a group
home on the hospital grounds to a private community group home,
according to Lisa Marcy of the Legal Center for the Handicapped.
   However, she said, the state Division of Handicapped Services
must approve a contract for Murphy's care at the home at an
estimated annual cost of $60,000.
   Murphy was declared psychotic and committed to the state
hospital in 1957 after he was ruled incompetent to stand trial on
rape and murder charges.
   Doctors at the hospital said in 1972 that he had been cured of
his insanity; however, the Utah Supreme Court ruled in June 1988
that Murphy was retarded, not insane, and must be allowed to return
to the community.
   A 12-member committee assembled by District Judge Pat Brian to
coordinate Murphy's rehabilitation believes he is now ready to
leave the hospital, Marcy said.
   ``He has exceeded everyone's expectations,'' she said. She told
the judge she had hoped to see Murphy leave the hospital by
Thursday.
   Murphy is working as a dishwasher and helper at a local cafe,
earning the minimum wage, she said.
   Brian said he would accept the committee's plan, but not before
Handicapped Services explained the delay. He set a hearing for Jan.
22 to review the case.
   Last February, Murphy was permitted to move into the group home
on the hospital grounds and take the job, as long as he wore an
electronic ankle bracelet while outside the hospital. Three months
ago, Brian allowed him to remove the bracelet.
</TEXT>
