<FIRST>r i AM-France-Scarf     11-27 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Scarf,0548</SECOND>
<HEAD>Council of State Rules Islamic Scarves May be Worn in School</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Council of State ruled Monday that Moslem girls
may wear Islamic scarves to school if it does not cause
disruptions, but the decision seemed unlikely to end the
controversy.
   The ruling by the council, France's highest administrative
authority, leaves it up to school authorities to judge on a
case-by-case basis whether the wearing of the ``hijab'' scarf
constitutes ``an act of pressure or provocation, of proselytism or
propaganda.''
   Education Minister Lionel Jospin had sought the ruling after
weeks of heated arguments.
   Wearing the hijab, which covers the hair, ears and neck, is not
incompatible ``with the principle of secularity in so far as it
constitutes the exercise of the freedom of expression'' and
religious belief, the council said.
   The principle of secularity in public schools has been the law
in France since the Roman Catholic church was officially separated
from the state in 1905. The latest controversy arose seven weeks
ago when three Moslem teen-agers in Creil, a town north of Paris,
refused to remove their scarves.
   The school principal, Ernest Chenieres, applied a 1937 law
prohibiting all religious symbols from school and denied the three
girls the right to attend class until they removed the scarves. The
girls refused and the issue became the center of a national debate.
   Similar cases arose in Marseille, Avignon, Montpellier and
Poissy and the arguments became linked to the issue of immigration,
particularly attitudes toward immigrants from Moslem countries of
North Africa.
   ``The Council of State has noted there can be no general and
absolute prohibition of the scarf,'' Jospin told reporters after
the ruling by the 90-member Council. He said he would circulate new
guidelines to schools.
   ``It is a debate that touches on freedoms so it should not be
regulated in a rigid way from on high,'' he said.
   Both conservatives and communists criticized the ruling.
   Saida Chella, a 17-year-old high school student in Avignon who
left school in October because the principal refused to allow her
to attend classes wearing a hijab, said: ``Starting tomorrow
morning, I will go to school ... with my scarf. The principal can't
refuse me that.''
   Alain Juppe, secretary-general of the conservative Rally for the
Republic opposition party, said the socialist government lacked the
courage to pass a new law clarifying the matter and was dumping the
problem back on the schools.
   ``If the law is not clear enough, it (the government) must
present Parliament with legislation that would clarify the
situation,'' he said.
   Andre Lajoinie, head of the communist group in the National
Assembly, said the government was ``backing away from the principle
of secularity.''
   Bruno Megret, No. 2 man in the extreme-right National Front that
has campaigned for years on an anti-immigration platform, said:
``The question being posed is not that of neutrality of schools,
but that of the colonization of France.''
   The National Education Federation, France's largest teachers'
union, said the council's ruling was ``a return to square one.''
   It said the ruling interpreted existing law, but teachers were
seeking precise regulations that would ``guarantee the secularity
of public service education.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
