<DOCNO> AP891127-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-27-89 1916EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ABA-DeathAppeals     11-27 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ABA-Death Appeals,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bar Group Calls For Streamlined Death Penalty Appeals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American Bar Association task force Monday
called for streamlining death-penalty appeals, but said even its
proposed changes would allow a convicted killer to fend off
execution for six years.
   The task force's lengthy report offered generally less severe
reforms than those proposed by a committee appointed by Chief
Justice William H. Rehnquist earlier this year.
   For example, the ABA task force recommendations would require
states to pay for qualified lawyers to represent death row inmates
for all their appeals.
   Civil liberties lawyers had denounced the Rehnquist-appointed
committee, led by retired Supreme Court Justice Lewis F. Powell,
for failing to assure the competence of such lawyers.
   The ABA task force report said assuring qualified lawyers not
only ``assures fairness, but also avoids unnecessary delays in the
process.''
   The report recommends imposing a one-year deadline for someone
whose murder coviction has been upheld on direct appeal in state
courts to seek federal court help. Powell's committee has
recommended a six-month deadline.
   No such deadline exists now, and the average time between
someone being sentenced to death and actual execution is over eight
years.
   The ABA task force report has been sent to Congress, where it
joins the Powell committee report. The task force report will be
presented to the ABA's policy-making House of Delegates at its
February meeting.
   Ronald A. Klain, chief counsel to the Senate Judiciary
Committee, was quoted by The National Law Journal as saying he
expects the task force report to be ``a very, very seriously
considered document.''
   The committee's chairman, Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., already has
proposed legislation that adopts some of the Powell committee's
recommendations.
   There are more than 2,200 convicted murderers on death rows
across the nation, but only 119 executions have occurred since the
Supreme Court reinstated capital punishment in 1976.
   The task force said its year-long study was aimed at shortening
the total time for reviewing death-penalty cases, but noted that
``some reasonable amount of time is still indispensable for a
thorough consideration of the issues.''
   ``We should no longer see the aberrant case that is still in
litigation after nine or 10 years,'' the report said, (but) it
would be unrealistic to expect the ... review process will take
less than approximately six years'' if all available appeals are
pursued.
</TEXT>
