<FIRST>r a AM-FishermenLost     11-27 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fishermen Lost,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>Search For Missing Lobstermen Intensifies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Intensified searching for the five crew members of
a lobster boat netted nothing Monday despite reports of three flare
sightings in 12 hours, officials said.
   At sea, 200 miles off Martha's Vineyard, five jets and two
cutters spent the day zeroing in on the 25-square-mile area of
rotary current where the flares had been pinpointed.
   Hope remained that the crew of the 72-foot Heidi Marie may be
alive and floating in relatively friendly Gulf Stream water.
   The steel-hulled lobster boat out of Stonington, Conn., and its
crew _ Mark Middleton, 33; and Ray Gould, Arthur Banks, Ray Morris
and Michel Hare, all in their 20s _ has been missing officially
since Wednesday. But officers at the Coast Guard's command post
began tracking distress signals for a week.
   On Friday, the day after a Thanksgiving Day storm raged through
the Northeast, rescuers turned up a floating radio beacon and
fishing markers bearing the Heidi Marie's name.
   Hopes dimmed over the weekend as searchers scoured tens of
thousands of miles under good conditions.
   ``We'd been looking for something the size of a Volkswagen in an
area the size of the state of New Hampshire,'' Lt. Paul Wolf said.
``We were getting to the point where we'd exhausted any chance of
finding anything on the surface of the ocean.''
   Then overnight Sunday and into Monday morning white flares were
sighted on three occasions, galvanizing searchers.
   Several fishermen at the docks on Connecticut shores refused to
talk about their friends. The dockmaster said only: ``Everyone here
is on edge, the families and the fishermen.''
   ``Safety is always on your mind,'' said Robert Cale, a
Stonington native who has recently gone back to lobstering. ``I've
lost cousins, a lot of people around here have lost relatives to
the sea.''
