<FILEID>AP-NR-11-27-89 1743EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-EastGermany     11-27 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East Germany,0638</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Germany Criticizes Czechoslovakia for Resisting Reform</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist leaders of East Germany, who
were late and reluctant themselves in embracing change, said Monday
the Czechoslovak party is paying ``the bitter price'' of resisting
reform.
   Pressure for more rapid change at home continued. In Leipzig, a
center of the reform movement, 200,000 activists marched and a
rally speaker demanded a referendum on German reunification.
   Some demonstrators carried placards for German unity and the
issue dominated the weekly Leipzig rally for the second Monday in a
row.
   The East German leadership resists reunification, but has
mentioned as an alternative a vaguely phrased idea of confederation
with West Germany.
   Officials in Bonn, the West German capital, said Chancellor
Helmut Kohl had a plan that called for several intermediate steps
leading to reunification.
   They said he would present it to Parliament on Tuesday. ZDF said
Kohl planned to discuss the formula with President Bush by
telephone.
   Government spokesman Hans Klein said Kohl might go to East
Germany for a summit Dec. 19, but would not decide until the
Communist Party congress scheduled to end two days earlier.
   In an interview with Bild, a mass-circulation newspaper in West
Germany, Mayor Wolfgang Berghofer of Dresden gave a gloomy
assessment of prospects for the East German party.
   ``The people have already taken our power away,'' Bild quoted
him as saying. ``The leading role of the Communist Party is already
history.''
   Berghofer has been mentioned as a possible challenger to party
chief Egon Krenz, who will seek re-election at the December
congress.
   Communist leaders criticized the 2.3 million-member Freie
Deutsche Jugend youth group for leaving the party, but reserved
their harshest comments for hard-liners in Prague.
   ``Undoubtedly, a storm is raging on the Vltava,'' the party
newspaper Berliner Zeitung said, referring to the river that runs
through the city. ``It is bringing the Czechoslovak Communist Party
the bitter price for the grave errors of the past.''
   It criticized the hard-liners for clinging to ``the heresy that
amid the radical reforms in economics, in the political sphere,
everything could stay as it was.'' The paper cited ``the illusory,
risky business of trying to choke the call for democracy with
police clubs ten days ago.''
   Freie Deutsche Jugend, the traditional stepping stone to success
for Krenz and other members of the leadership, announced Friday it
no longer wanted to be the ``helper and fighting reserve'' of the
party.
   The front-page editorial was the harshest East German criticism
of its Warsaw Pact ally to to date.
   East Germany stopped police repression of public protest in
early October, and reform ideas have gained momentum since.
   Berghofer, 46, is not a member of the Central Committee or
ruling Politburo, but has become prominent among reform-minded
Communists because of the way he handled unrest last month in
Dresden.
   He was quoted as telling Bild only ``two or three well known
names, or perhaps none'' will remain in the leadership after the
party congress and ``the Communists will become only one party
among many.''
   For 40 years, the Communists have claimed to get more than 99
percent of the votes in elections. Berghofer predicted the true
count in free elections would be less than 20 percent.
   Elections have been promised for late next year or early 1991.
   Democratic Awakening, an opposition group, said Monday it would
establish itself formally as a political party at a convention Dec.
16-17 in Leipzig. The party congress is schedled for Dec. 15-17 in
East Berlin.
   Democratic Awakening has about 10,000 members and is considered
more conservative than the largest opposition group, New Forum, to
which more than 200,000 people belong.
</TEXT>
