<HEAD>Former Interior Minister Dead at 89</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with three grafs with further on cause of death. Picks
up graf 3 pvs, `He entered ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunnar Hedlund, long-time leader of the
Swedish Center Party and former interior minister, has died at age
89.
   Hedlund died Sunday after a long illness. The cause of death was
not given but both the newspaper Aftonbladet and news agency TT
said it probably was heart failure.
   Hedlund was known for his quick wit, voiced in a heavy northern
accent.
   He entered parliament in 1942 representing the Farmer's Party,
and became party leader in 1949. Two years later he led his party
into a coalition government with the Social Democrats and took the
post of interior minister.
   In 1957, the Farmer's Party left the government, but Hedlund
remained popular. In his last election as leader in 1970, the
party, which had changed its name to the Swedish Center Party, won
almost 20 percent of the vote, making it the largest party in
opposition.
   After leaving politics, Hedlund made a second career as chairman
and manager of several forestry companies.
