<HEAD>Clashes Reported in Georgian Republic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight people were injured in clashes between two
ethnic groups in the Soviet republic of Georgia during the past two
days, a local journalist reported Monday.
   An editor of the Georgian news agency Gruzinform, who refused to
identify himself, said ethnic Georgians and Ossetins fought near
Tskhinvali, about 60 miles northwest of the capital Tbilisi.
   Local police blocked roads to Tskhinvali and the city itself was
quiet, he said.
   He said informal Georgian groups planned to meet in Tskhinvali
last Saturday, but loaded buses and trucks blocked their way and no
meeting took place. The ethnic clashes broke out later, the editor
said, adding that the agency had no details on the planned rally or
on the cause of the clashes.
   The Ossetians are one of the many small ethnic groups populating
the Caucasus republic that has been a trouble spot this year.
   Clashes between the Georgians and Abkhazians have been
especially violent, but the Ossetians and the Meskhetian region
also felt tensions.
