<FILEID>AP-NR-11-27-89 1935EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Press     11-27 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Press,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Editors Agree on Press Code</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The editors of Britain's national newspapers said
Monday that in an attempt to ward off regulatory legislation, they
have agreed to a code of press behavior.
   Pressure has been building to rein in the more sensational
tabloids as concerns have risen about the invasion of privacy.
   In a joint declaration, the editors said they realized
newspapers needed to improve self-regulation.
   The code, to be published in each paper, calls for an appointed
ombudsman to police press behavior and safeguard standards of
accuracy and fairness.
   ``They will have the power to question journalists and editorial
executives. They will have the right to require prompt publication
of statements of correction and to have their findings published,''
the code said.
   It sets out rules requiring a justifiable public interest if
private lives are intruded upon, and a fair opportunity for reply.
   Mistakes must be corrected promptly and with appropriate
prominence.
   Newspapers will be barred from paying criminals for their
stories. The purchase of stories from figures in the news is common
in British journalism.
   The editors said they hope the declaration will stop moves in
Parliament to curb invasion of privacy. Editors said they believe
legislation could hamper access for journalists.
   On Nov. 20, publisher Robert Maxwell fired Wendy Henry, the
editor of his tabloid The People, for publishing photographs of
Princes William and Harry and of entertainer Sammy Davis Jr. that
he found not acceptable.
   The princes' parents, the Prince and Princess of Wales, objected
to the photos as intruding on the children's privacy and as a
security concern.
</TEXT>
