<FILEID>AP-NR-11-27-89 1848EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0618 11-27 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0618,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>Islamic Fundamentalists Call for More Attacks on Soldiers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RECASTS first 2 grafs, picks up 3rd `Also Monday' and ADDS 1
graf with two killed by Israeli-backed militia in south Lebanon prison,
minor editing throughout. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Islamic fundamentalist group praised the
killing of Israeli soldiers and urged that more be ambushed in the
occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The call for more attacks was in a leaflet distributed in the
West Bank by the fundamentalist group Hamas, or Zeal. It called for
a strike Dec. 9, as the third year of the uprising in the occupied
lands begins.
   Also Monday, Arab reports said a Palestinian shot and wounded in
the neck by Israeli troops during a clash in April died of his
injuries in Egypt.
   Bassam Arrada Al-Shaer, 21, of the town of Rafah in the Gaza
Strip, on the Egyptian border, died Sunday of respiratory
complications at El Salam Hospital.
   His death raised to 617 the number of Palestinians killed by
Israelis in the uprising. Forty-two Israelis have died, including
nine soldiers.
   At least 151 Palestinians have been killed by fellow Arabs since
the rebellion began in December 1987, most on suspicion of
collaborating with Israel or for prostitution or drug dealing.
   The latest death came Monday, when a Palestinian man identified
as Mahmoud Abu al-Saoud, 22, died of wounds suffered five days
earlier when he was attacked by masked Palestinians armed with axes
in the West Bank town of Nablus, Arab reports said.
   They said he was accused of attempting to blackmail Palestinian
women with photographs and videotapes.
   A leaflet distributed Monday in Nablus by the PLO-backed Unified
Leadership of the Uprising urged an end to the internecine killings
and ordered groups operating outside the leadership's direction to
stop their activities.
   The leaflet called for ``stopping the campaign to kill those who
went astray'' and said all means must be used to convince people
cooperating with Israel to change their ways.
   The appeal followed weekend reports that groups of Palestinian
activists with assault rifles had begun patrols in Nablus to search
for suspected collaborators. Nablus has been the scene of 23 of the
collaborator killings, and most have been blamed on gangs operating
outside the leadership's control.
   In the Hamas leaflet, the group said it had mobilized ``several
thousand strugglers'' to step up the uprising.
   It praised the shooting deaths of two Israeli soldiers in
mid-November and the deaths of two others earlier this year and
called for ``the increased use of ambushes against Israeli soldiers
in the third year of the uprising.''
   Hamas has been outlawed by Israel, and more than 250 of its
leaders have been arrested, according to the army. Some are
awaiting trial on charges including involvement in the kidnapping
murders of the soldiers and other security offenses.
   Also Monday:
   _ Israeli soldiers rounded up more than 150 Palestinians for
questioning in the West Bank town of Bethlehem after empty bottles
were thrown at an army patrol, the army said. Four of those
questioned were detained.
   _ A pipe bomb exploded outside a bank in a shopping center in
the northern Israeli city of Haifa while police tried to dismantle
it. Two parked cars were damaged, but there were no injuries,
police said.
   _ Members of Israel's surrogate militia in south Lebanon shot to
death two men during a prison riot by inmates demandin to be
included in a proposed exchange with Israel, military sources said.
Reports from Lebanon said a Palestinian group, not identified, had
offered to trade the body of an Israeli soldier for Arab prisoners.
