<FIRST>r a AM-Butcher-Wilson     11-27 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Butcher-Wilson,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Bankers Plead Guilty in Massive Fraud Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Onetime Tennessee financial wizard Jake
Butcher and a close associate pleaded guilty Monday to two counts
of a federal indictment accusing them of defrauding an Orlando bank
of $3.9 million.
   The plea-bargain agreements in the complex case were entered
before U.S. District Judge G. Kendall Sharp shortly before the two
men were to have gone on trial.
   Butcher, who until 1983 headed a financial empire of 28 banks in
Tennessee and Kentucky, is serving a 20-year prison term for bank
fraud. He lost a race for Tennessee governor in 1978 and was the
chief organizer of the 1982 World's Fair in Knoxville.
   Also pleading guilty was Earl D. Wilson, who worked for Butcher
at the time the banks failed and is serving a 10-year sentence for
bank fraud.
   Butcher's attorney, Edward Garland of Atlanta, said related
conspiracy charges against his client would be dropped.
   The 89-page indictment alleged that Butcher and Wilson
orchestrated a scheme to obtain fraudulent loans from Florida
Center Bank in Orlando in 1984-85 using a series of ``straw
borrowers'' who would funnel the money to them.
   Butcher and Wilson could not obtain loans under their own names
because they had filed for bankruptcy and were either under
investigation or charged with bank fraud in Kentucky and Tennessee,
the government alleged.
   The grand jury charged that Butcher and the Wilsons paid former
bank president Joe F. Justice to make the loans. Justice, who was
not charged, is serving a 10-year sentence on similar charges in
another case.
   Florida Center Bank collapsed in 1986.
   Butcher faces a maximum term of seven years and a fine of up to
$500,000 on the two counts. Wilson faces a possible 10 years and a
fine of $500,000.
   Prosecutors will recommend that Butcher's time be served
concurrently with the sentence he is already serving in a prison in
Atlanta, Garland said.
   Butcher had faced a maximum sentence of 71 years in prison and
up to $4.5 million in fines if convicted in the Orlando case,
Assistant U.S. Attorney Ricardo Pesquera said.
   Pesquera would not elaborate on the plea-bargain arrangements
because he was prosecuting four other people in the same case, but
suggested he did not expect to call Butcher and Wilson to testify.
   Also pleading guilty to two counts in the 51-count indictment
issued in Orlando last August was Wilson's wife, Harriette, and
David Ogle and Allen Hicks, both of Knoxville, Tenn. Frederick C.
Streck of Atlanta, Ga. and Michael R. Allen of Altamonte Springs,
Fla., pleaded guilty to one count.
   The other defendants in the case generally served as fraudulent
borrowers, Pesquera told the jury in the case against the remaining
defendants, Harold and Margaret Artrip of Longwood, and James P.
Gresham and Sandra K. Chitwood of Atlanta.
   ``It was all part of the scheme and pattern,'' he said, asking
the jury to ``look at it as a jigsaw puzzle'' with all the pieces
fitting together as part of a plan to cheat the bank.
   Lawyers for Gresham, the Artrips and Ms. Chitwood argued that
all of the loans they obtained were legal and repaid to the bank
with interest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
