<FIRST>u a AM-DetroitNewspapers     11-27 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Detroit Newspapers,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Free Press and News Merge, Labor Contract Talks Resume</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY L. ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Detroit's two daily newspapers, the nation's
ninth- and tenth-largest papers, launched their long-stalled
partial merger Monday, as union and management officials resumed
contract talks.
   ``I think the feeling is, we are close. I'm optimistic we can
reach an agreement,'' Detroit Free Press Publisher Robert Hall said.
   Robert Giles, publisher of The Detroit News, said he also
expected to reach an agreement with five of the newspapers' six
unions by a 12:01 a.m. Thursday strike deadline. The press
operators' Graphics Communications International Union ratified a
contract Sunday.
   William Keating, chief executive of the Detroit Newspaper
Agency, which runs the combined operations, said Monday night talks
would continue until the two sides agree.
   ``I am totally convinced that everything will be resolved and
that there will not be a strike,'' Keating said.
   The main issue was money. Louis Mleczko, president of Local 22
of the Newspaper Guild, said management negotiators offered a
$30-per-week raise during the first year of a 2{-year contract, $30
in the second year, $15 for the remaining six months, and a signing
bonus equal to two weeks' pay for the approximately 3,300 employees
at the papers.
   The unions seek raises totaling $110 weekly during the 2{-year
contract plus a three-week pay bonus, said Mleczko. The average
salary of all workers at the two newspapers, excluding benefits, is
about $570 weekly, Hall said.
   Many newspaper employees have had only one raise since 1986,
when News owner Gannett Co. Inc. and Free Press owner Knight-Ridder
Inc. announced plans to pursue the joint operating agreement, under
which business operations are merged while editorial departments
remain separate.
   With the JOA in place, the Free Press remains a morning
newspaper while the News will generally have afternoon home
deliveries. There will be joint weekend editions, under the
masthead of The Detroit News and Free Press.
   According to figures released Nov. 13, the daily circulation of
the News is 690,422 and 832,382 on Sundays, and the Free Press' is
626,434 daily and 687,537 Sundays.
   The JOA's path was cleared, after years of legal challenges from
a coalition of readers and advertisers, when the U.S. Supreme Court
tied 4-4 on Nov. 13 after hearing an appeal. The tie let stand
lower court rulings that approved the 100-year agreement.
   The Free Press, which lost millions of dollars in the past 10
years, was described as in danger of failing without the JOA.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
