<FIRST>r i AM-Argentina-Britain     11-27 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina-Britain,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Trade Mission Meets With Argentines; First Since War</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 53-man British trade mission
began a week of meetings Monday to explore the possibility of
resuming commercial relations interrupted by the Falkland Islands
war of 1982.
   The mission, sponsored by the Latin American Trade Advisory
Group and the London Chamber of Commerce and Industry, is ``the
first contact toward re-establishment of trade relations with a
traditional partner of Britain,'' said Lord Montgomery, leader of
the group.
   He and the delegation met with Oscar Saggese, secretary of
industry and foreign trade and attended a luncheon with the
Argentine Chamber of Commerce.
   Britain's embassy has been closed since the 74-day war in 1982
for the South Atlantic archipelago, which Argentina started and
Britain won.
   Formal talks aimed at restoring relations without resolving the
issue of sovereignty over the islands, which both nations claim,
began earlier this year in New York and Madrid. Further meetings
are scheduled next month in Montevideo, Uruguay, and next year in
Paris.
   The trade delegation is to meet President Carlos Menem on
Thursday and will consult with ``representatives of business, banks
and state organisms scheduled for privatization,'' Montgomery said.
   He said the mission would ``evaluate current political
conditions to see if they are favorable for future capital
investments in areas such as petrochemicals, petroleum and
agriculture.''
   Saggese said the British delegates suggested Argentine
businessmen return the visit next year. He said trade between the
two countries, about $850 million in 1981, now amounts to $100
million a year, largely conducted through third countries.
</TEXT>
