<FIRST>u w AM-Santa'sSurprise     11-27 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Santa's Surprise,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Santa's Sack Contains Shocking Surprise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ho-ho's of a shopping mall Santa Claus
turned into uh-oh's over the weekend.
   Officials at Tysons Corner Center in suburban Virginia were
shocked to discover that their jolly old elf was handing out to
tots copies of a children's book containing the startling message
that there's really no Santa.
   There, on page 86 of ``A Pee Wee Christmas,'' fresh from St.
Nick's very own toy sack, was the revelation by one of the book's
characters that Santa Claus is a fake, just like his paste-on beard
and padded stomach.
   The books were yanked Saturday and replaced with Christmas
stickers and fingerprinting kits, but not before copies of ``A Pee
Wee Christmas'' had been dispensed to 300 or 400 innocent tots who
had climbed onto Santa's lap in the previous week.
   The mall was alerted by a complaint from Linda Smyth, a nurse
from nearby Vienna, Va., who had taken her 4-year-old son, Logan,
to meet Santa.
   ``I read the story to Logan at bedtime,'' she said, ``and he
fell asleep before I got to the juicy part, fortunately.''
   Said Tysons Corner general manager Jim Foster: ``What can I say?
We screwed up.''
   Foster said mall officials had screened more than a dozen books
looking for an appropriate Santa gift, but ``we just flat missed''
the troublesome passage in their final selection.
   The book tells the tale of a 7-year-old named Sonny who is
ridiculed by his friends for saying he believes in Santa Claus. His
friend Molly decides to set him straight.
   Here is the ``juicy part'' that raised Mrs. Smyth's eyebrows:
   ``Sonny,'' she whispered bravely. ``There isn't any real Santa
Claus. Your mom gives you the things on your list. I used to
believe in him too. But when you're seven you should know.''
   ``I know that,'' said Sonny. ``I knew he wasn't real. I saw his
beard. It was just pasted on.''
   Sonny adds that he was just pretending because ``it's more fun
to believe.''
   The book, part of a ``Pee Wee Scouts'' series that has sold more
than 2 million copies, was written by children's author Judy Delton
of St. Paul, Minn.
   In a telephone interview Monday, she said her Christmas story
had received very few complaints.
   Ms. Delton said ``A Pee Wee Christmas'' was written for 7- and
8-year-olds, who already have learned about Santa Claus from
television and playground gossip, but was never meant for younger
children.
   Nevertheless, she said, ``I was terribly sorry'' when she heard
about the flap over her book at the Tysons Corner mall.
   ``I felt really bad about it, and I can only apologize,'' she
said.
   Mrs. Smyth said she's glad Logan fell asleep while she was
reading ``A Pee Wee Christmas,'' and hopes her son continues to
believe in Santa Claus for many more years.
   ``That's the magic of being a child,'' she said. ``I know one
day he'll find out, but I don't want it to be like that.''
   Foster expressed chagrin over the incident, and offered this
word of advice: ``Don't believe everything you read.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891127-0175 </DOCNO>
