<HEAD>IRA Bombs Aircraft Factory</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two bombs exploded Monday night
at the newly privatized Short Brothers aircraft factory, badly
damaging one plane but causing no injuries, police said.
   The Press Association news agency said the outlawed Irish
Republican Army claimed responsibility. Police said a woman caller
telephoned a warning 20 minutes before the explosions and said
there were five bombs.
   One bomb damaged a Shorts 330 light aircraft and a second
exploded at an entrance gate, police said. Three more bombs were
defused.
   In July, the IRA planted five bombs that damaged two aircraft at
Shorts. It said the action was to protest alleged discrimination
against Roman Catholics and because the company did work for
Britain's Defense Ministry.
   The IRA wants to drive Britain from the Protestant-dominated
province and unite it with the Catholic Republic of Ireland.
