<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Peru     11-27 0156</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Peru,0161</SECOND>
<HEAD>Peruvian Rebels Kill Seven</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maoist Shining Path rebels shot a mining
superintendent to death, hanged a mayor and killed five other
people in weekend attacks in the Andes mountains, police said
Monday.
   Rebels killed the Contonga mine supervisor in Ancash department,
175 miles north of Lima, on Sunday and fled with dynamite,
detonators and fuses, police said.
   The same guerrillas killed three villagers of nearby Masin, they
reported.
   On Saturday, rebels hanged Mayor Anibal Bazan from a tree in
Singas, 185 miles northeast of Lima.
   The Shining Path has killed nearly 50 mayors this year in a
campaign of terror to gain control of rural areas.
   In Ayacucho, 235 miles southeast of Lima, hooded guerrillas
broke into the home of the dean of the state university's law
school Saturday night and shot him to death. They killed his
22-year-old daughter after she apparently recognized the voice of
one raider.
</TEXT>
