<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Politics     11-27 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Politics,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mrs. Thatcher Will Stay As Long As Party Wants Her</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher reaffirmed Monday
she will stay in office as long as she is wanted and said reports
she will step down soon after the next election ``could not have
been further from the truth.'' On her objection to European
Economic Community evolution toward a United States of Europe, Mrs.
Thatcher said Parliament would not allow Britain's monetary,
budgetary and economic policy to be left to the 12 member countries.
   ``I believe Britain is right,'' she said in a British
Broadcasting Corp. TV interview. `` We are choosing between the
British parliament and a group of people who are not accountable. I
believe our views will prevail as people look at it.''
   The EEC would ``go far further and have far better results if we
cooperate as 12 sovereign nations, voluntarily cooperating on the
things we do best,'' she said.
   Mrs. Thatcher, 64, has swept the Conservatives to three
successive election victories and is the longest-serving British
prime minister this century.
   ``I shall stay as long as the electorate and my own party wish
me to do, not a moment longer, but I hope as long as that,'' she
said Monday, adding she is fit and loves her work.
   She expressed concern about the effect of next week's
Conservative Party leadership election, saying, ``I think at the
moment, uncertainty about anything connected with the government is
not good _ but I would not like to use that to hinder anyone who
wants to stand.''
   The Conservatives have routinely endorsed her leadership since
1975. This year she faces a challenge from 69-year-old Sir Anthony
Meyer, a rank-and-file legislator.
   Voting is scheduled for Dec. 5. Under Tory rules, she must get
57 percent of the votes to win outright. If she does not, some more
prominent candidate than Meyer would be expected to enter the race
in a second ballot.
</TEXT>
