<FIRST>u a AM-MissingWoman 2ndLd-Writethru a0715 11-27 0622</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Missing Woman, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0715,0639</SECOND>
<HEAD>Community Search For Missing Student-Athlete Ends With Body Found</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with body positively identified,
authorities believe Miss Stavik abducted, other details; picks up 4th graf,
``Until Monday ...'' SUBS 16th graf, ``Detective said ...,'' to RESTORE
first reference to Gill.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREA BLANDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ACME, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This farming community's hunt for a missing
18-year-old honors student ended Monday when searchers found her
body in the shallow Nooksack River.
   The body was identified as that of Amanda Stavik, Whatcom County
Sheriff's Sgt. Ron Peterson told a news conference.
   Stavik had been missing since she went jogging Friday with her
dog, Kyra, while home from college on Thanksgiving break. The dog
returned alone.
   Authorities believe Miss Stavik was abducted, said Peterson, who
would not comment on the body's condition or how Miss Stavik died.
An autopsy will be conducted, he said.
   There was no evidence of a struggle on the bank near where the
body was found, leading authorities to suspect it floated
downstream, the sergeant said. He said detectives were still
looking for clues.
   There were no suspects in the case, Peterson said.
   Until Monday, authorities had seized upon a pair of teal blue
sweatpants recovered in the area as their only potential clue. Miss
Stavik was wearing that color garment when she was last seen.
   Whatcom County officials had asked the FBI for help and planned
to enlist the aid of the Green River Task Force, a Seattle-based
team of detectives with expertise in abduction that was formed to
pursue a serial killer.
   The FBI helped interview classmates of Miss Stavik at Central
Washington University in Ellensburg.
   The sweatpants were discovered 10 miles from the Stavik family's
home in this town of 250 people in northwestern Washington state,
80 miles north of Seattle and 20 miles south of the Canadian border.
   ``You think of those things happening in Seattle but not here,''
LoBay Smith said from behind the cash register at Acme Foods, where
customers had pledged $7,000 to anyone finding ``Mandy,'' as Miss
Stavik was known.
   Many of the Staviks' neighbors had joined the search in the
evergreen-studded foothills and along Highway 9, a busy road
connecting Seattle and its suburbs with the Mount Baker ski area.
   Miss Stavik's mother, Mary, had worked to keep her mind from
dwelling on her missing daughter.
   ``She was very happy and positive and feeling good about
school,'' Ms. Stavik said Sunday. She said her daughter had brought
a Japanese exchange student home for the holiday.
   Miss Stavik was last seen about a half-mile from her home by her
younger brother, Lee, 13. Her mother thought she had jogged the
three miles to the south fork of the Nooksack River.
   Lee, who was visiting a neighbor at the time, said it looked
like his sister was on her way back from the river.
   The sweatpants, recovered near an unpaved road where garbage is
sometimes dumped, did not prove to be solid evidence.
   Although they are the same color as sweatpants Miss Stavik was
wearing when last seen, bloodhounds failed to identify the garment
as Miss Stavik's, and her mother couldn't be certain they were her
daughter's.
   Detectives said their best leads may come from passers-by who
might have noticed something suspicious along the highway. The road
has about four times the traffic as normal because of a washed-out
bridge and the opening of ski season at Mount Baker, said
Undersheriff Doug Gill.
   ``We're hoping somebody saw something and will give us a call,''
he said.
   Investigators also have pulled the parole records of sexual
predators or other criminals who were known to be in the area, said
Gill.
</TEXT>
