<BYLINE>By JOEL STASHENKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWBURGH, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Funeral services were held Monday for two
of the children killed by a tornado that slammed into their
elementary school. One victim's mother said her son's organs would
help keep other children alive.
   More than 200 mourners attended a funeral service in this city
for Mark Flanagan, 7, and 175 gathered for a service in Middletown
for Jennifer Homan, 8.
   Both died Wednesday of injuries suffered Nov. 16, when a tornado
brought a cafeteria wall on more than 100 students lunching at East
Coldenham Elementary School. Nine children were killed and 16 were
injured.
   Mark's mother, Jean Flanagan, told mourners at Sacred Heart
Roman Catholic Church that her son's kidneys, heart valves and
lymph nodes were donated to help young transplant patients.
   ``Mark, you will hlp children live on,'' she told her son's
cream-and-gold-colored casket.
   Mrs. Flanagan, who has seen two other children die and suffered
two miscarriages, said her faith made the family's latest tragedy
easier to bear.
   ``That's what gives me the strength to say goodbye to you, Mark,
to know that I will see you again and my other children,'' she said.
   ``The lad is with God,'' said Monsignor George Valastro of
Sacred Heart. He called the boy a saint.
   Eight clergy members attended the service, including Episcopal
Bishop Austin Vaughan, the vicar of Orange County.
   Mark's casket was escorted from the church by an honor guard of
firefighters, some of whom were first on the scene following the
twister.
   Firefighters also attended Jennifer's funeral, and a firetruck
led a procession of about 30 cars from a funeral home in Middletown
to a cemetery in nearby Phillipsburgh.
   In her casket were placed pink, stuffed pigs she had owned, her
tap-dancing shoes and notes from classmates.
   ``Dear Jen,'' one note read, ``I will miss you and never forget
you. I will never forget what happened ...''
   Newburgh is about 60 miles north of New York City. Middletown is
nearly 25 miles southwest of Newburgh.
