<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua-Rockets     11-27 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Rockets,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nicaragua Claims Rockets in Salvador Could Belong to Contras</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, NICARAGUA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Minister Humberto Ortega said
Monday the anti-aircraft rockets found at the site of a plane crash
in El Salvador could have been from a U.S. shipment sent years ago
to Nicaraguan rebels.
   The Salvadoran government on Sunday suspended relations with
Nicaragua, accusing the Sandinistas of shipping the rockets and
other weapons to leftist guerrillas.
   A light plane with no registration number crashed Saturday about
60 miles east of San Salvador, the Salvadoran capital, and military
officers said three crewmen were killed and the fourth committed
suicide, shooting himself in the head.
   The plane did not burn and Salvadoran troops found in the
wreckage 24 Soviet-made SA-7 anti-aircraft rockets, one
U.S.-manufactured Redeye rocket, a Soviet-designed recoilless rifle
and 21 Soviet mortar shells. Salvadoran military officials said the
plane's flight originated in Nicaragua and the craft crashed when
it ran out of fuel.
   Nicaragua has denied over the years repeated charges that it was
supplying aid to the Salvadoran rebels.
   Ortega said the rockets found Saturday could be part of a
shipment of 300 that the former Reagan administration sent to
Nicaraguan rebels, known as Contras.
   ``Wasn't it the United States that in 1985 put in the hands of
terrorists the rockets that we don't know now where they are? They
can be in many different hands and markets,'' the defense minister
said.
   He made the comments at a ceremony marking Soldier's Day with
promotions and medals for troops wounded fighting the U.S.-backed
Contras. The defense minister is the brother of President Daniel
Ortega.
   Foreign Minsiter Miguel D'Escoto told reporters Nicaragua has
received no official notification from the Salvadoran governemnt
about a suspension of relations.
   ``We do not know what they are going to do. We have not broken
relations with them,'' D'Escoto said.
   Speaking about the arms shipment, he said, ``We know nothing
about the plane.''
   The Salvadoran diplomatic action could disrupt plans for a Dec.
8 meeting in Managua of five Central American presidents to resume
talks on the peace process for the region that includes
demobilization of the Contras.
</TEXT>
