<FIRST>r i AM-Interpol     11-27 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Interpol,0204</SECOND>
<HEAD>French President Opens New Interpol Headquarters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LYON, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Francois Mitterrand formally
opened Interpol's new headquarters beside the Rhone River Monday
and urged law enforcement officials from 147 countries to stop the
trade in illegal drugs.
   He told about 500 delegates at the organization's 58th annual
conference that losing the fight against drugs would represent `'a
collective failure of civilization.''
   The $22.5 million headquarters of the International Police
Organization _ Interpol _ replaced the organization's cramped
facilities in the Paris suburb of St. Cloud.
   Interpol acts as a clearing house for information among 147
countries. It does no investigating itself but provides members
with data on drug trafficking, terrorism and financial and other
crimes.
   Interpol officials say the new offices will allow the the
organization to expand its forensic capabilities and photo and
fingeprint files.
   It also will have a $645,000 communications system capable of
receiving and sending 7,000 messages per hour by telephone, telex
and radio.
   The structure will be easier to guard against attacks such as
the bombing by the Direct Action terrorist group in May 1986 that
wounded a police guard and seriously damaged the six-story building
in St. Cloud.
</TEXT>
