<FIRST>u w AM-Newspapers-Colombia     11-27 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Newspapers-Colombia,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bogota Paper Gets Help</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Bogota newspaper that was bombed because of
its coverage of Colombia's drug trade is getting a helping hand
from newspaper publishers in the United States and elsewhere in its
effort to stave off bankruptcy.
   Thomas C. Fichter of the American Newspaper Publishers
Association, one of two trade associations coordinating a drive to
raise funds for the troubled daily El Espectador, said Monday the
Bogota newspaper should receive the initial instalment on a loan
this week.
   Fichter said El Espectador has declared that it needs $2.5
million to continue publishing because of the bombing and other
losses it has suffered from the campaign against it by the
Colombian drug cartel.
   ``Right now we have got about $l.6 million pledged or paid and
there are sufficient people we haven't heard from yet that we think
will bring us to the $2.5 million mark,'' Fichter said.
   The president of El Espectador, Luis Cano, toured the United
States in October seeking support from news organizations. He said
a car bomb that exploded near the newspaper's offices on Sept. 2
did $2.5 million worth of damage.
   ``They had to pull out the windows and put on news roofs and
incur other expenses, not knowing where they were going to get the
money to pay for it,'' Fichter said. ``Not to mention the fact
their advertising lineage has been curtailed because many of the
advertisers have been intimidated.''
   Cano's younger brother, Guillermo Cano, publisher of the paper,
was killed by drug traffickers in 1986.
   Two employes of the newspaper in Medellin, where the drug cartel
has its headquarters, were killed in October. The newspaper
suspended home delivery in Medellin because of fear on the part of
truck drivers and delivery boys.
   El Espectador has a circulation of 350,000. Cano has said it is
losing money and facing possible bankruptcy.
   Fichter said, ``I think it struck a number of people all at one
time that something needed to be done.''
   Among them, he said, were newspaper executives and Bruce Gelb,
director of the U.S. Information Agency.
   Marty C. Davis, director of public liaison for the USIA., said
in a letter to executives of news organizations Monday that Gelb
``took his concerns to newspaper publishers who agreed to try to
raise money to keep El Espectador's presses running.'' Gelb visited
the newspaper's offices in Bogota on Oct. l5.
   Fichter said ANPA is working with the Inter-American Press
Association of Miami in coordinating the fund-raising campaign. He
said money or pledges had been received from about 50 donors in the
United States, Canada, Europe and Asia.
   Both Fichter and Ms. Davis said money would be available to help
other newspapers after El Espectador's needs had been met.
   ``The money is a loan,'' he said. ``They will give it back, and
that will perepetuate it.''
   Fichter said the fund-raising effort was the largest of its kind
that he knew of, although the trade associations have helped
troubled newspapers in various countries in the past. After the
fighting in Grenada in 1984, for instance, they helped the
newspaper in the Caribbean island obtain a new press to replace one
that had been destroyed.
</TEXT>
