<HEAD>Rightist Republicans Urge Reunited Germany</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Germany's ultraright-wing
Republican Party released on Monday a campaign platform calling for
a reunited Germany that would include territory lost in World War
II.
   Party chief Franz Schoenhuber, a former Waffen SS trooper,
announced the platform for next year's elections and said the
Republicans have set up organizations in ``several locations'' in
East Germany.
   He has made similar claims in the past. They were strongly
denied by East German communist authorities who say the Republican
Party is neo-Nazi.
   East Germany's official ADN news agency said Monday that
Republican leaflets have appeared in the country.
   ``Since the opening of the borders to the West, a rise in
activities of neo-Nazi groups in the direction of (East Germany)
can be noticed,'' ADN said.
   It said security officials will continue to fight all fascist,
neo-Nazi and racist tendencies.
   The Republicans' platform for the December 1990 federal
elections in West Germany calls for a confederation between the two
German states as a first step. It said free and secret elections
would follow to choose leaders of a unified German government based
in Berlin.
   It says East Germany must get out of the Soviet-led Warsaw Pact
and West Germany must leave the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
to permit ``a bloc-free, reunited Germany.''
   The 55-page program includes a map showing a united Germany and
including former German territories in Poland and the Soviet Union
that were lost with the defeat of Nazi Germany.
   Schoenhuber said the lands legally belong to Germany until a
peace treaty is signed.
   He claimed the party has ``tripled in membership to 25,000''
during the past year.
