<SECOND>AM-Missing Youths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0665,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>PRECEDE Tollgate, Ore.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Five Missing Youths Found Safe in Northeastern Oregon</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with youths found, rescued, details; no pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WALLA WALLA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five young people who were stranded
for two nights in the rugged Blue Mountains were found and rescued
Monday after a pilot spotted the word ``help'' stamped in the snow,
officials said.
   ``They are cold and hungry, but other than that they appear to
be OK,'' Capt. Joyce Gerdes of the Umatilla County, Ore., Sheriff's
Department said after an Army National Guard helicopter flew the
five out.
   The five, aged 7 to 20, were airlifted from an area about 30
miles east of Walla Walla near the Oregon-Washington line, said
Gerdes, whose department coordinated the two-state search for the
five.
   They were taken to the Walla Walla Regional Aiport, where they
were turned over to relatives, she said.
   The distress call stamped in the snow was spotted by the pilot
of a private airplane, who notified the airport tower, Gerdes said.
   The five left Walla Walla around 8 p.m. Saturday, telling their
parents they were going to play in the snow at Tollgate, Ore., and
return later that night, said Umatilla County Sheriff Jim Carey.
   The youths said their four-wheel-drive vehicle got stuck in the
snow.
   ``Apparently they spent the first night in their car,'' said the
helicopter pilot, Tim Kelly. They took refuge Sunday in a U.S.
Forest Service fire lookout tower, he said.
   The search began early Sunday, and involved an airplane, a
helicopter and snowmobiles. The hunt moved into Oregon later in the
day after someone reported seeing the young people in the Tiger
Canyon area, 17 miles east of Weston in the northeastern section of
the state.
   Teams searched through the night.
   Umatilla County Deputy Keith Garoutte said searchers had to
contend with freezing temperatures and fog in the mountains, with
snow depths of up to a foot at the top of Tiger Canyon.
</TEXT>
