<FIRST>r a AM-BusCrashTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0694 11-27 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bus Crash Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0694,0582</SECOND>
<HEAD>Witness: `Barrage of Screams' From Inside Burning Bus</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `Thom said ..., with 5 grafs to UPDATE with testimony
that Mahoney was driving in wrong lanes, further on rescue; picks up 8th
graf: ``There was ...; ADDS 1 graf with testimony that beer cans seen in
Mahoney's truck.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   ,
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By CHARLES WOLFE</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CARROLLTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A truck driver testified Monday how he
snatched some children from a burning church bus amid ``a constant
barrage of screams'' from the 27 people who were trapped and killed.
   The bus was ``blazing furiously'' soon after it was struck by
Larry Mahoney's pickup on Interstate 71, said James Thom of St.
Charles, Ill.
   ``There was a huge fireball. It was blazing. ... It was just
light like day,'' Thom said on the third day of testimony in
Mahoney's trial in Carroll Circuit Court.
   Mahoney, 36, is charged with 27 counts of murder. He also is
charged with 12 counts of first-degree assault, 42 counts of wanton
endangerment and one count of drunken driving.
   Mahoney is alleged to have driven in the wrong direction of
I-71, missing Thom's tractor-trailer and several other cars and
trucks before slamming into the bus at 10:55 p.m. on May 14, 1988.
   The former school bus, owned by Radcliff First Assembly of God
Church in Hardin County, 100 miles southwest of here, was returning
a youth group from an outing at an amusement park north of
Cincinnati.
   Jack Armstrong of Patriot, Ind., testified that he and his wife,
Joan, had been driving north behind Mahoney, and saw him driving in
the wrong lanes for about two miles before the crash.
   ``My wife screamed, `Oh my God, that's a school bus,'' recalled
Armstrong, who like his wife was once a school bus driver.
   He said he dashed to the back door of the bus and started
dragging children out one by one while his wife dragged survivors
off the pavement and into the grass median of the highway.
   Armstrong said he got ``maybe 25 or 30'' children out, but smoke
and heat kept him from rescuing more. Forty passengers survived the
wreck.
   Thom said he ground his truck to a halt and sprinted to the
burning bus.
   ``There was just a constant barrage of screams, cries for help _
people crying out, constant,'' he said.
   A few people were able to extend an arm or leg through the smoke
and fire toward the rear door ``and I just pulled,'' Thom said.
   He rescued ``three or four at the most,'' Thom said. ``The heat
and flames drove me away.''
   Mahoney buried his face in one hand during Thom's testimony,
tears streaming down his cheeks. Many of the victims' relatives in
the courtroom cried, too.
   The last person he rescued, Thom said, was a girl named Christy,
whose arms, face and legs were burned. He stayed with her until she
was evacuated, Thom said.
   Christy Pearman, 13 at the time of the crash, was the daughter
of bus driver John Pearman, one of three adults among the 27 who
died. The girl was in critical condition for several days after the
crash and represents one of the assault charges against Mahoney.
   Two other witnesses, former state trooper Robert Strong and
paramedic Tommy Webb, testified they saw cold cans of beer in the
cab of Mahoney's pickup.
</TEXT>
