<FIRST>u r AM-US-Afghan 2ndLd-Writethru a0760 11-27 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Afghan, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0760,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Resistance Leader Hopes Bush Will Sway Gorbachev on Afghanistan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 3-5 to CORRECT spelling from Mojadeddi to Mojaddedi</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leader of the Afghan resistance said Monday
he hopes President Bush will persuade Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev at their weekend summit to stop supporting the ``puppet
regime'' of Najibullah in Afghanistan.
   Sibghatullah Mojaddedi met with Bush in the Oval Office to thank
him and the American people for backing the Mujahedeen rebels in
their 11-year fight to oust the Soviet-backed government.
   Mojaddedi later told The Associated Press that he would ask U.S.
officials for high altitude anti-aircraft weapons to use against
Soviet planes that he said were still flying bombing missions from
Soviet territory.
   ``Still, the Russians our bombing our people, the Mujahedeen,
from their own territory,'' said Mojaddedi.
   Mojaddedi did not ask Bush directly for the weapons but said he
would raise the issue before he departs Washington on Friday.
   He also said that while he and Bush did not discuss next week's
meeting off Malta between the two superpower leaders, ``I am sure
that he will discuss (Afghanistan). It is a very important issue.''
   ``Gorbachev must be convinced that this is a puppet regime, that
the Afghanistan people do not support this ... puppet regime,'' he
said.
   Mojaddedi is the president of the Afghan Interim Government
formed by seven main resistance groups after the Soviet Union
completed the pullout of 115,000 troops from Afghanistan last
February.
   Covert U.S. military support for the rebels is reported to
exceed $500 million a year, but so far the United States has not
granted formal recognition to the rebels' government-in-exile based
in Peshawar, Pakistan.
   U.S. officials had hoped the resistance would quickly topple
Najibullah's government after the Soviet pullout. The rebels
control most of the Afghan countryside, but so far have been unable
to dislodge the Kremlin-backed forces from the capital of Kabul or
from Jalalabad and other major cities.
   White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said in a statement
that Bush ``reaffirmed our support for the Afghan resistance's
efforts to achieve self-determination and also expressed U.S.
interest in a political settlement.''
   He said Bush ``called upon the Afghan Interim Government to
continue and increase its efforts to fashion a stable, broadly
based government responsive to the needs of the Afghan people.''
   Mojaddedi, asked why the rebels have been unable to topple
Najibullah, said the Soviets have withdrawn ``partly from
Afghanistan, not completely.''
   He said of Soviet soldiers, ``Still they are fighting in the
name of Afghans inside Afghanistan,'' and he also said Soviet
planes conduct bombing runs from their own territory against
northern Afghanistan.
   He charged the Soviet Union has doubled or tripled its support
for the Najibullah government since the pullout to at least $300
million a month. And he said the rebels did not get supplies for
eight or nine months.
   Asked about factional strife among the resistance fighters,
Mojaddedi called that ``wrong propaganda. We are not fighting
amongst ourselves. We are all united. ... Sometimes it happens, but
rarely, seldom.''
   ``The Mujahedeen from different parties, they are united. And if
we were not united, we would not have achieved such progress in our
struggle,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
