enough evidence to seek the death penalty.
   Assistant Attorney General Warren Granville said the state would
call several witnesses at the preliminary hearing.
   Last month, The Associated Press reported that Corbin had
convened a state grand jury to investigate allegations of
obstruction in the Bolles case.
   State law makes it a crime to disclose grand jury matters.
Corbin declined Monday to confirm that there was a grand jury probe
or whether there was any connection between it and Monday's charge.
   Bolles died 11 days after the car he was in was blown up by a
remote-controlled bomb.
