<DOCNO> AP891127-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-27-89 1145EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv28   11-27 0710</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 28,0728</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv28</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tuesday PMs Nov. 28</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today's Puzzle: What Is an American Company Doing Helping Japan?</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: John Cunniff is on vacation.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ARMONK, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Imagine an American company that sponsors a
science prize in Japan to ``breed a succession of next-generation
Japanese Nobel Prize winners.''
   Imagine an American company that calls itself ``a valuable
source of European strength in the drive for greater efficiency,
and in competition for world markets.''
   What is this American company doing, shooting itself in the
foot? No. The company is International Business Machines Corp., and
it is acting very much in its own self-interest.
   IBM's generosity in Japan, Europe and elsewhere may not please
congressmen and government officials who are trying to build up the
United States to fight foreign rivals. But then, that's not IBM's
goal.
   IBM, as its name implies, is a truly international company that
just happens to have headquarters on a wooded hilltop in a small
town about 25 miles north of Manhattan.
   Overseas, IBM is happy to be thought of as a local company. The
perception helps the company sell more locally, hire the best
people in each country and get good treatment from local
governments on such issues as taxes and tariffs.
   C. Michael Armstrong, a native of Detroit, is proud of IBM's
success in spreading its research, manufacturing, sales and service
operations into every corner of the world.
   ``IBM to some degree has successfully lost its American
identity,'' the senior vice president in charge of IBM World Trade
Corp. said in an interview in his corner office earlier this year.
   IBM is the very model of a modern multinational. Others include
West Germany's Siemens AG, the Netherlands' NV Philips and, to a
lesser degree, American companies such as General Motors Corp. and
Ford Motor Co., which are entrenched in Europe and have alliances
with Japanese automakers.
   The future belongs to such companies, which float above national
boundaries, obeying the rules in every country where they operate
but belonging to no country in particular.
   These companies are not merely multinationals, but
transnationals, transcending international borders.
   It takes real effort to change perspective and see companies in
this light. Most political leaders continue to miss the point by
judging companies according to where their headquarters happen to
be.
   Governments of individual nations are going to have to learn how
to deal with transnational companies in ways that benefit their own
people. It is not an easy task, because governments have less
leverage against a transnational than against a company that does
all its business locally.
   A transnational company is like a living organism, with each
part dependent on the others for survival. A government that tried
to nationalize an IBM factory would find itself with a useless
asset because IBM would cut the factory off from its worldwide
system of distribution, manufacturing and research.
   Fortunately for the United States, IBM does have a strong
commitment to this country, which after all remains its largest
single market and source of employees. For example, IBM has shared
some of its most advanced computer chip technology with other U.S.
companies to assure itself of a steady supply of chips from outside
suppliers.
   On the other hand, U.S.-based transnationals like IBM, GM and
Ford have few qualms about importing parts and even whole products
for the American market, even though making them here would create
more jobs for Americans in design and manufacturing.
   The point is not that these companies are somehow disloyal or
treacherous. The point is that their interests do not always match
the U.S. national interest.
   The issue is more important than ever now that Washington is
debating how to dole out the benefits of an industrial policy _
that is, a program to improve the ability of this nation to compete
in world markets.
   Harvard University's Robert B. Reich, a professional skeptic,
put it this way in an essay earlier this year in The New Republic:
   ``Our economic future, as well as our national security, is
better served by developing a large corps of technologically
sophisticated workers within the nation than by boosting the
profitability of America's global corporations.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv Tuesday PMs Nov. 28</NOTE>
</DOC>
