<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--FilmReview Adv00   11-27 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Film Review, Adv 00,0459</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>At the Movies: `True Love'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   While big-buck movies crowd into the nation's theaters during
the holiday season, a number of smaller, worthy films face the
danger of being pushed out of the marketplace.
   Among them: ``Henry V,'' a daring new version by Kenneth
Brannagh; ``Staying Together,'' Lee Grant's warm study of a small
town family in trouble; ``My Left Foot,'' an inspiring tale of
human survival with an electrifying performance by Daniel
Day-Lewis; ``Drugstore Cowboy,'' grownup Matt Dillon in a highly
original film about druggies in 1970 Portland, Ore.
   Add to the list ``True Love.''
   Amazingly, it was filmed for less than $1 million. But ``True
Love'' has far more heart and humanity than today's bloated sequels
and star ego trips _ notably the noxious ``Harlem Nights.''
   The movie contains no recognizable names or faces. Nor does it
boast a high concept plot. Its fascination lies in its
high-spirited acting and verisimilitude to Italian-American life in
the Bronx.
   Director Nancy Savoca and her husband and co-producer, Richard
Guay, have written a script centering on the rituals of a
traditional wedding. The bride (Annabella Sciorra) frets over why
she is marrying Michael (Ron Eldard). He is unreliable, immature
and selfish.
   His qualms are just as severe. He enjoys his life of freedom, of
being able to hang out with the boys whenever he wants. Why take on
the hassle and responsibility of marriage?
   Their doubts and fears continue right up to the wedding night,
which he wants to spend with his chums. It's hard to imagine
anything so dumb, but that's about the only disparity in the film.
   As a director-writer, Nancy Savoca has a marvelous eye for
detail and human touches. The interplay among the males and
especially among the females (Are women so profane among
themselves?) is carefully drawn and exploited for all its humor.
   She also makes her actors look as if they weren't acting. Both
Sciorra and Eldard show sparks of star quality.
   ``True Love'' is getting a desultory release by MGM-UA and
deserves time to find its audience.
   Rated R for language. Running time: 1 hour, 4 minutes.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
   G _ General audiences. All ages admitted.
   PG _ Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
   PG-13 _ Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
   R _ Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
   X _ No one under 17 admitted. Some states may have higher age
restrictions.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
