<FILEID>AP-NR-11-27-89 1350EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   11-27 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Ballet Music by Giuseppe Verdi'' (London) _ Orchestra del
Teatro Comunale di Bologna, conducted by Riccardo Chailly
   
   If not for anything else, we should thank the French for
insisting on ballets in their operas. Verdi wrote seven for his
stage works performed in Paris, and these ``divertissements''
contain some beautiful music and an infrequent example of non-vocal
Verdi.
   Oboe, clarinet or violin often sings the melody over the usual
bouncing accompanying figures. The score has moments of highly
charged drama, and the orchestration is always superb.
   Chailly induces this somewhat rough-edged orchestra to give
rhythmically taut, high-spirited and at times exciting
performances. The band has its high spots, but an unfortunate
number of low ones _ bad intonation in the brass, blurry strings
and loose-knit pizzicati.
   The pieces are drawn from ``Macbeth,'' ``I vespri Siciliani,''
``Don Carlos,'' ``Aida'' and ``Otello.''
   _ By Daniel Wakin, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``We Too Are One'' (Arista) _ Eurythmics
   
   Once the darlings of post-modern, synth-pop enthusiasts, Dave
Stewart and Annie Lennox have at last begun to speak to all of us.
   Their hard-edged ``We Too Are One'' builds on a more
guitar-heavy rhythm and blues sound and sticks with lyrics rooted
in a strong sense of self-worth. Lennox plays the jilted woman in
the powerful lead single ``Don't Ask Me Why,'' and the brutal ``You
Hurt Me (And I Hate You).'' She sounds nasty and unforgiving, but
only because a man pushed her too far and she knows she's too good
for that.
   In the sharply critical ``The King and Queen of America,''
Lennox and Stewart comment on arrogant, phony political figures who
exploit people with empty promises, people who ``never did anything
_ to make ourselves feel proud.''
   The real highlights on ``We Too Are One'' come in its ballads.
Lennox laments the death of her father and grieves over her recent
miscarriage in ``Angel,'' a poignant comment on the sadness of
death and the hope of a better life in the netherworld.
   The hymn-like ``When the Day Goes Down'' is dedicated to the
less fortunate and downtrodden, telling them, ``all God's children
are beautiful and pure _ and you're as good as all of them.''
Lennox's rich alto caresses the words, lending them a genuine
sincerity, as Stewart's guitar weaves a gentle background.
   Nowadays, Lennox and Stewart write songs that are modern without
being threatening. ``We Too Are One'' seems more listener-friendly
than some of their previous eight albums. It won't scare away
aficionados of other types of music. Quite an accomplishment.
   By Kira L. Billik, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
