<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--PianoTuner Adv8-10   11-27 0898</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Piano Tuner, Adv 8-10,0931</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv08</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv10</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Dec. 8-10, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Artists: A Hero and a Friend</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If a man can't be a hero to his valet, can a
pianist be a hero to the technician who tunes his piano?
   Yes, both a hero and a friend, says Franz Mohr about the late
Vladimir Horowitz.
   Mohr, chief concert technician at Steinway &amp; Sons, accompanied
the pianist to performances that included his heralded comeback at
Carnegie Hall in 1965, his 1986 Moscow concert and two appearances
at the White House.
   He last saw Horowitz four days before he died, during a
Wednesday session for a new recording at Horowitz's Manhattan home.
When Mohr arrived Friday for another session, he was told that
Horowitz had practiced for half an hour but didn't feel well. The
pianist died suddenly Nov. 5 while discussing with his wife, Wanda,
a menu for that night's dinner to which they had invited pianist
Murray Perahia.
   ``Horowitz was in a class by himself,'' Mohr said. ``He had
tremendous command when it comes to technique. Many young artists
have technique today, too. But nobody has such a wide range of
color like Horowitz. He had from a super-fortissimo to a
super-pianissimo so soft it hardly exists. When he played his last
European tour, in 1987, he played Liszt's `Consolation' with such
command it made you cry.
   ``He played dangerously in a way, in his phrasing and his
tempos, almost many times to the breaking point but never over it.
He had such clarity. In fast passages you heard every note. Many
pianists smear through. Even now, at 86 ... he was tremendous.
Listen to his last record, `Horowitz at Home.' Unbelievable.''
   They were friends, too, Mohr said. ``Many times I'm invited for
dinner after a concert. We had the Horowitzes for dinner at our
home. They appreciated my family very much. I have two boys in the
piano business, in leading positions I would say. My daughter is
getting married in February. Wanda said they would come.
   ``Wanda was the best critic for him. He listened to her. She is
profound and knows music. My wife and I love her, too.''
   Horowitz's own piano, a wedding gift when he married Wanda
Toscanini in 1933, was moved from his home to the basement of the
Steinway showroom three years ago. His last recording was done on a
new piano from Steinway.
   Gesturing to Horowitz's piano, which he always took with him on
tours, Mohr said: ``He was planning to take this piano again on
tour. I prepared it for him. He was coming in this week to look at
it. He said soon he would play in Berlin, Hamburg and Amsterdam,
maybe Leningrad.''
   Asked whether Horowitz was even-tempered or volatile, Mohr said:
``I would say that being such a genius, as he really was, a man of
his caliber would change emotionally hour by hour. You see it in
his playing. He never played the same piece the same way.
   ``Of course he could blow up or get excited on the spur of a
moment that some little thing is not just right. That can happen
but it is understandable.
   ``For a technician, he was very easy to work with, because he
was consistent in what he did. He always had his rehearsal at 4
p.m. Saturday and his concert at 4 Sunday. He never practiced the
day of the concert. He said if he didn't know the piece the day
before, he shouldn't play it.''
   Mohr has traveled with pianists, some of them famous, who played
every day, on whatever piano was available and often practiced so
close to the time of the concert that he had no time to prepare the
piano.
   ``Tuning is extremely important,'' he said. ``An action has more
than 10,000 parts, consisting of wood and felt, therefore subject
to changes in humidity. You have constantly to check the regulation
of the instrument, especially a piano which travels. In Russia I
had two sets of tools with me, plus quite a few parts, like
strings.''
   Mohr is nervous only for the first few bars. Then, when he hears
the piano sounding all right, he relaxes and enjoys the music.
   He started his music career in performance, studying violin in
his native Germany. ``I had problems with my left wrist. I came to
the painful conclusion I couldn't pursue a musical career. I was
already 22 when I went into this (tuning). I worked my way through
the factory.'' Some technicians shrink from contact with musicians
but Mohr relishes it.
   Steinway moved him to New York in 1962. ``My predecessor was
Bill Hupfer. He was a legend. He had traveled all his life with
Rachmaninoff. When he retired, I took over as chief concert
technician.''
   Mohr recalled one Horowitz incident with a smile: ``He made me
pretty famous. When he played in Berlin, it was a tremendous
success. I came home on Monday. He called me, `You have to come
back. I play a second concert.' He said to the press in Berlin, `If
Franz doesn't come back, there won't be any second concert.' It
ended up on TV and all of that.''
</TEXT>
