<FILEID>AP-NR-11-27-89 0851EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-MorganGrenfell     11-27 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Morgan Grenfell,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deutsche Bank in Bid for Morgan Grenfell</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deutsche Bank AG, West Germany's largest bank,
said today that it offered to buy British merchant bank Morgan
Grenfell PLC in a friendly cash deal valued at $1.48 billion.
   The move was designed to block a hostile bid for Morgan Grenfell
by France's Banque Indosuez.
   Deutsche Bank's $8.56-a-share offer was $1.15 per share over
Morgan Grenfell's close Friday on the London Stock Exchange.
However, the announcement pushed Morgan Grenfell's stock slightly
above the offer price.
   The bid came three days before a vote by shareholders of Willis
Faber PLC, a British insurance services concern, on whether to sell
its remaining 9.9-percent stake in Morgan Grenfell to Banque
Indosuez for $7.19 a share.
   Earlier this month, Willis Faber sold Banque Indosuez a
10.5-percent stake in Morgan Grenfell for $6.38 dollars a share,
raising the French bank's stake in its British target to 14.9
percent.
   Banque Indosuez says it seeks a 24.8 percent stake, but needs
Bank of England approval to own more than 15 percent.
   In a joint statement today, Deutsche Bank and Morgan Grenfell
said the British bank ``will operate as a separate legal entity
within the Deutsche Bank group and with a high degree of autonomy.''
   Deutsche Bank has for years held a 4.9-percent stake in Morgan
Grenfell. Morgan Grenfell had initiated talks with the German bank
and a number of other European financial institutions over a
protective alliance after Indosuez announced its takeover
intentions.
   Indosuez, however, could raise its offer to Willis Faber, make a
general offer topping Deutsche Bank's, or simply sell its stake to
Deutsche Bank at a profit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
