<DOCNO> AP891127-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-27-89 0906EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>d f BC-AsianSilk     11-27 0152</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Asian Silk,0156</SECOND>
<HEAD>Asia Expands Exports of Finished Silk Products</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Asia, which produces 95 percent of the
world's raw silk, has gained a foothold in the market for finished
silk products, a United Nations report has found.
   Asian countries traditionally export raw silk to Europe, where
it was made into cloth and garments. But the November report said
major producing countries including China, India and Thailand have
been exporting more finished products.
   Their success has been partly due to increasing demand for
natural fibers sparked by the ecological awareness movement in the
West, the report said.
   It said China, which accounts for 60 percent of world's raw
silk, plans to reduce the share of its raw silk exports to 30
percent in 1990 from 49 percent in 1980, and to increase exports of
finished products and fabrics to 70 percent in 1990, from 51
percent in 1980.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891127-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-27-89 0915EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-EC-EasternEurope     11-27 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EC-Eastern Europe,0202</SECOND>
<HEAD>EC Reaches Trade Deal With Soviets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Community said Monday that
it signed a draft trade and economic cooperation accord with the
Soviet Union, four months after talks began.
   The accord is the fourth accord between the EC and an East
European country since the Community and the Moscow-led Comecon
trade bloc signed a mutual recognition agreement on June 25, 1988.
   It reflects the rapid changes in Europe's political landscape.
   Since late 1988, the EC has signed agreements with Hungary,
Czechoslovakia and Poland.
   Separately Monday, European Community External Relations
Commissioner Frans Andriessen called the developments in
Czechoslovakia of the last week ``a cause for profound rejoicing
throughout Europe.''
   ``Political reform and economic liberalization in Czechoslovakia
form part of a wider process which, for the first time in more than
40 years, offers to future generations the prospect of a Europe no
longer riven by division,'' he said in a statement.
   The trade and economic cooperation pact with Moscow must be
formally approved by the 12 EC states, which is considered a
formality, before it takes effect.
   No details of the draft agreement were immediately released.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
