<FILEID>AP-NR-11-27-89 1009EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f OPEC 2ndLd-Writethru f0035 11-27 0789</FIRST>
<SECOND>OPEC, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0035,0813</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Ministers Resume Negotiations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead to CORRECT to 1990 sted 1989; ADDS new 4th graf with
WTI prices; picks up 4th graf pvs, `OPEC was ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   OPEC ministers resumed negotiations on
Monday in an effort to reach an oil production and price agreement
for the first half of 1990.
   Seven oil ministers from the 13-member Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries gathered in a hotel room to see if they could
overcome their differences.
   The oil markets adopted a wait-and-see attitude toward the oil
producers' regular winter conference, now in its third day. North
Sea Brent Blend, the most widely traded international crude oil,
was quoted at a spot price of $18.47 a barrel in quiet dealings
Monday, up slightly from $18.44 late Friday.
   West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. grade of crude, was
down slightly in early trading with the near-term contract at
$19.79 a barrel, down 3 cents from Friday's close.
   OPEC was at an impasse, and loosely split into two camps, over
how to meet demands from Kuwait and the United Arab Emirates for
bigger shares of the cartel's production pie, sources said Sunday.
   ``We have not yet reached the stage of proposals. The issues are
so sensitive apparently that no one dares putting foreward
proposals,'' Algerian oil minister Sadek Boussena said. ``We are
still at the starting point.
   The cartel's gathering formally began on Saturday, and the
ministers suspended talks on Sunday to reflect on their options.
   OPEC members in the past have found such breaks, as well as
holding small group discussions in their hotels, more productive
than gathering all the ministers at the cartel's Vienna
headquarters.
   The ministers must decide whether to change their production
ceiling of 20.5 million barrels a day and their target price of $18
a barrel.
   Oil prices have been firm, with OPEC's ``basket,'' or composite,
of crude oils at $17.76 a barrel lately, even though analysts say
OPEC members are exceeding the group's output ceiling by more than
2.5 million barrels a day.
   Prices are more than $5 a barrel higher than a year ago because
of strong demand for oil from Third World countries and a decline
in output from non-OPEC producers. But OPEC is expecting demand to
fall in the first six months of next year.
   The oil market traditionally softens in the first and second
quarters as winter heating demands slacken before summer cooling
and gasoline demands pick up.
   Kuwait and the United Arab Emirates have been pumping about
double, or 2 million barrels a day each, what they are allowed
under the last OPEC agreement, underscoring their calls for bigger
shares.
   All the ministers appear to agree that the total ceiling could
be raised, perhaps by as much as 2 million barrels a day, but they
disagree on how the increase should be parceled out.
   A ministerial source, who demanded anonymity, on Sunday
described the two loose camps this way:
   One camp, led by the heavyweights Saudi Arabia and Iran, thinks
the increase in production should be granted to those members who
can produce more. Some members already are operating at near
capacity.
   This idea would allow Kuwait and the United Arab Emirates to
pump more, and would leave unchanged the shares for Saudi Arabia,
Iran and Iraq. The rest of the members would reduce their shares of
a larger pie.
   But this idea is onerous to poorer members that are more
dependent on their oil revenues, the ministerial source said.
   The second camp believes all the members should give up part of
their share to allow Kuwait and the United Arab Emirates larger
slices, the ministerial source said.
   But Saudi Arabia has insisted it won't accept less than its
allotment of one-quarter of the total production limit. It recently
increased its production above its quota, a move analysts say is
designed to emphasize that point.
   The fallback position would be to increase production equally
among all members, the ministerial source said.
   But this wouldn't address Kuwait and the United Arab Emirates'
demands for bigger shares, nor solve the problem of cheating on
quotas, which undermines OPEC's aims.
   Algeria's Boussena said an option being considered is an
agreement that would not be signed by all 13 OPEC members.
   Boussena added, ``We must have an agreement of 13. That is my
point of view.''
   OPEC could simply roll over its existing accord, as it has done
in the past, but the oil markets likely would view such a move as a
sign of weakness.
   Failure to reach an agreement could bring oil prices to as low
as $12 a barrel by the spring, the anonymous ministerial source
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891127-0243 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-27-89 1021EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet10am     11-27 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0306</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market advanced broadly today amid
spreading hopes for lower interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 14.51 to 2,690.06
in the first half hour of trading.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by more than 2 to 1 in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 657 up, 311
down and 455 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 22.12 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   The market began to rise last week on signs that the Federal
Reserve was takeing steps for the second time this month to relax
its credit policy.
   That development prompted Fed-watchers to conclude that the
central bank had decided to become more aggressive in its efforts
to cushion the impact of a slowing economy.
   The new trading week began amid talk of impending reductions in
major banks' prime lending rates.
   There was also conjecture that the Fed might make its intentions
even clearer before long by cutting the discount rate, the charge
it imposes on loans to private financial institutions.
   Among actively traded blue chips, Exxon rose ] to 46\; General
Electric ] to 60{; Philip Morris \ to 41}, and Chevron 1[ to 66[.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained .74 to 191.03. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was up .01 at 373.15.
   On Friday the Dow Jones industrial average climbed 18.77 to
2,675.55, bringing its gain for the week to 22.89 points.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by 2 to 1 on the NYSE,
with 914 up, 457 down and 520 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 86.29 million shares, against 145.73
million in the previous session.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
