<FILEID>AP-NR-11-27-89 1050EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-RigCount     11-27 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Rig Count,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rig Count Posts Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of working U.S. oil and gas rigs
dropped for the second straight week, declining by three this week
to 1,037 after rising 10 times in the past 13 weeks.
   But the total still reflects 126 more working rigs than for the
same week a year ago, Baker Hughes Inc. reported Monday. Last week,
the count dropped by five to 1,040.
   Baker Hughes' rig count _ the widely watched industry index of
drilling activity _ reflects the number of rigs actively exploring
for oil as of last Friday, not the number of rigs actively
producing oil.
   Houston-based Hughes Tool Co., an oil toolmaker company that
merged with Baker International Corp. of Orange, Calif., has kept
track of the rig count since 1940.
   In December 1981, at the height of the oil boom, the rig count
reached a peak of 4,500. But oil prices plunged to less than $10
per 42-gallon barrel in the summer of 1986, prompting a collapse in
the rig count that bottomed out at 663 _ the lowest since Hughes
began compiling figures.
   Among major oil producing states, Louisiana posted the largest
gains with 10 new rigs, while Colorado had three more. Declines
included a drop of five in New Mexico and drops of three rigs each
in Oklahoma and California. The number of rigs in Texas remained
unchanged. There were no reports for other producing states.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891127-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-27-89 1105EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-DetroitNewspapers 2ndLd-Writethru f0041 11-27 0721</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Detroit Newspapers, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0041,0739</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Issue of Detroit News and Free Press Marred by Strike Vote</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DT1</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with comment by chief executive,
ADD explanation of joint operating agreement, picking up at the 5th graf
previous, According to ... A version moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN DESMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Detroit News and Detroit Free Press published
their first editions under a partial merger today after a
three-year legal battle, but a possible strike may stall the joint
operation before it's a week old.
   Talks between the newspapers and the unions broke off Sunday
over wage and benefit demands.
   William Keating, chief executive of the Detroit Newspaper
Agency, which runs the combined operations, said he doesn't expect
a strike. ``I have consistently felt that labor matters can be
resolved and I continue to feel that way,'' he said Sunday.
   Detroit's two major daily newspapers began publishing under a
joint operating agreement following a vote Nov. 13 by the U.S.
Supreme Court, which upheld lower court rulings approving the
100-year agreement.
   The Knight-Ridder Inc.-owned Free Press declared it was a
financially failing newspaper in April 1986 and applied with the
News for permission to enter the operating agreement. Federal law
grants newspapers exemption from antitrust law if it's determined a
merger would prevent the failure of a paper and thus preserve two
independent editorial voices.
   According to figures released Nov. 13, the daily circulation of
the News, the nation's ninth largest newspaper, is 690,422, and
832,383 Sundays. The Free Press, the 10th biggest paper, had
circulations of 626,434 and 687,537.
   The newspapers merged business operations under the Detroit
Newspaper Agency. News and editorial departments remain separate
and independent but combined editions will be published on the
weekend under the masthead The Detroit News and Free Press. About
500 jobs were to be cut as a result of the arrangement.
   While the newspapers prepared the first post-agreement edition
of the Free Press for today, workers voted against ratifying a
contract offer from the new newspaper agency and in favor of strike
authorization.
   Teamsters Local 372, which represents 1,100 drivers and other
circulation workers, set a strike deadline of 12:01 a.m. Thursday.
Newspaper Guild Local 22, representing about 500 editorial workers
from both papers, voted unanimously to support a strike.
   ``The members of both papers feel the money package and benefits
were an insult to them,'' said Louis Mleczko, a News reporter and
president of Local 22. ``The publishers are going to have to share
some of the new riches from the 100-year monopoly they have been
granted from the court.''
   Robert H. Giles, president and publisher of Gannett Co. Inc.'s
Detroit News, said he expected issues to be resolved before the
strike deadline.
   Don Kummer, administrative officer for Local 22, said: ``What
we're looking at is the company testing the union to see if they'll
strike.''
   Press operators in the Graphics Communications International
Local 13-N surprised other unions by ratifying the wage offer from
the publishers. But they pledged to honor picket lines if the other
unions walked out.
   In other ratification votes announced Sunday, the unions
representing Detroit News photoengravers, workers who handle
special inserts and sort papers, and composing room employees also
rejected the new company's contract offers.
   Mleczko said the publishers offered a $30-per-week raise during
the first year of a 2{-year contract, $30 the second year and $15
for the remaining six months, and a signing bonus equal to two
weeks' pay.
   The unions wanted a $40-per-week raise the first year, $30 the
second and $40 for the next six months, plus a three-week bonus.
   The unions also asked the newspaper to pay for increases in
health care costs for future retirees. Fifty percent of those costs
currently are paid by unions.
   Union members at the two newspapers have had one raise in their
contracts since the operating agreement was announced in 1986. The
average wage for editorial employees and production workers at the
newspapers is $562 a week.
   Teamsters officials said the strike was set for Thursday to give
the employees time to get established under the new operations.
   The last newspaper strike in Detroit was at the Free Press in
July 1980 when Teamsters stayed away 12 days over economic issues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
