<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean Decline Drags Corn Down; Wheat Gains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices fell in early trading
today on the Chicago Board of Trade, dragging the corn market
lower. But wheat futures gained slightly on indications of renewed
Soviet buying interest.
   Selling of soybean futures stemmed from a continued lack of
export demand, analysts said.
   An abundance of Malaysian palm oil on the world market is
forcing soybean oil prices lower and European soybean processers
are believed to have enough beans on hand to last them through
December, said William Biedermann, director of research with the
futures brokerage Allendale Inc. in Crystal Lake, Ill.
   He said the opening dip in soybean futures triggered some
technical sell signals, accelerating the market's decline. The
January contract's drop below $5.83 a bushel was especially
significant.
   ``A close below that level would turn funds into sellers and
cause speculators to bail out,'' Biedermann said.
   Wheat futures were mixed and gaining, boosted by fading
prospects for substantial rainfall today in the winter wheat belt
and by Soviet purchases of wheat in Europe, an indication the
Soviet Union has re-entered the world grain market after an absence
of about three weeks.
   In early trading, wheat futures were } cent lower to 1\ cent
higher with December at $4.08 a bushel; corn was unchanged to 1\
cents lower with December at $2.36} a bushel; oats were 1 cent to
1\ cents lower with December at $1.45{ a bushel; soybeans were 4{
cents to 5\ cents lower with January at $5.81} a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .05 cent lower to .07 cent higher with December
at 76.07 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .18 cent
higher with November at 83.70 cents a pound; live hogs were .10
cent lower to .03 cent higher with December at 51.15 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .18 cent to .50 cent higher with February
at 64.77 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled higher on Friday.
</TEXT>
