<FIRST>u f PM-BankFraud     11-27 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bank Fraud,0218</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Bankers Plea Baragain Before Federal Trial Begins</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two former Tennessee financiers already
serving prison terms pleaded guilty today prior to the start of
their federal trial on charges of bilking an Orlando bank of $3.9
million.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Ricardo Pesquera said Jake Butcher, Earl
Wilson, and Wilson's wife, Harriette, pleaded guilty to some of
charges in the case. He did not elaborate.
   Butcher and Wilson, who are serving federal prison sentences for
bank fraud in Tennessee and Kentucky, had pleaded innocent in
September to 51 counts of bank fraud, bribery, conspiracy and
misapplication of funds.
   Along with Mrs. Wilson and nine others, they were charged in the
1986 collapse of Florida Center Bank in Orlando. A federal grand
jury charged that Butcher and the Wilsons paid former bank
president Joe F. Justice to funnel money secretly from the bank to
Butcher and Wilson.
   At the time, Butcher had filed for bankruptcy in Tennessee and
was under investigation for bank fraud. Butcher and Wilson once
operated a 20-bank chain.
   Butcher is serving a 20-year prison sentence for bank fraud in
Tennessee and Kentucky. Wilson is serving a 10-year sentence for
bank fraud in Tennessee. The others, including Mrs. Wilson, are
free on bail.
</TEXT>
