<FILEID>AP-NR-11-27-89 1322EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-MorganGrenfell     11-27 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Morgan Grenfell,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deutsche Bank Makes Friendly Bid for Morgan Grenfell</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deutsche Bank, West Germany's largest bank, on
Monday emerged as a ``white knight'' for Morgan Grenfell Group PLC
with a $1.48 billion takeover offer designed to stave off a hostile
bid by Banque Indoquez of France.
   Analysts said the $8.56-a-share cash offer, which has the full
backing of Morgan Grenfell's board of directors, represented a
premium over what the investment bank's stock was recently trading.
   Morgan Grenfell closed at $7.40 a share Friday on the London
Stock Exchange; it had fallen as low as $4 a share earlier this
year. The stock, though, rose sharply in price on Monday.
   ``It's a knock-out bid, one designed to forestall any notion
that Indosuez could top it,'' says Robert Law, a bank analyst at
Shearson Lehman Securities Ltd.
   Paris-based Indosuez, which already owns 14.9 percent of Morgan
Grenfell, had no comment on Deutsche Bank's bid, a spokesman said.
But analysts said it was unlikely Indosuez will make a higher offer.
   Last month, British insurer Willis Faber PLC sold a 10.6 percent
stake in Morgan Grenfell to Indosuez for $6.38 a share.
   Banque Indosuez says it seeks a 24.8 percent stake but needs
Bank of England approval to own more than 15 percent.
   Willis Faber shareholders were to meet Wednesday to decide
whether to accept Indosuez's $7.19-a-share offer for their
remaining 9.8 percent stake in Morgan Grenfell. But Willis Faber
appeared unlikely to sell unless Indosuez offered a higher price,
and said it was considering suspending the meeting.
   In a joint statement, Deutsche Bank and Morgan Grenfell said the
British bank ``will operate as a separate legal entity within the
Deutsche Bank group and with a high degree of autonomy.''
   Independent for 151 years, Morgan Grenfell was known as the
takeover king during the mid-1980s, playing a role in some of
Britain's biggest mergers. But it failed in its ambition of
becoming a fully integrated securities house, and pulled out of
share-dealing a year ago, firing 450 employees.
   John Craven, Morgan Grenfell's chairman, and Alfred Herrhausen,
a member of Deutsche Bank's board of managing directors, stressed
the mutual benefits of the deal.
   Deutsche Bank will get Morgan Grenfell's strength in corporate
finance and fund management, while strengthening its position in
the British market. Morgan will benefit from the West German bank's
distribution network and client base.
   ``The acquisition of Morgan Grenfell is an important step for
Deutsche Bank, which recognizes the pre-eminence of the London
market place within Europe in the fields of corporate finance and
asset management,'' Herrhausen said.
   ``We see the combination of the two organizations as an
excellent fit. Together we will form an unrivaled and powerful team
and give the enlarged Deutsche Bank group a leading position in
Europe.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
