<HEAD>London Shares Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices on London's stock exchange were
slightly higher Monday.
   The Financial Times 100-share index was up 1.9 points, or 0.09
percent, at 2,224.3, up from an early afternoon low of 2,212.9. A
light 333.3 million shares changed hands in quiet trading.
   Stock prices fell early on jitters over the slumping pound,
which continued to fall Monday, especially against the West German
mark. By the end of the London session, the pound was quoted at
2.79 marks, off sharply from 2.82 marks late Friday.
   An early rise on Wall Street, where participation returned in
full force after the Thanksgiving holiday, boosted late-afternoon
trading.
   The market received some support from West Germany's Deutsche
Bank AG's $1.48 billion cash bid for merchant bank Morgan Grenfell
PLC, a move which is seen as thwarting an unfriendly bid by
France's Banque Indosuez.
   Reflecting the market's belief that Deutsche Bank will be
victorious in its efforts, Morgan Grenfell shares finished below
the offer price of 550 pence, or $8.56, a share but up 60 pence, or
94 cents, from Friday.
</TEXT>
