<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Plunge in Technical Selloff</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed lower Monday on
the Chicago Board of Trade, led by a steep soybean selloff linked
to slack export demand and bearish technical signals.
   Soybean prices opened lower in reaction to weak demand for U.S.
soybeans by European processors, partially reflecting the abundance
of Malaysian palm oil, a soybean-oil competitor.
   The opening losses triggered technical sell signals, especially
when the January soybean contract fell below the 55-day moving
average of $5.83 a bushel, said William Biedermann, director of
research with the futures brokerage Allendale Inc. in Crystal Lake,
Ill.
   ``The technicals just really kicked in and we had fund and
speculator selling all day long _ heavy liquidation,'' he said.
   The wheat market closed narrowly mixed, with support stemming
from Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yuetter's statement that
France's sale of 1.3 million metric tons of wheat to the Soviet
Union was ``an encouraging sign'' that the Soviets were back in the
market for wheat.
   At the close, wheat futures were 1\ cents lower to { cent higher
with the contract for delivery in December at $4.06} a bushel; corn
futures were 3{ cents to 4} cents lower with December at $2.33\ a
bushel; oats were 3{ cents to 3} cents lower with December at $1.43
a bushel; soybeans were 6{ cents to 11 cents lower with January at
$5.76\ a bushel.
