<FIRST>r f AM-Italy-Soviet     11-27 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Italy-Soviet,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fiat Signing Agreement to Manufacture Cars on Eve of Gorbachev Visit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TURIN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fiat said Monday it will sign an agreement
to build a new line of cars in the Soviet Union, an important step
in President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's plans to increase the supply of
consumer goods.
   The Turin-based automobile giant said the joint venture
agreement would be signed Tuesday, the eve of Gorbachev's visit to
Italy.
   Fiat is Italy's largest private industrial group and has
produced cars in the Soviet Union since 1970.
   Fiat's managing director, Cesare Romiti, and Nikolai Pyjin, the
Soviet minister for the automobile industry, were scheduled to sign
a letter of intent for the project in Rome on Tuesday.
   While financial details have not been released, analysts believe
that Fiat and the Soviet Union will invest up to $1.4 billion.
   The plant will be built at Elabung, 60 miles southeast of
Moscow, and is expected to turn out 300,000 automobiles a year when
it begins operations between 1992 and 1993, according to industry
sources.
   The output of the model, based on the popular Fiat Panda in
Italy, would be then increased to between 600,000 to 900,000 cars a
year.
   Out of the first year's production, about a fourth would be sold
on Western European markets, giving the Soviet side some return on
its investment, according to the sources, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Other ageements between Italian and Soviet companies are
expected to be signed during Gorbachev's three-day visit to Italy
and the Vatican.
   Among the initiatives reported in the works are an agreement
with Pirelli to produce 10 million tires a year in the Soviet
Union; a plant for household electronic goods by the Merloni group;
and a chemical and agro-industrial cooperation accord with the
Montedison-Ferruzzi group.
   Italian officials said Italy will also offer its technology to
help convert Soviet military industries into civilian ones.
   In 1966, Fiat became one of the first Western groups to launch a
major venture in the Soviet Union. The Togliattigrad auto plant,
which began production of Fiat 124 models in 1970, has contributed
about half of all Soviet vehicles.
</TEXT>
