<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     11-27 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices fell in light trading
Monday on what analysts described as a technical selloff.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the January contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil,
fell 19 cents to close at $19.63 a barrel.
   Contracts between February and June finished between 18 cents
and 25 cents lower.
   Analysts said the market's weakness did not reflect events in
Vienna, Austria, where the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries is holding its semi-annual conference.
   OPEC ministers completed their third day of negotiations Monday
without reaching any conclusions on production limits, the issue
dominating the talks.
   ``We haven't heard any specific OPEC-related news and the
market's selloff didn't seem to be coordinated with news of the
adjournment,'' said Larry Lawrence, manager of options and
technical analysis for Elders Futures Inc.
   Refined oil products traded on the exchange also declined.
   Wholesale unleaded gasoline for December delivery lost 0.74 cent
to 50.89 cents a barrel, while contracts for delivery between
January and June ended 0.81 cent to 1.10 cents a gallon lower.
   No. 2 heating oil for December delivery slipped 0.49 cent to
60.92 cents a gallon, January lost 0.44 cent to 60.43 cents and
February declined 0.43 cent to 58.75 cents a gallon.
   Analysts said the sparse volume was due partly to the OPEC
meeting.
   ``People are waiting to hear,'' said Greg Dreis, energy broker
with Merrill Lynch Energy Futures. ``Once we see a decision out of
OPEC we'll see more activity.''
   OPEC ministers are trying to decide whether to devise a new plan
for allotting production shares according to each nation's ability
to pump oil or simply to continue the current quota system.
</TEXT>
