<FIRST>u f AM-AutoSales Bjt   11-27 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sales Down 4.4 Percent From Weak Period Last Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of new North American-made cars and trucks
fell 4.4 percent in mid-November from the same period last year,
automakers reported Monday in the latest indication of their
industry's weakness.
   The industry's lengthening sales slump _ which has been paced by
the Big Three of General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler
Corp. _ could mean automakers will lengthen their year-end factory
shutdowns in an attempt to trim production and deflate an inventory
backlog, analysts said.
   The eight major companies making cars and light trucks in North
America said they sold an average of 31,032 vehicles daily during
the Nov. 11-20 period, compared with a daily rate of 32,466 during
year-earlier period.
   Car sales dropped 6.1 percent while light truck sales fell 1.8
percent during the period.
   For the Big Three, overall vehicle sales were down 8.6 percent
from last year during the 10-day period.
   Through Nov. 20 of this year, car and truck sales from all
U.S.-based manufacturers were 2.6 percent behind last year's pace.
Car sales were down 3.6 percent and truck sales were off 0.8
percent during the year-to-date period
   The industry's sales slide began in early October, as automakers
ushered in the 1990 model year with higher prices.
   Analysts said Monday they expected automakers to consider
cutting production rather than piling on more rebates or other
customer incentives to help sell cars and trucks.
   ``We're at a point in the cycle where production cuts make more
sense,'' said John Kirnan of Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co. of New York. He
said automakers might look at extending holiday shutdowns to reduce
production.
   ``It would dramatize to the feds the need for lower interest
rates and to the UAW how important it is to be sane in their
demands,'' Kirnan said.
   The United Auto Workers union and the Big Three automakers open
contract talks this summer over replacing the pacts that expire at
midnight Sept. 14, 1990.
   The automakers have been wrestling with bloated inventories
since early this year, trying to shrink them with dealer and
customer incentives and short-term plant shutdowns.
   Last week, the UAW staged a large demonstration at Chrysler
headquarters to protest the company's scheduled February closing of
a Detroit assembly plant and the laying off of 1,700 employees.
   Ford said its car and truck sales pace was down 13 percent in
mid-November, with car sales off 11.6 percent and truck sales off
14.8 percent. For the year through Nov. 20, Ford's vehicle sales
were down 2.5 percent.
   Chrysler's car and truck sales pace was down 3.3 percent in
mid-November from the same time last year. A 12 percent drop in its
car sales was offset by a 6 percent increase in its light truck
sales.
   Chrysler's year-to-date car and truck sales were down 6.4
percent from last year.
   General Motors said its mid-November car sales were down 13
percent while its truck sales were up 4.1 percent, combining for a
7.3 percent decline for its vehicles during the period. For the
year, GM's car and truck sales were down 5 percent from last year.
</TEXT>
