<DOCNO> AP891127-0271 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-27-89 1726EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-IBM-Radiation     11-27 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IBM-Radiation,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Critics Say IBM's Radiation Reduction Is Halfway Measure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A move by International Business Machines Corp.
to reduce the electromagnetic radiation emitted by computer
displays does not go far enough, some critics said Monday.
   IBM was praised for taking the lead in reducing very low
frequency radiation, but several advocates of radiation reduction
said the company had neglected to do anything about the extremely
low frequency spectrum.
   ``This move of IBM's is partial at best, and I think is a public
relations stunt at worst,'' said Paul Brodeur, author of a newly
published book on electromagnetic radiation, ``Currents of Death.''
   Brodeur said the government and private industry should work
strenuously to cut electromagnetic radiation at 60 cycles a second,
the range associated with power lines. He argues it can cause
leukemia and brain cancer.
   IBM said Monday it did not do anything about the 60 hertz
radiation because customers had not asked for it. The company
argues there is no evidence that radiation from computer displays
is a health hazard. Scientific studies have been contradictory.
   ``We don't have any active work right now'' on 60 hertz
radiation, Paul Snayd, manager of IBM's VDT and Ergonomics Project
Office, said in an interview. ``We have not visited it at all.''
   IBM in September introduced a line of InfoWindow terminals for
mid-sized and mainframe computers that give off less
electromagnetic radiation in the 15 kilohertz to 17 kilohertz
range, categorized as very low frequency.
   The reduced-radiation feature of the terminals was included in
response to requests from customers in Sweden and Denmark, not
because of health concerns, IBM said. The terminals were promoted
as low-radiation in Europe but not in the United States, where
press materials made no mention of the radiation issue.
   Snayd said the radiation-reduction feature probably will be
introduced in future displays for personal computers. Some analysts
expect that to happen next year.
   No other U.S. computer makers have said they plan to follow
IBM's lead in radiation reduction.
   Brodeur faulted IBM for implying the terminals were low in
radiation when in fact they deal with only one portion of the
spectrum. But IBM's Snayd countered that the company had not billed
them as low radiation in the United States at all.
   ``When and if we do we'll be very precise about their
characteristics,'' he said.
   The Newspaper Guild union has been leading the fight for
controls on radiation from video display terminals. David Eisen,
the research and information director, praised IBM's radiation
reduction.
   ``This is certainly a salutary development, and certainly
something the unions in the United States and Canada have been
calling for for the last four years,'' Eisen said.
   But he added, ``It would be far better if they were shielding in
the (60 hertz) frequencies as well and I see no reason they should
not be shielding for both.''
   Electromagnetic radiation from computer displays is different
from and less dangerous than the ionizing radiation of gamma rays
and X-rays.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891127-0272 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-27-89 1734EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-BellSouth-Shareholders     11-27 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BellSouth-Shareholders,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>BellSouth Approves Anti-Takeover Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   BellSouth Corp. announced Monday its board of
directors had adopted a shareholder rights plan to protect the
company against the possibility of a hostile takeover.
   Company officials said the protection plan was not in response
to any attempt at an acquisition of BellSouth. The plan would take
effect if anyone acquired 10 percent of the company's stock without
management's approval.
   The move comes as BellSouth continues a bitter fight with McCaw
Cellular Communications Co. for control of the cellular telephone
properties of Lin Broadcasting Corp.
   ``This plan will help ensure that all BellSouth shareholders
realize the long-term value of their investment in the company by
requiring potential buyers to negotiate with our board first,''
said BellSouth Chairman John L. Clendenin.
   ``And the plan should provide additional protection to our
shareholders from the negative effects of abusive
share-accumulation tactics. By discouraging abusive tactics, the
plan promotes the fair and equal treatment of all shareholders,''
Clendenin said.
   Under the plan, if any person or group acquires 10 percent of
the company's stock without prior board approval, other
shareholders then would be allowed to buy BellSouth common stock at
half price _ thus diluting the holdings of the potential buyer.
   Atlanta-based BellSouth is the holding company for Southern Bell
and South Central Bell, which serve nine Southeastern states, and
has other business interests including substantial cellular phone
properties.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
