<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     11-27 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell sharply against most major
foreign currencies Monday as traders anticipated a further decline
in interest rates in the United States.
   Gold prices also were mostly lower.
   ``The psychology is definitely bearish for the dollar and
bullish for the (West German) mark,'' said Earl Johnson, a vice
president for foreign exchange at Harris Trust &amp; Co. in Chicago.
   Traders expected interest rates to fall in this country in
response to a slowing economy, and to rise in West Germany because
of the continuing political changes in Eastern Europe, Johnson said.
   A nation's currency tends to follow the direction of its
interest rates. Lower U.S. rates make the dollar less attractive,
while higher West German yields make the mark a better investment.
   The dollar's downward trend is expected to remain in place in
the next few weeks unless the Bush administration issues new
statistics indicating strength in the economy, Johnson said.
   When the economy is stronger, the Federal Reserve is more likely
to nudge interest rates higher to prevent it from overheating.
   Traders will be watching as the government issues several
economic reports this week, including third quarter gross national
product figures and personal income, construction spending and the
Index of Leading Indicators for October.
   Overseas dealers also said they expected the dollar to drop
further.
   ``As long as there aren't any major surprises from the interest
rate side, I expect the dollar to move lower under fluctuations,''
said a dealer at a Frankfurt bank.
   Late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday's
prices, included: 1.7890 West German marks, down from 1.8010;
1.6040 Swiss francs, down from 1.6095; 6.1100 French francs, down
from 6.1415; 1.16665 Canadian dollars, down from 1.6725; and
1,320.75 Italian lire, down from 1,326.75.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1.7900 West German marks, down from 1.8040; 1.6050
Swiss francs, down from 1.6145; 6.1125 French francs, down from
6.1600; 2.0203 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0340; 1,321.25 Italian
lire, down from 1,333.75; and 1.1670 Canadian dollars, up from
1.1665.
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell to a closing 143.35 Japanese yen from
143.80 yen at Friday's close. Later, in London, it rose to 143.40
yen, but in New York, it fell to 143.195 yen from late Friday's
143.60.
   The dollar gained against the British pound, as sterling fell to
$1.5605 from $1.5635 late Friday in London, and to $1.5585 from
$1.5625 late Friday in New York.
   In gold trading in New York, a troy ounce of gold fell $5 to
$413.90 on the Commodity Exchange, while Republic National Bank
quoted a late bid of $413.75 a troy ounce, up 85 cents from late
Friay.
   In earlier London trading, gold fell to a late bid price of
$414.25 a troy ounce from $416.25 bid late Friday and in Zurich,
the metal fell to a closing bid of $414 from $416.10 bid late
Friday.
   In Hong Kong, gold fell $1.12 to close at a bid $418.02.
   Silver dropped 18.4 cents on the Commodity Exchange in New York,
closing at $5.69. Earlier in London, silver fell to a late bid
price of $5.73 a troy ounce from late Friday's $5.86.
</TEXT>
