<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     11-27 0676</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0700</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Gold Prices Plunge on Profit-Taking ^By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Gold prices plummeted Monday amid heavy profit-taking by
speculators as the market broke a five-day runup that had pushed
the metal to its highest levels in almost a year.
   On other commodity markets, cotton futures plunged the permitted
daily limit; soybeans were down sharply; energy futures retreated;
and livestock and meat futures were mixed.
   Gold futures settled $5.20 to $6.10 lower on New York's
Commodity Exchange with the contract for delivery in December down
$5.20 at $414.10 a troy ounce. Silver fell 18.7 cents to 20.7 cents
with December settling at $5.693 a troy ounce.
   Monday's sell-off was the steepest daily decline in gold prices
since Aug. 4 and the most significant drop since the market began
climbing sharply about six weeks ago from levels near $360 an ounce.
   Analysts said gold had been due for a correction after climbing
so hard, so fast and many remained bullish.
   ``The trend remains intact,'' said James Steel, metals analyst
with the futures brokerage Refco Inc. in New York.
   But they said gold easily could fall a bit further before
resuming its climb, which has been based largely on investment
buying stemming from the uncertain economic outlook, the volatile
stock market and worries about the rapid rate of political change
in Eastern Europe.
   There were no solidly bearish developments Monday to prompt the
gold sell-off, so observers concluded the selling reflected
profit-taking by players who had ridden the market up since
mid-October.
   ``I don't think we're finished yet with the rally in gold or
silver,'' said Jack Barbanel, managing director of First Global
Asset Management Inc. in Princeton, N.J. ``It's healthy for the
market not to overextend itself.''
   Most cotton futures prices fell the daily limit of 2 cents a
pound on the New York Cotton Exchange in a sell-off inspired almost
entirely by technical sell signals in the absence of fresh
supply-and-demand news.
   The trigger was the March contract's drop below the September
low of 72.20 cents early in the session, said Ernest Simon, a
cotton analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   ``When it came close to it, frantic, panicky selling
developed,'' he said.
   Cotton settled 1.75 cents to 2.33 cents lower with March at
71.08 cents a pound; and the December contract, which has no limit
pending expiration, down 2.33 cents at 67.72 cents a pound.
   Grain and soybean futures finished mostly lower on the Chicago
Board of Trade, led by a steep soybean sell-off linked to slack
export demand and bearish technical signals.
   The wheat market closed narrowly mixed, with support stemming
from Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yuetter's statement that
France's sale of 1.3 million metric tons of wheat to the Soviet
Union was ``an encouraging sign'' that the Soviets were back in the
market for wheat.
   Wheat settled 1\ cents lower to { cent higher with December at
$4.06} a bushel; corn futures were 3{ cents to 4} cents lower with
December at $2.33\ a bushel; oats were 3{ cents to 4 cents lower
with December at $1.43 a bushel; soybeans were 6{ cents to 11 cents
lower with January at $5.76\ a bushel.
   Technical factors also were cited for Monday's moderate decline
in energy futures prices on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled .08 cent to .25 cent
lower with January at $19.63 a barrel; heating oil was .29 cent to
.58 cent lower with December at 60.92 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .74 cent to 1 cent lower with December at 50.89 cents
a gallon.
   Livestock and meat futures were narrowly mixed on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .17 cent lower to .05 cent higher with December
at 75.92 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .05 cent
higher with November at 83.75 cents a pound; live hogs were .60
cent lower to .03 cent higher with December at 50.90 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .22 cent lower to .35 cent higher with
February at 64.55 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
