<FIRST>r f AM-NewspaperAppointment     11-27 0149</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Newspaper Appointment,0155</SECOND>
<HEAD>New York Daily News Names Managing Editor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Matthew V. Storin, editor of the weekly Maine
Times and a former executive at newspapers in Boston and Chicago,
was named managing editor of the New York Daily News on Monday.
   Storin, 46, served as managing editor of The Boston Globe,
editor of the Chicago Sun-Times and deputy managing editor of U.S.
News &amp; World Report magazine before taking the job in Topsham,
Maine two years ago.
   Storin fills the vacancy created when Daily News Editor Jim
Willse was promoted from managing editor.
   Storin joined The Boston Globe in 1969 in its Washington bureau.
He became managing editor after stints as White House
correspondent, Asian correspondent and city editor.
   He left the Globe for U.S. News &amp; World Report in 1985 and
joined the Sun-Times as editor and senior vice president the
following year.
</TEXT>
