<FIRST>u f AM-GreatNorthern     11-27 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Great Northern,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Georgia-Pacific Seeks Vote To Oust Great Northern Board</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIRK BEVERIDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Georgia-Pacific Corp. said Monday it was
seeking to oust the board of directors of Great Northern Nekoosa
Corp., which has advised shareholders to reject Georgia-Pacific's
$3.6 billion buyout offer.
   Georgia-Pacific stated it was soliciting shareholder consents
for a special meeting at which Great Northern shareholders would
vote on whether to remove the board.
   ``It's clearly time to let Great Northern's shareholders speak
for themselves, since their board obviously does not speak for
them,'' Georgia-Pacific Chairman T. Marshall Hahn Jr. said in a
statement released through his Atlanta headquarters.
   In a separate move, Georgia-Pacific filed motions Monday in U.S.
District Court seeking to force a Great Northern shareholders
meeting to be moved up from March to within the next 30 days.
   Georgia-Pacific also sought to force Great Northern to disclose
to the Securities and Exchange Commission any steps it might be
taking to alter its financial structure and make a takeover more
difficult.
   Great Northern's board on Nov. 21 recommended that stockholders
reject Georgia-Pacific's sweetened buyout offer of $63 a share, or
about $3.6 billion total. Great Northern also had rejected
Georgia-Pacific's initial offer of $58 a share, a total of about
$3.1 billion.
   Great Northern stock rose 12{ cents to $61.62{ a share Monday on
the New York Stock Exchange. Georgia-Pacific rose 37{ cents to
$47.62{ a share.
   Great Northern, based in Norwalk, Conn., and incorporated in
Maine, has refused to negotiate with Georgia-Pacific over either
offer, calling the proposed buyout financially dangerous and
illegal under antitrust law.
   The company issued a news release from its headquarters calling
Georgia-Pacific's court motions ``entirely meritless'' and
self-serving and said it would contest them in court.
   The stepped-up attack on Great Northern came a day before Hahn
was to meet in Augusta with Gov. John R. McKernan and Attorney
General James E. Tierney.
   Maine officials have sought assurances from both companies that
the merger fight would not cost any state residents their jobs or
put valuable woodlands in the hands of developers.
   Hahn has made no promises, saying that because he does not have
access to Great Northern's inside information on its Maine
holdings, he cannot say for sure what Georgia-Pacific will do if it
wins the takeover battle.
   Georgia-Pacific's effort to have shareholders oust Great
Northern's directors is separate from the federal court action.
   Under Maine law, if at least one-third of the shareholders seek
a special meeting for voting on removal of the directors, the
meeting must be called within 60 days.
   The court papers ask that a separate shareholders meeting
already scheduled for March 20 be moved up to within the next 30
days, so shareholders can go ahead and vote on the Georgia-Pacific
offer.
   Georgia-Pacific, in asking for disclosure of any plans by Great
Northern to change its financial structure, also seeks to force
Great Northern to provide 72 hours notice before it makes such
changes.
   Georgia-Pacific's motion stated that Great Northern shareholders
could suffer irreparable harm if the court did not prevent the
company's management from taking further steps to either prevent a
takeover or restructure Great Northern.
</TEXT>
