<FIRST>u f AM-Miller&amp;Rhoads     11-27 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Miller &amp; Rhoads,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Department Store Chain To Sell All Assets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The failing Miller &amp; Rhoads department
store chain on Monday abandoned a plan to reorganize under federal
bankruptcy law and said it would seek to sell all its assets.
   The reversal came just four months after the century-old
regional department store sought Chapter 11 protection from
creditors and sought to reorganize as a smaller company.
   ``Certainly everybody in the company is disappointed,''
President John E. Stokely told a news conference at the company's
flagship store in downtown Richmond.
   Stokely said the chain filed a plan in U.S. Bankruptcy Court on
Monday that ``contemplates the sale of all assets.''
   He said the company's ``current circumstances and financial
condition led the board of directors to conclude that a
reorganization as a profitable going concern is not feasible.''
   Under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code, a company can
function under court protection while it devises a way to pay its
bills.
   Miller &amp; Rhoads had 14 stores in July when it filed for
bankruptcy court protection. Since then, the company has begun
arrangements to rid itself of six of its less profitable stores,
including one in North Carolina. The rest of its stores are in
Virginia.
   Stokely said negotiations are continuing to sell four of the
eight remaining outlets to May Department Stores Co. of St. Louis.
   Stokely said none of the sales transactions would be completed
before the end of January. The chain will operate normally through
the Christmas season, he said.
   Stokely estimated it would take four to six months to complete
the sale of all of 104-year-old Miller &amp; Rhoads assets. He said
jobs should be available to the majority of the company's
approximately 2,000 employees through the sale of the chain's
properties to other retailers.
</TEXT>
