<FIRST>r f BC-Visa-McCartney 3rdLd-Writethru f0292 11-27 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Visa-McCartney, 3rd Ld-Writethru, f0292,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>McCartney Becomes Visa Pitchman</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS penultimate graf to CORRECT name of Indianapolis site to
Market Square Arena sted Market Arena.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rock icon Paul McCartney will be getting a
little help from his friends at Visa U.S.A. during his comeback
tour.
   The credit-card giant announced Monday that it will sponsor the
1990 U.S. portion of the ex-Beatle's concerts.
   McCartney will appear in a multimillion-dollar television
campaign promoting the tour and Visa will be the only credit card
accepted for ticket purchases and stadium souvenirs.
   Although McCartney won't endorse the card directly, he becomes
the latest in a string of rock stars to be connected with
commercial products.
   The Rolling Stones' recent ``Steel Wheels'' tour had a
promotional tie-in that included sponsors such as Anheuser-Busch
Cos., and a licensed clothing line available at J.C. Penney Co.
   McCartney's tour, which also promotes the environmental group
Friends of the Earth, kicked off in September in Europe. His U.S.
outing began last week, although the portion that Visa will sponsor
starts in February and includes 12 dates in six cities.
   McCartney will play at the Palace in Auburn Hills, Mich., Feb.
1-2; Pittsburgh's Civic Arena Feb. 4-5; the Worcester (Mass.)
Spectrum Feb. 8-9; Rupp Arena in Lexington, Ky., Feb. 11-12;
Indianapolis' Market Square Arena Feb. 14-15; and Atlanta's Omni
Feb. 16-17.
   Visa, based in San Francisco, is the world's largest credit-card
company, with more than 200 million cards worldwide.
</TEXT>
