<HEAD>Planning Agency Says Japan's Economy Has Entered Fourth Year Of Expansion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's economy is beginning its fourth year of
expansion, with the current growth period expected to beat the
longest period of postwar growth in May, the Economic Planning
Agency said in a monthly economic report issued Tuesday.
   The third year of sustained economic growth was achieved in
November, the agency said. The longest spell of postwar expansion,
which took place after 1961, lasted 57 months, it said.
   Personal consumption and continuing strong capital equipment
investments by Japanese corporations are expected to continue, with
no overt concerns detected in the economic environment, it said.
   The report represents an amalgamation of previously issued
statistics regarding consumer spending, retail sales and wholesale
prices for the immediately preceding months.
</TEXT>
