<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru f0290 11-27 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0290,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Share Prices Slip</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE Nikkei, dollar.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was lower against the Japanese yen
Tuesday morning, while the key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange
fell marginally.
   The dollar, which opened at 143.33 yen, down 0.02 yen from
Monday's finish here, ended morning trading at 143.45 yen. It
ranged from 143.33 to 143.47 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 major issues lost a marginal
9.70 points, or 0.03 percent, ending the morning session at
36,871.83. The index was a 397.6-points gainer Monday, attaining a
record 36,881.53 close.
   The index was lower since the opening because market players
were afraid of a rapid rise in share prices following the hefty
gain the previous day, securities dealers said.
   Satoru Nagayoshi, a dealer with New Japan Securities Co.,
attributed the Nikkei's slight loss to technical sellings by Nomura
Securities.
   ``Trading was active,'' he said, mainly because the yen has been
stable on the foreign exchange market.
   Meanwhile, in exchange dealings, the dollar-yen rate moved
narrowly as market players stepped to the sidelines after a similar
wait-and-see mood in New York, said a trader with the Bank of Tokyo.
   The yen remained higher against the dollar as participants
bought it by selling the West German mark for profit-taking, he
said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The mark has been stronger than almost any other major currency
after the recent reforms in Eastern Europe.
   Since many market players, who expect West Germany will be the
major beneficiary of the movements in Eastern Europe, still have a
large demand for the West German currency, technical selling of the
mark against the yen in Tokyo ``will last only temporarily,'' said
the Bank of Tokyo trader.
   Bank of Japan Governor Satoshi Sumita said Tuesday that the
central bank will conduct concerted intervention if the market
continues to fluctuate excessively, Kyodo News Service reported.
</TEXT>
